<SLUG> BC-Australia-Election-One Nation Victim </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
One Nation's only victim may be Asian-Australian politician
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Australia-Election &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) _ Australia's sole member of Parliament
of Asian heritage may be the only politician to be ousted by the
right-wing One Nation party, which is critical of Asian immigration
levels, a member of the government said Sunday.
	   Hopes were fading that Bill O'Chee, a member of the junior
ruling coalition partner the National Party in Queensland state,
would hold his seat in the upper house Senate, colleague Ron
Boswell said.
	   One Nation's Heather Hill appeared likely to take a place as a
Senator for Queensland, pushing out O'Chee, according to the latest
computer analysis of voting trends by the Australian Broadcasting
Corp.
	   Hill is the only One Nation candidate to still have any chance
of election in Saturday's national poll. All other candidates were
unsuccessful, including party leader Pauline Hanson.
	   ``It appears that he (O'Chee) may be the only victim of One
Nation,'' Boswell told ABC radio.
	   ``The only Asian person in Parliament and it will be a great
loss to the Asian community and be a great loss to us,'' Boswell
said.
	   O'Chee was born in Australia to a Chinese-born father and
Irish-born mother.
	   Hanson has been a controversial force in Australian politics for
the past two years after claiming Australia was in danger of being
``swamped by Asians'' and claiming Aborigines are a privileged
minority. 	   
</TEXT>
