<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Reports: Malaysia's Anwar admitted to hospital
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Malaysia's ousted deputy prime
minister Anwar Ibrahim was admitted to a hospital for a medical
check-up over alleged beatings while in police custody, news
reports said Sunday.
	   Anwar, 51, entered the government-owned Universiti Hospital
under tight security Saturday. Police sealed off the first floor
where he was to be treated, barring visitors, including his wife
and children, the Star newspaper reported.
	   Hospital officials could not be immediately contacted Sunday.
Anwar's lawyers said they did not know how long he would remain in
the hospital but that he was expected to appear Monday in High
Court when a trial date will be set.
	   The former heir apparent to Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad
appeared twice in court last week, pleading innocent to 5 counts of
corruption and 5 of illegal homosexual acts.
	   Anwar sported a black eye and bruises on his neck and arm, which
he alleged came from police punches and slaps that left him bloody
and unconscious the night of his arrest, Sept. 20.
	   An eye surgeon who examined Anwar last week determined the
dissident politician had been ``assaulted'' but the injuries had
not caused permanent eye damage. The court granted Anwar's request
for further medical attention after he complained of neck and back
pain.
	   At the hospital, Anwar was expected to undergo a series of
X-rays on his backbone and his bruised left eye, among other
checks. He was admitted to the orthopedic department upon arrival.
	   Health Minister Chua Jui Meng said doctors would submit a report
of their findings to the court. No deadline has been set.
	   Anwar was arrested under the draconian Internal Security Act,
which allows jail without trial, after leading thousands in a
protest against Mahathir.
	   Mahathir, who has ruled for 17 years, initially suggested that
his former protege had inflicted the bruises on himself to win
public sympathy. But as global condemnation grew, Mahathir ordered
an independent investigation.
	   The United States, Australia, Canada, Indonesia and United
Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan, among others, have voiced
concern over Anwar's case and allegations of police brutality.
	   Deputy Inspector General of Police Norian Mai was quoted in
Sunday papers as saying he expected the investigation to be
completed soon.
	   Mahathir sacked Anwar on Sept. 2 from his posts as deputy prime
minister and finance minister, saying he was morally unfit for
office. The two had clashed over economic policy as Malaysia sank
into recession. 	   
</TEXT>
