<SLUG> BC-Sports-RugbyU-Rush Charged </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former test player charged in accident
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) _ Police have laid five careless and
dangerous driving charges against former New Zealand test and
sevens rugby union player Eric Rush following a fatal car crash.
	   Brendon Malcolm, a 23-year-old kiwifruit worker, died, his wife
Claire broke her collarbone and hand, and their friend Bryce Casey
received head injuries after their car and the car Rush was driving
collided at Mangatawhiri, south of Auckland, on Aug. 10.
	   Sgt. Bruce Pryor of Pukekohe police said Rush had been charged
with careless use of a motor vehicle causing the death of Malcolm
and two charges of careless driving causing injury to Mrs. Malcolm
and Casey. He also faces two charges of driving in a dangerous
manner.
	   Rush broke his hand and received rib and sternum injuries. He
had been training with the national sevens squad in Rotorua and was
driving alone to Auckland in a car allocated to fellow squad member
Glen Osborne.
	   The first New Zealand sevens player to receive a Commonwealth
Games gold medal, Rush, 33, last month dedicated his gold medal to
Malcolm.
	   While in Kuala Lumpur, he said he had pulled out of a lucrative
contract to play rugby in France next year for a variety of
reasons, including ``some legal stuff.''
	   Rush, a solicitor, will appear in Pukekohe District Court on
Tuesday. (djp)
</TEXT>
