w1435 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cambodia-Press     10-04 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Press </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cambodian newspaper says government to shut down foreign press
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Cambodia's government plans to shut
down two English-language newspapers and temporarily expel British
and American journalists from the country, a pro-government
newspaper reported Sunday.
	   The Cambodia Daily and the Phnom Penh Post, widely seen as the
country's only independent newspapers, have committed ``serious
professional mistakes'' and will be temporarily shut down, the
Cambodian-language Rasmei Kampuchea (Light of Cambodia) reported,
citing government spokesman Khieu Kanharith.
	   The correspondent for a German press agency was also heavily
criticized in the front-page article. Khieu Kanharith accused
Deutsche Presse-Agentur and The Cambodia Daily of biased coverage
of an alleged assassination attempt against the country's leader
Hun Sen.
	   The bimonthly Phnom Penh Post was described as ``a publication
that has always been against the Royal Government.''
	   Rasmei Kampuchea also quoted the government spokesman as saying
all American and British journalists will be temporarily expelled
from Cambodia because their personal security could not be
guaranteed if the U.S. House of Representatives passes a resolution
condemning Hun Sen.
	   Khieu Kanharith could not be reached for comment Sunday, but the
information ministry confirmed it was seeking action against the
foreign press.
	   The newspaper report comes as Hun Sen's ruling Cambodian
People's Party and the two-party opposition are negotiating to form
a government following July 26 national elections.
	   Hun Sen's party won a slight majority in the vote, claiming 64
of 122 seats in the National Assembly, but not the two-thirds
necessary to form a government alone.
	   A remote-launched rocket-propelled grenade exploded near Hun
Sen's convoy on his way to the opening of parliament on Sept. 24.
He escaped injury, but a 12-year-old boy who was sitting on the
side of the road was killed.
	   Hun Sen _ who has on at least four occasions claimed to be the
victim of an assassination attempt _ immediately accused the
opposition of being behind the failed plot.
	   Hun Sen has faced severe criticism by a U.S. congressman from a
district in California with a large ethnic Cambodian community.
	   Representative Dana Rohrabacher (R-Calif.) has urged the House
to pass a resolution calling for Hun Sen to be tried for genocide
and war crimes in an international court.
	   Rohrabacher's office said Friday that the House International
Relations Committee unanimously passed a Rohrabacher resolution
calling for an investigation of Hun Sen for ``possible criminal
culpability for conceiving, directing and sustaining a variety of
actions in violation of international humanitarian law.''
	   Khieu Kanharith was quoted in Sunday's Rasmei Kampuchea as
saying the news from Washington could put American and British
journalists in danger and that they should be forced to leave the
country for their own safety.
	   Hun Sen was a young field commander in the army of the Khmer
Rouge during the brutal communist guerrilla group's 1975-79 rule of
Cambodia.
	   More than 1 million people died from starvation, disease and
execution when the Khmer Rouge were in power. However, historians
and researchers say there is no evidence that Hun Sen was
responsible for any mass killings.
	   Hun Sen defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1977 and fled to
Vietnam. There he became part of the nucleus of Cambodian
communists installed in Phnom Penh after the Vietnamese expelled
the Khmer Rouge from power in 1979. 	   
</TEXT>
