<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Malaysia's Anwar leaves hospital
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Anwar leaving hospital. REMOVES attribution;
AMENDS overline &QL; 
 &UR; By JOCELYN GECKER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Former deputy prime minister Anwar
Ibrahim left a hospital Sunday after overnight medical check-ups of
injuries he received during police custody.
	   A police motorcade whisked Anwar, seated in the back of a jeep
with tinted windows, away from the government-owned University
Hospital, where he had been admitted late Saturday.
	   Anwar's lawyers said they did not know where he was being taken.
They had been denied access to their client since his last court
appearance Wednesday. Hospital officials refused to comment on
Anwar's condition.
	   The former heir apparent to Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad
appeared twice in Sessions Court last week, pleading innocent to
five counts of corruption and five of illegal homosexual acts.
	   He alleged that his black eye and bruises on his neck and arm
came from police punches and slaps that left him bloody and
unconscious the night of his arrest, Sept. 20.
	   Anwar was scheduled to be rearraigned Monday in High Court. Then
a trial date will be set.
	   An eye surgeon who examined Anwar last week determined the
jailed politician had been ``assaulted'' but the injuries had not
caused permanent eye damage. The court granted Anwar's request for
further medical attention after he complained of neck and back
pain.
	   At the hospital, Anwar was believed to have undergone checks
including X-rays on his backbone and his bruised left eye. He was
admitted to the orthopedic department upon arrival.
	   Health Minister Chua Jui Meng said the doctors would submit a
report of their findings to the court. No deadline has been set.
	   Police stood guard within and outside the hospital, using a
wooden barricade to seal off entry to the first floor where Anwar
was being treated. Police blocked stairwell entrances and barred
visitors, including Anwar's wife and children.
	   After leading thousands in protests against Mahathir's 17-year
rule, Anwar was arrested under the Internal Security Act, which
allows indefinite detention without charge.
	   Mahathir initially suggested that his former protege had
inflicted the bruises on himself to win public sympathy. But as
global condemnation grew, Mahathir ordered an independent
investigation.
	   The United States, Australia, Canada, Indonesia, World Bank
President James Wolfensohn and the United Nations Secretary General
Kofi Annan, among others, have voiced concern over Anwar's case and
allegations of police brutality.
	   Deputy Inspector General of Police Norian Mai was quoted in
Sunday papers as saying he expected the investigation to be
completed soon.
	   Mahathir sacked Anwar on Sept. 2 from his posts as deputy prime
minister and finance minister, saying he was morally unfit for
office. The two had clashed over economic policy as Malaysia sank
into recession. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
