<HEADLINE>
Georgian president calls for resolution to Russia's economic
</HEADLINE>
crisis &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TBILISI, Georgia (AP) _ Georgian president Eduard Shevardnadze
called for Russia to stay on the track of ``democratic
development'' and find a resolution to its economic crisis, news
reports said Sunday.
	   Shevardnaze, who met Saturday with Gennady Seleznyov, the
speaker of Russia's lower house of parliament, is eager for
``political and economic stability of (Georgia's) great neighbor
Russia, as well as its democratic development,'' according to the
reports.
	   Georgia, still embroiled in political and economic instability
after the fall of the Soviet Union, has been hit hard by
aftershocks from Russia's latest financial trouble.
	   Shevardnaze and Seleznyov also discussed the conflict in
Georgia's breakaway Abkhazia region, as well as the Russian
parliament's continuing refusal to ratify a friendship treaty
signed by Shevardnadze and Russian President Boris Yeltsin in 1993.
	   Seleznyov said ``not everything is all right in the ratification
issue,'' but did not go into details.
	   Despite tensions over the treaty, there are ``no unresolved
issues in Georgian-Russian relations,'' Seleznyov said.
	   (nw/ren)
