<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Satellite </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia marks 41st anniversary of first satellite in space
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia marked the 41st anniversary Sunday of the
launch of the Sputnik satellite - the first manmade object sent
into Earth's orbit.
	   Sputnik, launched on Oct. 4, 1957, was a crude satellite. The
size of a beach ball, it went around and around the earth, sending
``beep, beep'' signals by radio.
	   But the little satellite, the first manmade object to orbit the
Earth, profoundly changed human history. Then, at the height of the
Cold War, the space race was on, and the Soviet Union and the
United States were committed to spending whatever it took to gain
dominance in space.
	   The anniversary, marked by meetings at space and scientific
institutes, is also a reminder of Russia's present space troubles.
	   Russia's Mir space station will be ditched sometime next year
because of funding shortages, and an international space station
has been delayed because of Russia's inability to fund a key
component.
	   (nw/ren)
</TEXT>
