<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinians </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
More West Bank clashes Sunday on eve of Jewish holiday
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By NASSER SHIYOUKHI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HEBRON, West Bank (AP) _ Stone-throwing clashes broke out Sunday
at an Israeli checkpoint outside the tense West Bank town of
Hebron, but no injuries were immediately reported.
	   It marked the fifth straight day of skirmishes in and around
Hebron, which is home to 450 Jewish settlers and 130,000
Palestinians and a frequent flashpoint for violence.
	   Sunday's fighting broke out at the Halhul checkpoint outside
Hebron, where Israeli troops were refusing to let anyone pass. A
crowd of about 100 Palestinians gathered, and some began throwing
stones and bottles at the soldiers.
	   The troops responded with rubber bullets and tear gas, but
witnesses said no one was hurt.
	   The closure of the West Bank and Gaza Strip, with some easings,
has been in effect since just before the Sept. 20 New Year holiday.
	   Army radio said it was expected to continue through the weeklong
Jewish festival of Sukkot, which was beginning at sundown Sunday.
	   Palestinians complain bitterly about closures, which prevent
tens of thousands of workers from getting to jobs in Israel and
cost the Palestinian economy millions in lost wages and commercial
trade.
	   In sealing off the Palestinian lands, Israel cited threats from
the Islamic militant group Hamas, which has killed scores of
Israelis in suicide bombings since 1994. Hamas vowed to carry out
attacks after Israeli soldiers killed two wanted fugitives from the
group last month.
	   Israel radio quoted defense officials as saying potential terror
targets include airports, border crossings, beaches, and sites
abroad associated with Israel or Judaism.
	   Also Sunday, the two sides were working to lay groundwork for a
visit by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who is due to
arrive Tuesday. Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat was holding
talks with Israel's Cabinet secretary Danny Naveh.
	   Albright's visit is meant to prepare for an Israeli-Palestinian
summit in Washington on Oct. 15-19. The Clinton administration has
been trying to get the two sides to agree to terms for an Israeli
pullback in the West Bank.
	   Erekat has said the United States was trying to coax a pledge
from Israel to ease settlement activity in exchange for assurances
from the Palestinians that they will not encourage illegal
construction.
	   Israel has repeatedly accused the Palestinians of not doing
enough to crack down on Hamas and other militants.
 &UR; (ns-lk)
</TEXT>
