<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Election, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Australian government claims mandate despite narrow re-election
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with quotes from Howard, adds photo numbers. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos SYD101-102 &QL; 
 &UR; By ROHAN SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ After a narrow re-election victory,
conservative Prime Minister John Howard on Sunday claimed a mandate
for his key economic plans of tax reform and sale of the national
telephone company.
	   But Howard's ability to push through the reforms remained in
doubt as minor and opposition parties _ who may have a majority in
Parliament's upper house _ claimed the huge loss of support for the
government showed people did not want his plans implemented.
	   With close to 80 percent of the vote counted, Howard's
conservatives came in with what the Australian Broadcasting Corp.
predicted will be a majority of seven seats in the lower house, a
loss of at least 20 of their previous 41-seat majority.
	   Lynton Crosby, director of Howard's Liberal party, said he
expected the government to end up with a majority of up to a dozen
seats, but even the slimmest majority gave Howard a mandate.
	   ``We will have a majority of representatives in the Parliament,
that's what counts. That gives us the authority and the opportunity
to pursue our plans,'' Crosby said.
	   But the main opposition Labor Party said the huge erosion of
support for the government denied Howard a mandate to introduce his
planned tax on all goods and services or sell the government's
remaining stake in telecommunications company Telstra Corp.
	   The minority Democrats party said it was on track to win five
additional seats in the Senate, enough to win the balance of power.
Leader Meg Lees has said the party would block the sale of Telstra
and will change Howard's tax package to exempt food.
	   Howard told reporters his victory was an endorsement of his
reform plans, which he would ask both houses of Parliament to
endorse at the at the first opportunity.
	   Howard claimed victory late Saturday at a rally of cheering
supporters in Sydney.
	   ``I want first and foremost to thank the Australian people for
returning the government. I want to thank the Australian people for
embracing a bold economic reform that is in the long-term interest
of the Australian community,'' Howard said.
	   The win will see Howard in office to preside over the Sydney
2000 Olympics, the centenary of Australia's federation as a nation
in 2001, and the country's entry into the new millennium.
	   Needing to win 27 extra electorates to win government, the Labor
Party led by Kim Beazley cut deep into Howard's parliamentary
majority, but not enough to win.
	   ``I'm proud to say the Labor Party is back in town. We approach
the next three years with great confidence,'' said Beazley in
conceding.
	   The conservatives also held off a strong challenge from the far
right-wing One Nation party, which attracted about 8 percent of the
national vote.
	   One Nation leader Pauline Hanson, who exploded onto the
political scene about 18 months ago with proposals to freeze Asian
immigration and cut welfare programs for Aborigines, appeared not
to have been re-elected, calling into question the party's
viability.
	   About 12 million registered voters cast their ballots Saturday
at thousands of polling booths in public buildings, from the
nation's desert Outback to its tropical north and in its bustling
cities in the southeast.
	   Howard staked his government's fate on reforms to simplify an
antiquated tax structure that has been built up since the
Depression era of the 1930s, with the goods and services tax as the
centerpiece. Voters rejected a similar plan at a 1993 election.
	   Howard offered income tax cuts worth Australian dollars 13
billion (U.S. dlrs 7.6 billion) to soften the blow of the new tax. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Australia-Election, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
