<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Pakistan-Australia,0232 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Victory very close for Australia
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RIZWAN ALI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   RAWALPINDI, Pakistan (AP) _ Pakistan lost three wickets in just
seven deliveries by lunch on Sunday as Australia moved closer
toward winning the first Test against Pakistan.
	   Pakistan which conceded a heavy 244-run first innings lead, were
reeling at 55 for four with Salim Malik (9 not out) and Moin Khan
(12 not out) fighting a grim battle.
	   Australia amassed a massive 513 in its first innings in reply to
Pakistan's 269 runs before its innings folded in the last over of
Saturday.
	   Skipper Aamir Sohail and Saeed Anwar were off to a cautious
start under overcast conditions, adding 24 runs in the first hour.
However, once McGrath changed his ends and bowled into the strong
breeze, Sohail played on to his stumps after scoring 13 runs.
	   Damien Fleming in his fourth over of the day ignited Pakistan's
collapse. He trapped Muhammad Wasim and Inzamamul Haq leg before
and both batsmen were out for a duck. From 32 for three, Pakistan
was further reduced to 32 for four when Colin Miller got a lucky
decision off Saeed Anwar from English umpire Peter Willey as the
batsmen struck on the front pad while stretching long way forward.
	   Fleming had taken two for 26 while McGrath and Miller had one
wicket each for 14 and 12 runs respectively. 	   
</TEXT>
