<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-India-diplomats,0253 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pakistan-India expel diplomats ahead of talks on disputed Kashmir
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ Pakistan and India expelled each
others' diplomats on espionage charges just two weeks before
``confidence-building talks,'' a private news agency reported
Sunday.
	   The expulsions also were reported in Pakistani newspapers but no
official confirmation was available from either country.
	   The News Network International, quoting unnamed diplomatic
sources, said India expelled a Pakistani diplomat on Tuesday for
spying. The name of the Pakistani official was not available.
	   Pakistan's foreign ministry spokesman Tariq Altaf neither
confirmed nor denied the report saying ``I will check the report
... (but) such things do happen in view of the state of relations
between the two countries.''
	   In India, foreign ministry spokesman K.C. Singh also refused to
either confirm or deny the expulsions.
	   The foreign secretaries of the two countries are scheduled to
meet in Islamabad on Oct. 15 to resume stalled talks on the
disputed Himalayan region of Kashmir. India and Pakistan have
fought two wars over the province since independence in 1947.
	   Both countries hold parts of Kashmir and lay claim on the rest.
Kashmir is the only Muslim majority state in the Hindu-dominated
India.
	   Tensions in South Asia have escalated after India conducted a
series of nuclear tests in May, which was matched with similar
series of tests by Pakistan the same month. 	   
</TEXT>
