<SLUG> BC-Iran-Afghanistan </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Paper: 4 Afghans accused of spying arrested in Iran
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ Iran has arrested four Afghan men who
allegedly were spying for the Taliban militia in the southeastern
province of Sistan-Baluchestan, the Asr-e-Azadegan newspaper
reported Sunday.
	   The men were sent to Iran ``to carry out acts of sabotage,'' the
independent Farsi-language paper said, quoting unnamed Iranian
officials.
	   It gave no other details.
	   An estimated 200,000 Iranian troops currently are carrying out
ground and air maneuvers over a 50,000-square-kilometer
(20,000-square-mile) area along Iran's border with Afghanistan and
Pakistan.
	   The maneuvers in the Sistan-Baluchestan and Khorasan provinces
mark the deepening tension between Iran and the Taliban.
	   Taliban fighters killed eight Iranian diplomats and an Iranian
journalist after the Aug. 8 capture of the northern Afghan city of
Mazar-e-Sharif.
	   The Taliban, which rule about 90 percent of Afghanistan, said
renegade fighters killed the Iranians. But Taliban leaders have
refused Iranian demands that the killers be handed over.
	   The Taliban, in turn, have accused Iran of backing Afghanistan's
northern-based opposition alliance.
	   Taliban leaders say they have moved 20,000 troops to the border
in response to Iran's war games.
