<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Police </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police to be separated from armed forces beginning April
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Indonesia's police force will be
gradually separated from the military and placed under civilian
control beginning next year, armed forces commander Gen. Wiranto
announced Sunday.
	   Now, the police are part of the military, known as ABRI, along
with the army, navy and air force.
	   Since the resignation of autocratic President Suharto last May
that followed riots and protests, calls have been growing for their
separation.
	   The change will be a basic reform for the armed forces.
Indonesia's military has been accused of human rights abuses during
Suharto's 32-year rule.
	   The change will come into effect ahead of general elections set
for May next year. The government says the poll will be conducted
freely and democratically after decades of tightly controlled
politics under Suharto.
	   The police are expected to play a major role in crowd control
and other security matters during the campaign and balloting.
	   News reports on Sunday said supervision of the police would be
transferred initially from the military to the defense ministry.
Wiranto as armed forces chief and defense minister heads both.
	   The Jakarta Post said an evaluation would be conducted within
six months to assess whether the police should eventually be placed
under the control of the home affairs ministry or directly under
the president.
	   Wiranto told reporters that the duties and functions of the
police should be tied to a civilian government rather than the
armed forces.
	   On another matter, Wiranto said Indonesia's economic crisis has
forced the military to scale down its annual celebrations for
national armed forces day Monday.
	   He said the traditional parade had been canceled.
	   Instead, President B.J. President is scheduled to attend a
ceremony that for the first time will be held at the military's
headquarters at Cilangkap in Jakarta's eastern outskirts.
	   Normally the ceremony, which commemorates the founding of the
military in the fight against Dutch colonizers after World War II,
is staged in the center of Jakarta. 	   
</TEXT>
