<SLUG> BC-Russia-Chechen Hostages, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chechen gunmen take four British hostages
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS kidnapping Saturday not Sunday, ADDS locator in 2nd
graf, details in 4th graf.

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Unknown gunmen took four British hostages in
Russia's breakaway Chechnya region after a shootout with their
bodyguards, a news agency reported Sunday.
	   The four British citizens, who were in Chechnya to install a
cellular phone system, were taken hostage Saturday after 20 men in
camouflage attacked the house where they lived in the Chechen
capital of Grozny, the Interfax news agency said.
	   One bodyguard and an unknown number of attackers were wounded in
the firefight, Interfax said. Police are searching regional
hospitals for anyone coming in with gunshot wounds.
	   The kidnapping took place only 500 meters (550 yards) from the
regional government's department to fight kidnapping, Interfax
said. Policemen heard the shots, but didn't react because gunfire
is frequent in the evening in Grozny, the report said.
	   The British embassy in Moscow would not comment on the report.
	   The kidnapping comes just weeks after Chechen warlords released
two British charity workers, ending 14 months of captivity in the
turbulent republic in Russia's northern Caucasus region.
	   Hundreds of Russian and foreign citizens have been abducted by
gangs seeking ransom since the 1994-1996 independence war with
Russia, and dozens remain held.
	   Chechnya's President Aslan Maskhadov's government has been
unable to stem kidnappings that have become a steady business for
some criminal gangs.
	   Chechnya considers itself independent and has been running its
own affairs since Russian troops left two years ago. Moscow says
that Chechnya remains part of Russia but has no control over its
affairs.
	   (nw/ren)
</TEXT>
