<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Scandal </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Top aide to Taipei mayor resigns over hostess bar visits
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ The Taipei mayor's top aide stepped down
Sunday from his re-election campaign after he was found to have
frequented hostess bars.
	   The resignation of Ma Yung-cheng, formerly the city government's
spokesman, deprives mayor Chen Shui-bian of a key adviser in a
difficult campaign.
	   Chen is trying to defend the opposition stronghold against
popular former justice minister Ma Ying-jeou of the ruling
Nationalist Party.
	   The bar visits, which were disclosed by a defector from the city
government, were particularly damaging because Chen has made
hostess clubs a key target of his campaign to rein in Taipei's
flamboyant night life and crack down on gangs.
	   Ma, the adviser, acknowledged he was a customer of two Taipei
hostess clubs, where young women accompany clients in drinking and
singing, but he described the visits as a ``personal defect.''
	   ``My visits over two years ago had nothing to do with city
government business, though I'm not trying to rationalize my
behavior,'' Ma told a news conference and bowed in apology.
	   But Ma said at least one visit to a club was made at the
invitation of city council deputies and accused them of being
hypocrites.
	   ``Here we see those who used to invite me to clubs, who might be
called frequent customers of clubs, suddenly turning themselves
into paragons of morality and accusing me,'' Ma said.
	   The council members demanded he produce evidence.
	   Ma was one of two young advisers who helped engineer Chen's
ground-breaking victory in 1994 elections that snatched the
mayorship of Taiwan's capital away from the Nationalists.
	   His reputation as a sharp-tongued playboy forced him into less
public roles in Chen's administration, though he had recently
resigned from the city government to work for the campaign full
time.
	   Chen's other adviser, Luo Wen-jia, was forced to resign from the
city government after several people were injured during a
promotional tug of war he organized.
	   Luo recently returned from study in the United States to serve
as executive director of Chen's campaign.
	   Chen's opponent Ma is known for his incorruptibility and
efficiency, and the two are running neck and neck despite the
mayor's high approval ratings.
	   The election, coinciding with polls for the legislature and
mayor of Taipei's second largest city, Kaohsiung, is set for Dec.
5.
</TEXT>
