<SLUG> BC-Sports-Motorcycle Racing-Australian Grand Prix, 1st Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Writethru
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Doohan wins fifth consecutive title &QL; 
 &UR; EDs: updates with quotes, new material throughout &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PHILLIP ISLAND, Australia (AP) _ Michael Doohan conquered his
home course Sunday to win the Australian Grand Prix and clinch his
fifth consecutive 500 c.c. world motorcycle championship.
	   Tens of thousands of fans swamped the Australian after he
flashed past the checkered flag. Holding high an Australian flag
with the figure `5' on it, Doohan weaved through a sea of bodies
forming a guard of honor the entire length of the circuit.
	   ``To actually win the championship here is something I could
never have dreamed of,'' Doohan said.
	   ``To have an Australian crowned world champion in Australia is
fantastic _ I hope everyone else is enjoying it.''
	   As soon as he appeared at his post-race press conference, Doohan
confirmed that he and Honda had agreed to try for a sixth world
title next year.
	   Roaring away from pole position Sunday _ his 57th career pole _
Doohan relegated his rivals to a race amongst themselves for the
minor placings.
	   This time there would be no mistake as he zeroed in on win No.
53 ahead of New Zealander Simon Crafar and Honda teammate Alex
Criville of Spain.
	   Doohan said that despite breaking out to a five-second lead over
the pack, he had to stare down a mental hurdle approaching lap 17.
	   It was on that lap last year that the Australian lost
concentration for a split second and slid out of the race.
	   ``The big thing here for me was lap 17, so when I got past lap
17 it was pretty much maintenance control after that,'' Doohan
said.
	   ``When there were four or five laps to go and I had a
five-second lead I thought `Just bring the thing home'.''
	   Only minutes before the start of the race, there were nervous
thoughts that he might have to pull out as his crew struggled with
a mechanical problem.
	   ``When I left pit lane for my sighting lap things weren't all
that good, it was missing and running on only three of the four
cylinders,'' Doohan said.
	   ``But the team did a great job to get it running again.''
	   Doohan opened up a lead of 1.9 seconds after just one lap,
surprising even himself with an uncharacteristically fast start.
	   Tire wear remained a concern and despite maintaining a healthy
break he said if he had forced the pace further his tires would not
have lasted the distance.
	   Doohan won the 27-lap race in a time of 42 minutes, 42.511
seconds, slowing to beat Crafar by .8 seconds. Crafar set the
fastest lap time and a circuit record of 1:33.868. (djp) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
