<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Romania-Hungarians </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ethnic Hungarians to remain in Romanian government
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TARGU MURES, Romania (AP) _ The Hungarian minority party has
decided to remain in the Romanian government, saying it does not
want to be blamed for the failure of Romania's limping reforms,
radio reported Sunday.
	   Last month, the party which represents the interests of the 1.7
million Hungarian minority said it would withdraw from the Romanian
government over the failure to establish a Hungarian state
university that the government promised but was later blocked by
Parliament.
	   The government on Wednesday said it was prepared to set up a
Hungarian-German university called Petofi-Schiller, which appeased
some Hungarians and was widely attacked by Romanian politicians.
	   After a stormy 12-hour debate in this Transylvanian city, ethnic
Hungarians voted by 59-37 late Saturday to stay in the cabinet and
four-party ruling coalition, regional radio reported Sunday in the
city some 250 kilometers (156 miles) northwest of the capital.
	   ``We cannot allow ourselves to let them (Romanians) blame us for
the failure of reforms,'' said Bela Marko, head of the Democratic
Union of Hungarians in Romania, after the vote.
	   Romania is struggling to implement market and democratic
reforms, but the process is slowed by political bickering in the
coalition. Investors say bureaucracy and corruption discourage
business and have contributed to a recession.
	   Romanians are opposed to a state Hungarian university, citing
bitter historical disputes between Romania and Hungary. They claim
European norms do not require the Hungarians to have their own
state university.
	   The few thousand Germans who live in Romania said they do not
need a state university and some Romanian politicians say the
university is bound to become a Hungarian one
	   Most ethnic Hungarians live in the northwestern region of
Transylvania, which was under the Austro-Hungarian empire until
1918 and has changed hands several times over the centuries.
	   Relations between the two countries improved in 1996 when they
signed a bilateral treaty. Hungarians joined the coalition
government when reformist parties were elected in November 1996.
	   (str/am/dc)
</TEXT>
