<SLUG> BC-Sports-Auto Racing-Bathurst 1,000, 1st Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Richards, Rydell combine for win
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDs: corrects Richards as a New Zealander in 1st graf, changes
headline &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BATHURST, Australia (AP) _ Australian-based New Zealander Jim
Richards won his sixth Bathurst 1,000-kilometer touring car race
Sunday, teaming with Swedish driver Rickard Rydell to give Volvo
its first win at Mt. Panorama.
	   Richards shared a Volvo S40 with British touring car champion
Rydell in a race-long duel with the Nissan Primera of Richards' son
Steven and Englishman Matt Neal.
	   The Nissan finished two seconds behind while third place went to
the Audi of Australian two-liter touring car champion Brad Jones
and Cameron McConville.
	   Jim Richards started from pole position but Steven grabbed the
lead on the first run up Mt. Panorama and stayed in front until the
first fuel stop, then for a brief time before the last stop.
	   Five pace-car periods, two in the last hour, kept the top three
in touch.
	   The Vectra of Greg Murphy and Russel Ingall led briefly and was
third for much of the time before crashing on lap 84, one of three
victims of oil and debris from a crashed car.
	   Sunday's race was the second staged for two-liter cars since the
split between race organizers and the more popular V8 Holdens and
Fords.
	   The crowd was again sparse compared with those attracted by the
larger cars which will have their own 1,000-kilometer Bathurst race
in November. (djp)
