<HEADLINE>
Precede ZAGREB
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Pope John Paul II holds Mass in Split after beatifying WW II
cardinal
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with pope's arrival in Split; CHANGES byline,
dateline. Mass scheduled to begin at 0845 GMT. Picks up 4th graf
pvs &QL; 
 &UR; By VICTOR L. SIMPSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SPLIT, Croatia (AP) _ A huge throng of people waved flowers and
small Vatican flags Sunday to welcome Pope John Paul II to this
centuries-old southern coastal town on the last day of his visit to
Croatia.
	   The city was draped in the Vatican's traditional yellow and
white in preparation for an outdoor Mass that the pope was to hold
later. Hundreds of thousands of people arrived from across the
country as well as from neighboring Bosnia and Montenegro, which
together with Serbia comprises Yugoslavia.
	   On Saturday evening, the border crossing between Croatia and
Montenegro was opened for the first time since the 1991 Serbo-Croat
war, allowing Croats from Montenegro to attend the Mass.
	   The Mass was to be held on a broad plateau overlooking the
Adriatic Sea, and many pilgrims were headed to the Mass from their
boats, anchored along the coast.
	   Some 80, 4th graf pvs
