w1544 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Golf-JapanOpen     10-04 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Japan Open </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tanaka wins his first Japan Open crown
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HIGASHI-IBARAKI, Japan (AP) _ Hidemichi Tanaka shot a
3-under-par 69 Sunday and won the Japan Open crown by one stroke
over Naomichi ``Joe'' Ozaki, a regular on the U.S. tour.
	   The 5-foot-7 (1.65-meter) Tanaka, renowned as a miniature John
Daly with a 300-yard (270-meter) drive, surged ahead of overnight
leader Ozaki with a round of five birdies and two bogeys for a
total of 5-under 283.
	   Joe, the youngest of three Ozaki brothers on the Japan tour,
shot a 1-over-par 73 with a sole birdie against two bogeys en route
to a 4-under 284 total over the par-72 Oarai Golf Club course. He
had led Tanaka by three strokes overnight.
	   Only two others finished with under-par totals over the windy
7,160-yard (6,516-meter) course, also known for its narrow fairways
studded with pine trees and punitive rough.
	   It wasn't an easy victory for Tanaka, whose most scary moments
came on the par-4, 435-yard (396-meter) final hole. After hitting
his drive right and deep into the trees, the 27-year-old in his
seventh year of career needed two shots to come out of the woods
with the first hitting a tree trunk and recoiling backward.
	   However, Tanaka avoided disaster with his sensational second
shot, clearing through a gap in the trees half the size of a coffee
table and flying 180 yards (165 meters) to the green. He then
two-putted from 35 feet (10 meters) for bogey and for the victory.
	   ``When I bogeyed the 16th after hitting my approach too short, I
knew I was under the pressure of the Japan Open crown,'' said
Tanaka who has been in a slump due to a back trouble since winning
his second career tournament in 1996.
	   ``When I drove into the trees at the final hole, I again
realized that I was off a little because of the tournament being
the Japan Open,'' Tanaka added. ``For me, this victory is
dreamlike, so is the fact that I could manage to get away with the
bogey on the final hole.''
	   Joe Ozaki, the top money-winner of the 1991 season, said his
final round ended before being able to pick up momentum.
	   ``I had a few birdie chances today, but the way I was putting
made it a very long day,'' he said.
	   Ozaki, who has played mostly on the U.S. PGA Tour since 1993,
was seeking his 26th title on the Japan tour. He has yet to win in
the United States.
	   Tanaka's first Japan Open title was worth 24 million yen (dlrs
176,000) from a purse of 120 million yen (dlrs 882,000).
	   Satoshi Higashi shot a 69 for 2-under 286, followed by Toru
Taniguchi, who turned in a 73 for 1-under 287.
	   Defending champion Craig Parry of Australia went around in 72
and shared sixth at 2-over 290 with Masashi ``Jumbo'' Ozaki, who
shot a 74, and four others.
	   Jumbo, the eldest of the Ozaki brothers, is the leading
money-winner this season so far with two victories. He was seeking
his 109th career victory.
 &UR; (kph)
</TEXT>
