<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Animal Blessing </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Exotic pets surprise Philippine church-goers
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos Available

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Pet owners brought a swarm of
animals, including iguanas, pythons and a donkey, to be blessed at
a Roman Catholic church in Manila Sunday.
	   Our Lady of Remedios Church and an animal welfare group invited
people to bring in their pets to mark the feast day of St. Francis
of Assisi. But they were overwhelmed by the animals that turned up.
	   The rite, offered for the first time at the church, was intended
to draw public attention to St. Francis' cause of caring for
animals and the environment, said the Rev. Francis Carey, the
priest who led the animals' blessing.
	   ``I didn't realize there would be so many,'' he said.
	   He counted at least 100 animals, including sheep, rabbits,
parrots and a hedgehog. A group of men dragged in a donkey, and a
small boy brought a fish in a glass bowl.
	   Church-goers who attended mass stayed on to gawk at the animals,
as the picturesque stone church began to smell and sound like a
zoo.
	   The blessing proceeded smoothly, except for some cats that
squirmed when doused with holy water.
	   ``I think the cats didn't like the water very much,'' Carey
said. 	   
</TEXT>
