u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Football-USCol 2ndLd-Writethru   10-04 1496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Football-US College Roundup, 2nd Ld-Writethru,1495 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ohio State's defense leads top-ranked Buckeyes over Penn State
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with late games. No pick up. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) _ Ohio State did it with defense.
	   Linebackers Jerry Rudzinski and Joe Cooper recovered fumbles in
the end zone for touchdowns as the top-ranked Buckeyes beat No. 7
Penn State 28-9 Saturday.
	   Last year, Penn State gained the No. 1 ranking with a win over
Ohio State at State College, Pa. In the rainy rematch at Columbus,
Ohio, the Buckeyes (4-0, 1-0 Big Ten) backed up their No. 1 ranking
with a dominating defensive performance against the Nittany Lions
(3-1, 0-1).
	   Ohio State held Penn State to 181 yards, including 79 on the
ground.
	   ``We wanted to redeem ourselves from that embarrassment last
year,'' Rudzinski said. ``We had the same players back and wanted
to step up and show the country.''
	   Rudzinski recovered a fumble by Penn State quarterback Kevin
Thompson for a TD with 3:51 left in the first half. In the third
quarter, Percy King blocked a Penn State punt and Cooper recovered
to put Ohio State up 21-3.
	   The Buckeyes' offensive touchdowns came on a 20-yard TD pass
from Joe Germaine to Michael Wiley just before halftime and Joe
Montgomery's 1-yard run with 3:08 left in the third quarter.
	   Ohio State quarterbacks coach Tim Salem got so excited by
Wiley's TD that he punched his hand through a window and sent glass
shattering into the press box. He suffered small cuts on his right
index finger and forearm.
	   In other Top 25 games, it was No. 2 Nebraska 24, Oklahoma State
17; No. 3 Tennessee 17, Auburn 9; No. 4 UCLA 49, Washington State
17; No. 12 Georgia 28, No. 6 LSU 27; No. 8 Florida 16, Alabama 10;
No. 9 Florida State 24, Maryland 10; No. 10 Virginia 52, San Jose
State 14; No. 13 Wisconsin 24, Indiana 20; No. 14 Arizona 31, No.
20 Washington 28; No. 15 Colorado 27, Oklahoma 25; No. 16 West
Virginia 45, Navy 24; No. 18 Texas A&AMP;M 24, Kansas 21; No. 21
Southern California 35, Arizona State 24; No. 22 Arkansas 27,
Kentucky 20; No. 23 Notre Dame 35, Stanford 17; co-No. 23 Missouri
35, Northwestern State 14; and No. 25 Michigan 12, Iowa 9.
 &UR; No. 2 Nebraska 24, Oklahoma State 17 &QC; 
	   At Kansas City, Mo., Nebraska's defense stopped Nathan Simmons
on the 1-yard line as time ran out to extend the nation's longest
major-college winning streak to 19 games.
	   Oklahoma State, seeking its first victory over Nebraska since
1961, faced a fourth-and-4 at the Huskers' 12 with 14 seconds left.
But Tony Lindsay kept the drive alive, hitting Sean Love with an
11-yard pass.
	   Lindsay then spiked the ball to stop the clock with five seconds
left. On the final play, Simmons ran up the middle but was stopped
by Mike Rucker and a swarm of defenders.
	   Nebraska (5-0, 1-0 Big 12), which took the lead on Joe Walker's
73-yard punt return with 7:29 left, stretched its unbeaten streak
against Oklahoma State (2-2, 1-1) to 35 games.
 &UR; No. 3 Tennessee 17, Auburn 9 &QC; 
	   At Auburn, Ala., Shaun Ellis returned an interception 90 yards
for a touchdown and Tennessee capitalized on three Auburn turnovers
to win the rematch of last year's SEC championship game.
	   Tennessee (4-0, 2-0) took a 17-0 lead in the first quarter, then
almost squandered it as Auburn (1-3, 1-2) shut down the Vols the
rest of the way.
 &UR; No. 4 UCLA 49, Washington St. 17 &QC; 
	   At Pasadena, Calif., Jermaine Lewis and Keith Brown each ran for
two TDs as UCLA extended its school-record winning streak to 13.
	   Cade McNown ran for one score and passed for another as the
Bruins (3-0, 1-0 Pac-10) won a league opener for just the second
time in eight years.
 &UR; No. 8 Florida 16, Alabama 10 &QC; 
	   At Tuscaloosa, Ala., Travis McGriff caught nine passes for 213
yards, including a 32-yard TD from Jesse Palmer, as Florida (4-1,
2-1 SEC) held off Alabama (2-2, 1-2).
	   Terry Jackson rushed for 135 yards but was stopped on
fourth-and-1 to give Alabama a last chance with 45 seconds left
from its own 26-yard line. Tide freshman Andrew Zow hit Calvin Hall
on a 45-yard pass to the Florida 34 with 19 seconds remaining, but
Tony George picked off a screen pass from Zow on the next play to
end the threat.
 &UR; No. 9 Florida St. 24, Maryland 10 &QC; 
	   At College Park, Md., Sebastian Janikowski kicked five field
goals and Chris Weinke passed for 261 yards as Florida State
overcame its own mistakes and surprisingly tough Maryland.
	   The Seminoles (4-1, 2-1 ACC) scored on their first four
possessions but led only 16-10 at halftime against a team they have
dominated for years.
 &UR; No. 10 Virginia 52, San Jose St. 14 &QC; 
	   At Charlottesville, Va., Thomas Jones ran for 203 yards and two
of Virginia's six rushing touchdowns.
	   Aaron Brooks also rushed for two touchdowns, Antwoine Womack ran
for 142 yards and one score, and Tyree Foreman added a 3-yard TD
run as the Cavaliers (5-0) gained 446 yards on the ground.
 &UR; No. 12 Georgia 28, No. 6 LSU 27 &QC; 
	   At Baton Rouge, La., freshman Quincy Carter passed for 318 yards
and two touchdowns as Georgia (4-0, 2-0 SEC) beat LSU (3-1, 1-1).
	   Carter quieted the huge Tiger Stadium crowd by leading Georgia
to touchdowns on its first three possessions.
 &UR; No. 13 Wisconsin 24, Indiana 20 &QC; 
	   At Bloomington, Ind., Ron Dayne became the sixth player in
major-college history to rush for 4,000 career yards as a junior.
	   Dayne carried 28 times for 130 yards, giving him 4,083 for his
career. He also scored on a 2-yard TD run that put Wisconsin (5-0,
2-0 Big Ten) ahead 24-20 with 10:54 remaining.
 &UR; No. 14 Arizona 31, No. 20 Washington 28 &QC; 
	   At Seattle, Ortege Jenkins scored on a 9-yard run _
somersaulting over three defenders into the end zone _ with four
seconds left to give Arizona (5-0, 2-0 Pac-10) its ninth straight
victory two seasons.
	   Washington's Jim Skurski missed a 23-yard field goal attempt
with 2:59 left. The Huskies dropped to 2-2 overall and 1-1 in the
Pac-10.
 &UR; No. 15 Colorado 27, Oklahoma 25 &QC; 
	   At Norman, Okla., Mike Moschetti threw three TD passes, Marlon
Barnes ran for a career-high 135 yards and Marcus Washington scored
on an interception return for Colorado.
	   The Buffaloes (5-0, 2-0 Big 12) won for the fifth straight time
in Norman. Oklahoma (2-2, 0-1) lost its second straight, despite
134 yards and two touchdowns from De'Mond Parker.
 &UR; No. 16 West Virginia 45, Navy 24 &QC; 
	   At Annapolis, Md., Marc Bulger threw for 354 yards and two
scores as West Virginia (3-1) rallied to beat Navy (1-3).
	   Amos Zereoue rushed for 95 yards and two TDs for West Virginia,
which trailed 17-3 in the second quarter and didn't take the lead
until early in the fourth when Antwan Lake recovered a fumble in
the Navy end zone.
 &UR; No. 18 Texas A&AMP;M 24, Kansas 21 &QC; 
	   At Lawrence, Kan., Dante Hall ran for 177 yards and three
touchdowns, including the game-winner with 3:24 left.
	   Linebacker Dat Nguyen set up two scores for the Aggies (4-1, 1-0
Big 12) with an interception and a recovery of a muffed punt.
Kansas (2-3, 0-3) has not won a conference game since beating Iowa
State 34-24 last Nov. 1.
 &UR; No. 21 USC 35, Arizona St. 24 &QC; 
	   At Los Angeles, Ifeanyi Ohalete returned a blocked punt 14 yards
for a touchdown early in the fourth quarter to put Southern
California (4-1, 2-0 Pac-10) ahead for good.
	   J.R. Redmond had a school-record 350 all-purpose yards and
scored a touchdown for Arizona State (2-3, 1-2), which was
outscored 21-0 in the final period.
 &UR; No. 22 Arkansas 27, Kentucky 20 &QC; 
	   At Little Rock, Ark., Clint Stoerner threw two fourth-quarter TD
passes and David Barrett set up the tying score with a 62-yard
interception return as Arkansas (4-0, 2-0 SEC) rallied to beat
Kentucky (3-2, 0-2).
	   Kentucky quarterback Tim Couch passed for a career-high 499
yards and three touchdowns, and broke his own SEC records with 47
completions and 66 attempts.
 &UR; No. 23 Missouri 35, Northwestern St. 14 &QC; 
	   At Columbia, Mo., Devin West ran for 176 yards and three
touchdowns as Missouri (3-1) overcame a sloppy effort to beat
Northwestern State (4-1).
	   Missouri, which entered the game as the nation's top rushing
team with 310 yards per game, gained 260 as it won for the fourth
straight time at home. West scored on runs of 17, 5 and 4 yards and
topped 100 yards for the third time in four games.
 &UR; No. 23 Notre Dame 35, Stanford 17 &QC; 
	   At South Bend, Ind., quarterback Jarious Jackson ran for 100
yards and threw for 163 as Notre Dame beat Stanford.
	   The Irish (3-1), who were outscored 79-23 in the opening half of
their first three games, scored on their first three possessions
against the Cardinal.
 &UR; No. 25 Michigan 12, Iowa 9 &QC; 
	   At Iowa City, Jay Feely kicked a 22-yard field goal with 8:19
left to give Michigan the victory over Iowa.
	   The Wolverines (3-2, 2-0 Big Ten) overcame sloppy play and
turnovers to win their third consecutive game and continue their
mastery over the Hawkeyes (2-3, 1-1), who have lost six straight in
the series.
</TEXT>
