<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Madikizela-Mandela </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Madikizela-Mandela in fear following break-ins
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ Winnie Madikizela-Mandela, the
controversial ex-wife of President Nelson Mandela, feels threatened
after a series of break-ins at her home, a newspaper reported
Friday.
	   In the third and most recent break-in, which occurred last week,
one or more intruders ransacked her bedroom but took nothing, the
Sunday Times reported.
	   ``I think they are giving me a message that they will return for
me very soon,'' Madikizela-Mandela was quoted as saying by the
Johannesburg weekly.
	   Police detective Inspector Mandla Hlakula said the intruder
appeared to be ``a highly trained person,'' the newspaper said. No
suspects were named.
	   Madikizela-Mandela, who was divorced from Mandela in 1996, is
the president of the ANC Women's League and a heroine of the
anti-apartheid struggle.
	   She was convicted in 1991 of kidnapping four young men and
taking part in assaults on them. Initially sentenced to six years
in jail, Madikizela-Mandela eventually paid a dlrs 3,200 fine on
appeal.
	   She has alienated many in the ANC by her criticism of the
government's slow progress in solving social issues and her call
for reintroduction of the death penalty to address soaring crime
rates.
	   (aos)
</TEXT>
