<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Politics, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETANSMITS to correct writethru sequence
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Malaysia's Anwar leaves hospital, women protest
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with women's protests in 7th-10th grafs; EDITS
thruout. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By JOCELYN GECKER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Malaysia's reformer politician
Anwar Ibrahim left a hospital Sunday after medical check-ups for
injuries he says he sustained in police beatings.
	   Anwar, due for arraignment Monday on five counts of corruption
and five of illegal homosexual acts, was admitted to the
government-owned University Hospital late Saturday, after a court
gave permission.
	   His overnight checkup over, a police motorcade whisked Anwar,
seated in the back of a jeep with tinted windows.
	   His lawyers said they did not know where he was taken. They have
been denied access to their client since his last court appearance
Wednesday.
	   Anwar, a former deputy prime minister, was once the heir
apparent to Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad. But as Anwar's
popularity increased along with his challenges of the longruling
Mahathir, he fell out of favor and was arrested Sept. 20.
	   In two court appearances last week, Anwar pleaded innocent to
the charges and said his black eye and bruises on his neck and arm
came from a police beating the night he was arrested.
	   Police have banned all gatherings connected with Anwar's reform
movement and they forced a group of 300 women, with their children
and some husbands, to disperse Sunday when they gathered across a
highway from the king's palace.
	   ``We are fighting for justice,'' said a Muslim woman in a head
scarf who, like others, said she was afraid to give her name.
	   ``They call this a democracy but they won't even let us gather
and sit on a hillside.''
	   The women left after two hours when riot police trucks and a
water cannon arrived. They did not mention Anwar but sang patriotic
songs.
	   An eye surgeon who examined Anwar last week determined the
jailed politician had been ``assaulted'' but the injuries had not
caused permanent eye damage.
	   The court granted Anwar's request for further medical attention
after he complained of neck and back pain.
	   University Hospital officials refused Sunday to comment on
Anwar's condition. He was to have undergone checks in the
orthopedic department, including X-rays of his backbone and his
bruised left eye.
	   Health Minister Chua Jui Meng said the doctors would submit a
report of their findings to the court. No deadline has been set.
	   Police stood guard within and outside the hospital, using a
wooden barricade to seal off entry to the first floor where Anwar
was being treated. Police blocked stairwell entrances and barred
visitors, including Anwar's wife and children.
	   After he was fired Sept. 2 as deputy prime minister and finance
minister, Anwar led thousands of people in two weeks of peaceful
protests against Mahathir's 17-year rule.
	   Anwar was arrested under the Internal Security Act, which allows
indefinite detention without charge.
	   The two top men in the government had clashed over economic
policy as Malaysia sank into recession. Mahathir has also accused
Anwar of plotting within the ruling party to supplant him before he
was ready to retire.
	   Mahathir initially suggested that his former protege had
inflicted the bruises on himself to win public sympathy. But as
global condemnation grew, Mahathir ordered an independent
investigation.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Malaysia-Politics, 2nd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
