<SLUG> BC-China-Reporter, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Family still waits for word on detained Chinese journalist
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 8th graf pvs to UPDATE with dissident
released; edits to conform &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Nearly a month after China's secret police hauled
away a leading Chinese journalist, his family still has no word on
his whereabouts or condition, a rights group reported Sunday.
	   Shi Binhai will pass his 30th day in detention Monday. Police
are required by law to either file formal detention orders or
release suspects after 30 days in custody, although the deadline is
often ignored.
	   As of Saturday night, Shi's family had neither received a
detention notice nor been told where he is being held, the Hong
Kong-based Information Center of Human Rights and Democratic
Movement in China reported.
	   Shi's wife, Zhang Hong, last saw him being taken away on Sept. 5
by agents from the Ministry of State Security.
	   An editor with the China Economic Times, a reformist newspaper
with loose connections to China's State Council, or Cabinet, the
36-year-old Shi also helped compile the popular book ``Political
China: Facing the Era of Choosing a New Structure.''
	   Although the book examines the need for political reform, media
and dissident circles believe other activities got Shi in trouble
with authorities.
	   The Information Center speculated that Shi was preparing to
interview Zhao Ziyang and had been in contact with the former
Communist Party leader who was purged for refusing to back a
crackdown on student democracy demonstrators in Tiananmen Square in
1989.
	   For many intellectuals and dissidents, Zhao has become a symbol
of a more tolerant era and for political change. Last seen in
public visiting students in Tiananmen Square on May 19, 1989, Zhao
has since lived under house arrest in a walled compound in Beijing.
	   Shi Binhai was detained amid a concerted police sweep against
democracy campaigners trying to set up a political opposition
party.
	   Police in northeastern Changchun city on Sunday released Tang
Yuanjuan, one of at least a dozen dissidents rounded up in the
clampdown. Tang had been held for a little more than two weeks.
	   Shi's 30th day in custody, Monday, is also the day China plans
to sign the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights,
the U.N. rights treaty that guarantees freedom of expression.
	   The Hong Kong-based Information Center called Shi's case a test
of whether Chinese leaders intend to respect the covenant. Even
after signing, the treaty will not come into force until ratified
by China's legislature, which may choose to attach reservations,
effectively nullifying some provisions.
</TEXT>
