<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Bailout Plan </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Head of ailing business group to announce bailout
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ Apologizing for the negative impact his
company's problems have had on the nation, the head of U-Land
business group said on Sunday that a bailout would be announced in
two days.
	   Chief Executive Officer Chou Chi-jui did not provide details but
predicted U-Land would survive its cash flow problems.
	   ``I know we're going to be fine, because U-Land's core structure
is still excellent,'' Chou told reporters. ``I deeply apologize for
allowing this matter to have such a large impact on the nation.''
	   The Taiwan stock market's main index plunged nearly 4 percent
Friday after U-Land announced its construction and textile
businesses had bounced checks of 140 million Taiwan dollars (U.S.
dlrs 4 million).
	   The group also operates an air carrier, U-Land Air Lines.
	   While Taiwan has weathered Asia's economic crisis admirably,
many investors saw U-Land's problems as just the tip of the iceberg
for the economy as businesses suffer from an economic slowdown and
loss of markets.
	   The group, which has accumulated debt of almost 10 billion
Taiwan dollars (U.S. dlrs 289 million), had asked for a week to put
together a bailout package from banks and investors.
	   Newspaper reports said some of U-Land's construction projects in
central Taiwan would be transferred to other companies in exchange
for cash, and listed King Textile would take on additional
investors, although U-Land intends to keep management rights.
	   Set up by brothers Chou Chi-jui and Chou Chi-chang 10 years ago,
the company grew into a small regional group with investments in
the Philippines and Vietnam.
	   They launched U-Land Air Lines in 1995 with a flamboyant 1
Taiwan dollar (2 U.S. cents) fare offer that quickly put them on
the airline map but left them with a pile of debt that has
continued to grow.
	   The airline may sell some planes in favor of leasing but will
continue with a plan to to buy 40 percent of Air Philippines, the
China Times Express reported.
	   Company representatives were unavailable for further comment
Sunday. 	   
</TEXT>
