w1635 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Malaysia-TurningPoint 1stLd-Writethru   10-04 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Turning Point, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
September a turning point in Malaysian politics
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: INSERTS 10th graf, `Our ... man,' with fresh Sunday quote from
Anwar's wife.
 &UR; AP Photos KL106
 &UR; By RANJAN ROY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ It was a difficult September in
tropical Malaysia. The deputy prime minister was fired over sordid
sex allegations, arrested and then turned up in court with a black
eye.
	   Battered and bruised, Anwar Ibrahim has struck a chord, making
ordinary Malaysians defy state power and question political
authority for the first time.
	   In a nation where even the main opposition party had stopped
short of calling for the top man's dismissal, people began to
publicly criticize Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad's 17-year-rule
and shout in the streets for him to resign.
	   ``I think it is a generational thing. Younger Malaysians are
saying that they are not prepared to accept someone's word just
because he has been in power so long,'' said Rustam Sani, a social
critic.
	   Since Mahathir, 72, fired Anwar on Sept. 2, it has been four
weeks of fiery speeches, mammoth crowds, posters, leaflets,
underground videotapes, tear gas and water cannons in a country
where political protest is virtually banned.
	   Never has a dissident gone around the country declaiming that
Mahathir is corrupt and never have so many responded to such
dissent.
	   ``It is not a blip on the screen,'' says Abdul Razak Baginda,
executive director of the Malaysian Strategic Research Center, a
private think tank.
	   ``We have this thing toward the government. Respect or fear of
the state apparatus. But now a lot of us are angered by what has
happened,'' said Baginda.
	   The law requires police permits for public gatherings of more
than four people. Anwar just showed up. The throngs gathered,
feeling the exhilaration of shouting out their feelings while
police did nothing to stop them.
	   ``Our movement has aroused something very latent in the minds of
Malaysians,'' Anwar's wife, Azizah Ismail, told a news conference
Sunday. She said ordinary folks had begun fighting a ``corrupt and
debilitating system that acts on the whims of one power-hungry
man.''
	   There were 35,000 in Kuala Lumpur's Merdeka Square on Sept. 20,
chanting ``Reform,'' and carrying Anwar on their shoulders a few
hours before his arrest.
	   Some got carried away, marched toward the prime minister's
residence, trashed the lobby of the ruling party headquarters. Then
the police acted.
	   Day after day they charged protesters, soaking them with
stinging jets of water, beating and arresting them as government
opponents were scooped up into detention. At least 300 people were
arrested.
	   Yet many who remained free spoke out more strongly than ever.
	   Lim Kit Siang, head of the opposition Democratic Action Party,
for the first time said Mahathir had been in power too long and
took him on face-to-face in a Parliament debate over Anwar's
detention.
	   ``It's not that people are pro-Anwar, but the people are
concerned with what the government is doing. It has full control,''
said Zainal Rohizan, a university employee who rushed to court last
week for a glimpse of Anwar after reading about his injuries.
	   Anwar, 51, said he was handcuffed and blindfolded, then
clobbered by policemen on the night of his arrest on Sept. 20.
During his arraignment on 10 counts of sodomy and corruption nine
days later, the man who had been in line for the past five years to
step into the prime minister's seat said police stopped beating him
only when he fell unconscious.
	   The last time Malaysians came out on the streets to protest
against Mahathir was in 1987 when he sacked Supreme Court judges.
More than 100 people were detained under the Internal Security Act,
which allows imprisonment without trial.
	   ``But this time the main actor is a politician with a much
greater national presence, second only to Mahathir's,'' said
Chandra Muzaffar, a professor of politics at University of Malaya.
	   ``It has stirred the grass roots the way 1987 had not,'' said
Chandra. ``The issue has captured national imagination cutting
across ethnic divides.''
	   It was not just majority Malays angry over the treatment of a
politician of their race and religion, but Chinese and Indians who
joined protests, he said. Malays comprise nearly 60 percent of the
country's 22 million people. Chinese are 30 percent and ethnic
Indians 10 percent.
	   The political crisis could not have come at a worse time. Months
of wrangling between Mahathir and Anwar over policy had left
investors confused and the economy directionless. Just before Anwar
was booted he announced that Malaysia had sunk into its first
recession in 10 years. Thousands will lose their jobs, the
government has said.
	   Yet many Malays are grateful for the modern cities and factories
Mahathir has built in a country that until a decade ago was an
Asian backwater exporting rubber and tin.
	   ``Malaysians being Malaysians, once they find their pockets full
will start wondering why they are wasting time with politics,''
said Chandra. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Malaysia-Turning Point, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
