r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Germany-Obit-Kaske     10-04 0262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Obit-Kaske </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Siemens chief who led expansion in 1980s dies
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MUNICH, Germany (AP) _ Former Siemens chief Karlheinz Kaske, who
oversaw the electronics company's vigorous expansion into a
worldwide concern during the 1980s, has died at age 70.
	   Kaske died on Sept. 27, the company said. No cause of death was
given.
	   Born in Essen, Kaske studied physics before joining Siemens and
Halske in 1950. He left to work as a teacher and consultant, but
returned in 1969 after helping plan the consolidation of Siemens
companies into today's Siemens AG conglomerate.
	   He was appointed to the managing board in 1975 and became
president and chief executive officer in 1981, an office he held
until 1992.
	   During his tenure, Kaske led Siemens into overseas markets,
including the United States and China. He also helped strengthen
Siemens' position in Europe with the takeover of Plessey together
with Britain's GEC.
	   His strong interest in research and development and
microelectronics showed in the company's expansion into automotive
systems and its purchase of Nixdorf AG.
	   By the time he stepped down, Siemens worldwide sales had more
than doubled and income had nearly quadrupled to almost 2 billion
marks (dlrs 1.2 billion at current exchange rates).
	   Kaske continued to hold various positions, including chairman of
MAN AG's supervisory board and member of the board of Eastman
Kodak, and worked for many philanthropic and educational causes.
	   Siemens released no information about survivors or funeral
services.
 &UR; (pfg)
</TEXT>
