w1651 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Australia-Election-Ha     10-04 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Election-Hanson </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Politicians, ethnic leaders welcome failure of Hanson
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Australia-Election &QL; 
 &UR; By ROHAN SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Right-wing politician Pauline Hanson's
One Nation Party should not be written off, despite its failure at
Australia's national election, political opponents and ethnic
community leaders said Sunday.
	   Hanson's hopes of leading her party to a role of national
influence were dashed Saturday when One Nation failed to secure a
single seat in Parliament's lower house.
	   With almost 80 percent of the vote counted, Hanson even appeared
to have lost her own seat, depriving One Nation's its namesake on
the national political stage.
	   One Nation's sole success was in the upper house Senate, where
candidate Heather Hill is poised to take the place of government
coalition member Bill O'Chee. But another minority party, the
Democrats, looks likely to control the balance of power in the
Senate, denying One Nation influence.
	   Just hours after predicting One Nation would win up to 15
electorates, a subdued Hanson said on Saturday night that she would
continue to try to run her party.
	   ``I'm still the president of One Nation and I hope I will be
there to work behind the scenes,'' Hanson told reporters.
	   One Nation strategist and failed candidate David Oldfield denied
the party was finished.
	   ``We're in a position now where, while we haven't had as many
people elected as we would've liked, we've still got a strong
contingent in the Queensland parliament,'' he told the Nine
television network.
	   One Nation's high water mark now appears to have been the June
election in Queensland state, where the party won 23 percent of the
vote amnd 11 seats in the state's parliament.
	   Hanson has dominated Australian politics since she was elected
to national parliament as an independent in 1996. She warned that
Australia was in danger of being ``swamped by Asians'' and opposed
land rights and special welfare benefits for Aborigines.
	   On Sunday, ethnic leaders said the major parties should still
concentrate on issues which Hanson opposed to appeal to voters.
	   Diane Shteinman, president of the Executive Council of
Australian Jewry said the major parties could not ignore the
worries of people who had voted for her party.
	   ``It wasn't as if she was rejected by the electorate ... there
were a lot of votes out there for the One Nation party,'' Shteinman
said.
	   Politicians from all major parties were quick to welcome One
Nation's poor performance.
	   ``Rumours of One Nation's demise are very premature,'' said Mike
Kaiser, the opposition Labor Party's secretary in Queensland.
	   Prime Minister John Howard said One Nation would struggle
without Hanson in parliament.
	   ``I hope that One Nation just dissolves. It probably won't in
the short term _ it might take some time,'' he said.
</TEXT>
