<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Kosovo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian government condemns possible NATO attack on Yugoslavia
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The Russian government condemned Sunday any
unsanctioned NATO attack on Yugoslavia as a ``rude violation'' of
the United Nations charter, and urged the conflict be solved
diplomatically.
	   ``The Russian government thinks it necessary to emphasize again
that using force against a sovereign state without the sanction of
the Security Council would be a rude violation of the UN charter,''
according to a government statement.
	   ``We are convinced that complicated ethnic conflicts, which the
Kosovo conflict undoubtedly is, cannot be settled militarily.''
	   The statement echoed earlier comments by Russian Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov and other Russian leaders, who sharply opposed any
NATO attacks.
	   Western governments have warned that NATO might take military
action after accusations that Serbian forces committed atrocities
against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
	   Russia's parliament last week declared that any NATO military
action over Kosovo taken without U.N. approval would be considered
an ``illegal act of aggression.''
	   In a unanimous resolution passed Friday, the State Duma said it
would review all agreements between NATO and Russia if the Western
alliance were to opt for force against Yugoslavia.
	   The NATO allies have not yet resolved their differences over
whether a further U.N. resolution is needed to launch air strikes,
and a final decision about whether to use force won't likely be
made until later this month.
	   (nw/ren)
</TEXT>
