w1663 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Taiwan-China     10-04 0347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-China </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taiwan to include independence supporters in China visit
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ In a move likely to upset Beijing,
supporters of Taiwanese independence will be part of the delegation
that will visit the Chinese mainland.
	   Beijing, which views Taiwan as a renegade province, has been
hopeful that the visit set to begin Oct. 14 will lead to progress
in reunification talks.
	   But Koo Chen-fu, a senior statesman who is Taiwan's top envoy to
China, has agreed to allow members of the Democratic Progressive
Party to accompany him on his breakthrough visit, Chiu Yi-jen, the
party's secretary-general, told reporters Sunday.
	   Chiu said the party is concerned only that ``the voice of all
the Taiwanese people'' is heard during the meetings, and would
leave selection of individuals and designation of their official
capacities to Koo.
	   The Democratic Progressive Party, or DPP, advocates Taiwan's
permanent and formal independence from China, arguing that Taiwan
has developed its own political and social culture after being
separated from China for all but four of the last 100 years.
	   China rejects that view and threatens to invade the island if it
declares independence.
	   The DPP has asked to join Koo's delegation because it says China
will likely use the meeting to push for concessions on political
talks between the sides.
	   Taiwan's ruling Nationalist Party, of which Koo is a ranking
member, officially supports reunification, but only gradually and
not on China's terms.
	   China broke off negotiations in 1995, two years after they
started, over a series of moves by Taiwan to assert itself
internationally.
	   China demands that Taiwan agree to discuss an agenda for
political talks before restarting their dialogue.
	   Taiwan hopes Koo's visit will help pave the way for a
restoration of talks on practical issues like resolution of fishing
disputes.
	   The government says it doesn't rule out talking about an agenda
for political negotiations but argues that agreements on
substantive issues should come first. 	   
</TEXT>
