<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Sugar </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippines considering multi-billion peso plan to revive sugar
</HEADLINE>
industry

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ The Philippine government and private
firms are considering a 40 billion peso (dlrs 930 million)
investment to revive the country's ailing sugar industry.
	   The money will be used to modernize sugar mills and refineries,
irrigate cane plantations and buy farm equipment under a five-year
plan, a government statement said Sunday.
	   The plan also calls for investment in research to develop
high-yielding and disease-resistant cane varieties.
	   The plan was drawn up by sugar industry leaders and submitted to
President Joseph Estrada when he visited sugar-producing provinces
on central Negros island on Friday.
	   If the plan is not carried out, the Philippines may have to
import sugar in the next few years as demand, which grows by 3.4
percent annually, would far exceed production, the statement said.
	   Enrique Roxas, president of the National Federation of Sugar
Planters, said declining cane production, aggravated by poor cane
quality, has sharply reduced sugar production in the last few
years.
	   Until the early 1990s, the Philippines had met domestic sugar
demands and was one of the largest suppliers of sugar to the United
States under a quota arrangement. 	   
</TEXT>
