<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Human Rights, HFR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE ON 1700 GMT OCT. 4, TIME SET BY SOURCE
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Rights group documents atrocities in Kosovo
 &UR; By JEFFREY ULBRICH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) - Both the government of President
Slobodan Milosevic and Kosovo's Albanian rebels have committed
atrocities in seven months of conflict, but government abuses have
been on a far greater scale, Human Rights Watch said in a report
issued Sunday.
	   The New York-based human rights organization blamed the
international community for failing to take any serious action to
stop the killing of mostly Albanian civilians in the
ethnic-Albanian majority Serbian province.
	   ``The tentative international response has been driven by fear
of either endorsing Kosovo independence or being drawn into a
long-term commitment of forces to maintain a peaceful settlement
within former Yugoslavia'' it said.
	   The report came just one day before U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan was to deliver his own assessment to the Security Council on
whether Belgrade is complying with U.N. demands to halt its assault
on ethnic Albanians. If not, Washington has indicated that NATO air
attacks will come within two weeks.
	   Human Rights Watch said Serbian police and military ``committed
extrajudicial executions and other unlawful killings,
systematically destroyed civilian property and attacked
humanitarian aid workers, all of which are violations of the rules
of war.''
	   ``The Albanian insurgency, known as the Kosovo Liberation Army,
has also violated the laws of war by such actions as the taking of
civilian hostages and by summary executions,'' the report said.
``Although on a lesser scale than the government abuses, these too
are violations of international standards and should be
condemned.''
	   The report leaves no doubt that it feels Milosevic bears ``the
primary responsibility for gross government abuses.'' It says at
least 250,000 thousand people have been displaced, many of them
women and children now living without shelter in the mountains and
forests.
	   ``Despite the seriousness of these abuses, the international
community has failed to take any serious action to stop the
killing,'' the report said, adding that ``Milosevic continues to be
viewed by many as a legitimate and trustworthy negotiating
partner.''
	   To deal with the many reports of massacres, summary executions
and mass graves, Human Rights Watch says the international
community must insist on immediate access for international
forensic experts to investigate the allegations and support the
International Criminal Tribunal for Yugoslavia.
	   ``We feel the International Criminal Tribunal in The Hague
should be involved,'' said Peter Bouckhaert, a Human Rights Watch
investigator here.
	   ``If independent forensic experts would be allowed to all the
sites, it would be a lot easier to find out who is responsible.''
	   That is particularly true, he said, in cases where the Serbian
police themselves are implicated.
	   ``It is important that the government doesn't pick and choose
who will investigate them,'' Bouckaert said.
	   The report details and documents serious breaches of
international law, condemns the government for restricting the
ability of humanitarian aid workers to treat people who have fled
their homes. It also criticizes government restrictions on the
press seeking to report atrocities.
	   ``Some ethnic Albanian journalists have been threatened,
detained or beaten by the police, and independent Serb media have
been labeled `traitors' or threatened with legal action for
objective reporting on Kosovo.''
	   (ju/gj)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
