r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-Aceh     10-04 0265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Aceh </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fact-finding team found 760 killed or missing in Aceh
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ A fact-finding team sent by the
provincial government has found about 760 soldiers and rebels
missing or killed in a military operation against Islamic
separatist rebels in the northernmost province of Aceh.
	   The death toll, reported Sunday by the official Antara news
agency, was similar to what has already been announced by the
Indonesian Armed Forces.
	   Antara quoted Yusuf Ismail Pase, team vice chairman, as saying
they found some 600 women who had been widowed, along with 1,960
orphans and 10 women who had been raped.
	   Aceh, a predominantly Muslim province, is one of three
Indonesian provinces where separatist rebels are fighting for
independence.
	   Sunday's findings were slightly different from those disclosed
in August by the National Commission on Human Rights, a
government-sponsored watchdog, which uncovered mass graves of
alleged victims in the military.
	   That group found 781 deaths. It also reported as missing at
least 160 people and said 368 people had been tortured.
	   Pase said his team has also found various cases of violence and
extortion of properties like cars, motorcycles and jewelry.
	   He noted the operation has left a deep traumatic impact on the
villagers, especially between 1989-1992, the early years of the
operation.
	   In August, Armed Forces Commander Gen. Wiranto decided to end
the military operation and withdrew troops from the tip of Sumatra
region, about 1,750 kilometers (1,100 miles) northwest of Jakarta.
</TEXT>
