<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Currency </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Malaysian customs will seize travelers' extra cash
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Customs officers were ordered
Sunday to begin seizing any Malaysian currency that travelers
carried above the limit of 1,000 ringgit (dlrs 263), a newspaper
reported.
	   State Customs Director Abdul Rahman Abdul Hamid was quoted by
the Sunday Star as saying the seizures were to begin at Johor
Bahru, the border crossing between Malaysia and Singapore.
	   Currency restrictions went into effect Oct. 1, limiting the
amount of local and foreign currency travelers can carry out of the
country and the amount of ringgit they can bring in.
	   Abdul Rahman said during the three-day grace period, more than
100 travelers had been found carrying ringgit above the limit. From
now on the extra cash will be confiscated and a receipt given, he
said. Travelers can appeal to the central bank to get their money
back.
	   Non-Malaysians are allowed to carry out of the country no more
foreign currency than they bring in, but Abdul Rahman did not
specify whether there had been any violations of that rule.
	   He said that on Saturday the central bank had raised the limit
on the amount of foreign currency citizens can take out of Malaysia
to 50,000 ringgit (dlrs 13,157).
	   Senior customs officers will be able to clear up to that amount
so that travelers can pay for medical or school expenses abroad, he
was quoted as saying. Previously the limit had been announced as
10,000 ringgit (dlrs 2,631). 	   
</TEXT>
