u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Italy-Politics     10-04 0369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Italian Communist sticks to decision to yank support for Prodi
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: Will be updated with vote by Communist leaders, time
uncertain &QL; 
 &UR; With AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By FRANCES D'EMILIO
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Italy's Communist leader on Sunday insisted on
withdrawing support for Premier Romano Prodi's 2 1-2-year-old
coalition, a move expected to trigger the collapse of one of the
country's longest-lived governments.
	   Bitterly divided, leaders of the Communist Refoundation party,
which gives Prodi a majority in the lower Chamber of Deputies, were
scheduled to vote later in the day on the proposal to yank support
for the center-left coalition.
	   Prodi has said he would call a confidence vote if the Communists
decide to yank support. The coalition has a majority without the
Communists in the Senate, but has depended on them for passage of
key legislation in the Chamber.
	   Defying other top Communist officials, Fausto Bertinotti, party
secretary, defended his strategy to vote against the government's
proposed 1999 budget and to refuse to back the government in a
confidence vote. Bertinotti said he is betting that a new
government would be more leftist.
	   While Prodi could theoretically win votes from centrists now in
the opposition as well as from Bertinotti dissenters to pass the
budget as well as in a confidence vote, he has stressed that his
electoral platform included a pledge to work with the Communists in
major policy issues. Thus he is likely to resign if the Communists
won't back him.
	   The Communists' No. 2, Armando Cossutta, has argued against
Bertinotti's plan, insisting it would be better to work with he
government for a budget that would devote more funds to job
creation.
	   A split left, argued Oliviero Diliberto, the Communist Chamber
whip, would help the center-right opposition, led by ex-premier
Silvio Berlusconi, who has been pressing for early elections.
	   The Communists contend the budget doesn't contain enough funds
to creat jobs, especially in the south, where unemployment runs as
high as 20 percent.
	   Prodi's coalition has outlived all but two of Italy's other 54
postwar governments.
	   (fd) 	   
</TEXT>
