<HEADLINE>
Auto component workers end South African strike
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to ADD terms &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ The National Union of
Metalworkers ended a five-week long strike on Sunday by spare-part
makers in the auto industry after agreeing on wage hikes.
	   The strike was called off after union members endorsed the
latest wage proposals, which include raises of up to 10 percent.
	   The country's seven auto manufacturers had been nearly shut down
because of a shortage of components caused by the strike.
