r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Baseball-Japan     10-04 0343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-Japan Roundup </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lions shutout Dragons 5-0, reducing magic to three
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Domingo Martinez and Ken Suzuki connected for
back-to-back solo homers in the eighth Sunday as the Pacific
League's winningest Seibu Lions shut out the Fukuoka Daiei Hawks
5-0 at home.
	   Seeking their second league pennant in a row, the Lions now have
reduced their magic number to three with nine games left.
	   Martinez, formerly with Triple-A Rochester, has 29 home runs and
ranks fourth in the league.
	   Lions' reliever Yukihiro Nishizaki gave up one hit, while
fanning two in two innings and collected his first victory since he
joined the Lions from the Fighters earlier this year.
	   The Hawks wrapped up their season Sunday with their fifth loss
in a row.
	   No other Pacific League games were scheduled Sunday.
	   In the Central League, Tetsuya Iida tripled home three runs in
the top of the first inning as the Yakult Swallows trounced the
front-running Yokohama BayStars 8-4, delaying their league victory.
	   The BayStars lost their second game in a row, with their magic
for the league pennant still at three with eight games left.
Takahiro Ikeyama hit a two run homer in the second.
	   Swallows starter Kenjiro Kawasaki (16-10) gave up seven hits,
struck out three and walked two in seven innings. He is tied with
the Yomiuri Giants' Masumi Kuwata for the league lead in wins.
	   Robert Rose, formerly with the California Angels, batted in a
run on a double in the bottom of the eighth. But that came too late
for the BayStars.
	   The Swallows, the league's defending champions, have been
already eliminated for this year's pennant.
	   At Koshien, Nathan Minchey threw a four-hitter and allowed no
runners beyond first base after the third inning as the Hiroshima
Toyo Carp edged the Hanshin Tigers 3-1.
	   Minchey (15-11), formerly of the Boston Red Sox, struck out four
and walked none and completed the game with 120 pitches, chalking
up his fifth win this season against the last-place Tigers.
 &UR; (may)
</TEXT>
