SYRIA: MUBARAK -  Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak has arrived in
Syria for talks with President Hafez al-Assad over rising tensions
between Damascus and Turkey. Turkey has been amassing troops along
its border with Syria for several weeks. APTN has pictures of
Mubarak's arrival at Damascus International Airport. (First Run
F-L-A-S-H 1220)
----
HEBRON: CLASHES - Clashes have broken out at an Israeli checkpoint
outside the tense West Bank town of Hebron, but no injuries have
been reported. Sunday marked the fifth straight day of skirmishes in
and around Hebron, which is a frequent f-l-a-s-hpoint for violence.
(First Run 0900 The Americas)
----
MIDEAST: PEACE - Palestinian and Israeli negotiators are holding a
new round of talks in Jerusalem, aimed at ironing out outstanding
problems with interim peace deals.
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu says he hopes the
Palestinians decide whether or not they want progress in the Middle
East peace process before U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
arrives on Tuesday. (First Run 1030 F-L-A-S-H)
----
ISRAEL: SYRIA - Israel on Sunday limited routine exercises along its
border with Syria in a signal that it did not want to become
involved in any potential military conflict in the region. In recent
weeks, Turkey has been massing troops along its border with Syria
and tensions between the two neighbours have increased. Israel says
it has nothing to do with the dispute. (First Run 1030 F-L-A-S-H)
----
UK: KOSOVO - The British government has warned Serb leader Slobodan
Milosevic to end his game of cat-and-mouse or face action by the
international community. Defense Secretary George Robertson told
BBC's Breakfast With Frost on Sunday that NATO is ready to move on a
series of options - including military action. (First Run 1030
F-L-A-S-H)
----
AUSTRALIA: REACTIONS - Prime Minister John Howard's conservative
government may have narrowly won re-election but it suffered a
greatly diminished majority in parliament. APTN's followup package
includes comments from Howard and Labour leader Kim Beazley and
footage of One Nation leader Pauline Hanson, who failed to hold
her seat. (FIRST RUN 0715 ASIA PACIFIC)
----
JAPAN: SUMO - APTN has coverage of a news conference by top
foreign-born sumo wrestler Akebono and his wife Christina Reiko
Kalina, who got married in April but staged an official wedding
ceremony on Saturday. (FIRST RUN 0715 ASIA PACIFIC LATE)
----
RUSSIA: NORILSK - APTN has a special feature on Norilsk Nickel, one
of Russia's biggest industries, which is doing its best to weather
the financial crisis. Privatised in 1994, Norilsk is in the middle
of major restructuring but to make matters worse, the metals giant
is now struggling with a triple crisis as world nickel prices
plummet. (FIRST RUN 0800 EUROPE MORNING)
----
RUSSIA: MARCH - Anti-government demonstrators are expected to
continue marking the fifth anniversary of the storming of Moscow's
White House and the battles between government forces and
opposition lawmakers. APTN has protest coverage. (FIRST RUN AFTER
1130 EUROPE UPDATE)
