r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Germany-PotsdamerPlat     10-04 0372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Potsdamer Platz </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1 million visitors storm Berlin's new center on opening weekend
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos BER101-102 &QL; 
 &UR; By FRIEDER REIMOLD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BERLIN (AP) _ On a weekend meant to celebrate German unity, an
estimated 1 million Berliners stormed a brand new shopping and
entertainment complex on what used to be the no-man's land of the
Berlin Wall.
	   In scenes reminiscent of the exuberant days that followed the
Wall's collapse in 1989, the 10 new streets through Potsdamer Platz
were full of shoppers and strollers admiring the brightly lit
complex built by Daimler-Benz at a cost of 4 billion marks (dlrs
2.4 billion).
	   ``It's like 1989, when they tore the Wall down,'' said one
excited visitor. ``It's unbelievable here,'' said an elderly man,
almost in tears.
	   Most stores in Germany closed for Saturday's German Unification
Day holiday. But those at Potsdamer Platz were open until midnight
_ and were packed till the end.
	   ``I've been waiting since 8 o'clock to go home,'' one flustered
salesclerk said shortly before midnight. ``But with this chaos you
can't even think of it.''
	   The newly opened Mendelssohn-Bartholdy-Park subway station was
so jammed at times trains couldn't load or unload passengers, and
just passed through without stopping.
	   Before World War II, the square in the center of Berlin was one
of Europe's busiest intersections _ site of the first traffic
signal on the continent.
	   What wasn't destroyed by Allied bombing during World War II,
though, was torn down when the area became part of the ``death
strip'' between the Wall's two sections.
	   Daimler-Benz and Sony stepped in after unification, turning the
wasteland into Europe's biggest construction site.
	   The 19-building Daimler-Benz complex, which officially opened
Friday, includes apartments, shops, theaters, a casino, hotel and
offices around a square named for actress Marlene Dietrich, a
Berlin native.
	   Italian architect Renzo Piano oversaw the project and designed
the centerpiece, a 20-story, terra cotta office tower for the
Daimler-Benz's financial service unit, Debis.
	   Sony expects to have its European headquarters on the site
finished by 2000.
 &UR; (rm-pfg)
</TEXT>
