<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Politics, 1st Ld, 1st Add </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROME: the chamber.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   There was no immediate reaction from the government.
	   A confidence vote could be scheduled in the next few days. If
Prodi fails to muster a majority in the chamber he would be forced
to resign and new elections might be called.
	   Bitterly divided, the Communist Refoundation's national
political committee voted 188 to 112 in favor of refusing to vote
for the government's proposed 1999 budget as well as to stop
backing the center-left coalition.
	   Defying other top Communist officials, Fausto Bertinotti, party
secretary, defended his strategy to vote against the government,
betting that a new government would be more leftist.
	   The Communists' No. 2, Armando Cossutta, had argued against
Bertinotti's plan, insisting it would be better to work with he
government for a budget that would devote more funds to job
creation.
	   A split left, argued Oliviero Diliberto, the Communist Chamber
whip, would only help the center-right opposition, led by
ex-premier Silvio Berlusconi, who has been pressing for early
elections.
	   Prodi's coalition has outlived all but two of Italy's other 54
postwar governments.
	   (fd)
</TEXT>
