<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 10/04/1998 09:39:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1773 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 1stLd-Writethru   10-04 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede PRISTINA
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Russian delegation meets Milosevic as NATO threatens strikes
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Russians meeting Milosevic; trims. Changes byline
 &UR; AP Photos BEL101-102

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Reacting to the threat of a NATO
strike on Yugoslavia, Russia's defense and foreign ministers called
on President Slobodan Milosevic on Sunday, as his generals prepared
to defend the country against attack.
	   Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev
met with Milosevic and Milan Milutinovic, president of Serbia the
dominant Yugoslav republic that controls Kosovo.
	   Despite Russia's opposition NATO is preparing for possible
intervention in Serbia's southern province to end seven months of
bloodshed. Serbian police and the Yugoslav army have killed
hundreds of people and left upward of 275,000 others homeless in
their seven-month crackdown on Albanian separatists in the
Albanian-majority province.
	   There was no official confirmation of the surprise meeting. But
news photographers captured it on film.
	   Russia is the Serbs' main ally, sharing bonds of religion, and
joint Slavic roots.
	   In Moscow, the Itar-Tass news agency carried a government
statement again expressing opposition to any NATO intervention in
Kosovo without the sanction of the U.N. Security Council, of which
Russia is a veto-carrying member.
	   ``Military interference ... would aggravate many times the
confrontation in Kosovo and undermine diplomatic efforts'' to
reestablish peace and dialogue, said the statement.
	   Preparing for any attack, Yugoslav generals put the nation's air
defense on high alert, even as Serbian authorities indicated they
were ready for compromise by installing an interim government in
the rebellious Serbian province. A Western diplomat also said that
up to 120 Yugoslav army armored vehicles, including tanks, have
been pulled out of Kosovo so far.
	   But the West apparently remained unmoved.
	   Speaking in Copenhagen, Denmark, German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel said Friday that the NATO intervention clock ``is at one
minute to 12.'' He stressed that ``no ultimatum, no date has been
set,'' but added: ``Mr. Milosevic must know that we are serious.''
	   The Yugoslav government said Friday the fighting had ended and
blamed continuing violence on ethnic Albanian rebels. Serbia is the
larger of two republics that comprise Yugoslavia. Serbian police
and the Yugoslav army has routed separatist Kosovo Albanian rebels
in a seven-month crackdown that has killed hundreds _ most of them
Albanian civilians _ and left upward of 275,000 villagers refugees.
	   Ethnic Albanian political leaders rejected the interim council,
drawn up without any consultation with them, and made up of seven
Serbs, five ethnic Albanians and the rest Turks and Muslims.
	   Constituting the council, moribund since 1989, was part of a
last-ditch effort to show that Serbs intend to end the conflict.
U.N. chief Kofi Annan plans report Monday to the Security Council
on whether Belgrade is complying with demands to halt its assault
on ethnic Albanians. If not, Washington has indicated that NATO air
strikes will follow within two weeks.
	   Momentum for international leaders to step in has increased in
the past week amid revelations of massacres of ethnic Albanian
civilians in the forests of Kosovo.
	   On Saturday, Serb police took reporters to the site of what they
thought was a mass grave on a mountain top near the village of
Volujak, about 60 kilometers (40 miles) west of the provincial
capital, Pristina. Dogs, they said, had unearthed human bones in an
area formerly held by the Albanian separatist Kosovo Liberation
Army.
	   With reporters looking on, police dug up parts of four skeletons
and said from the smell that they suspected there were more, but
there was no way to identify the remains or determine their
ethnicity and cause of death without closer forensic investigation.
	   The Serbian media reported that Chinese-made bullet casings were
found and also empty casings of hunting rifles at the site where
the bodies were found, both characteristic for ammunition used by
the KLA.
	   (gj/mos/ms)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
