w1784 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MiddleEastBusinessBri     10-04 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Middle East Business Briefs </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Egypt, Iran, Jordan, Kuwait. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Egypt has received dlrs 336 million from the
United States to finance development projects, it was announced
Sunday.
	   Washington has also pledged to give another dlrs 826.6 million
to finance other projects, including agriculture and water, health
and population and environment.
	   Egypt will also receive dlrs 86 million in cash transfers by the
end of the year.
	   Sunday's announcement was made in Cairo by Egypt's Minister of
State for Planning Zafer el-Bishry and U.S. Ambassador Daniel
Kurtzer.
 &UR; ___
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ Iran and Iraq are discussing ways to
facilitate business with each other, the official Islamic Republic
News Agency reported Sunday.
	   It said talks were held between the head of the Iraqi Chamber of
Commerce Zahir Abdul-Ghafur Younus and his Iranian counterpart
Ali-Naqi Khamoushi. Younus is in Iran to attend the 24th Tehran
International Trade Fair, the agency reported.
	   It said the two men discussed how to facilitate issuing entry
visas and the possibility of exporting Iranian goods to Iraq.
	   Meanwhile, Iran's Trade Minister Mohammad Shariatmadari met with
his Iraqi counterpart Mohammed Mehdi Saleh in Tehran Saturday, the
official Iraqi News Agency reported. The two ministers agreed to
expand economic and trade ties and to export Iranian food and
medicine to Iraq.
	   This is the second consecutive year that Iraq attends the Tehran
trade fair.
	   The two countries fought an eight-year war that began in Sept.
1980.
	   Iraq is suffering from crippling U.N trade sanctions imposed
after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
	   For humanitarian reasons, Iraq was allowed to buy food and
medicine under a U.N-approved agreement in 1996 which permits it to
sell a limited amount of oil.
 &UR; ___
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Jordan plans to give financial and
administrative independence to its only news agency, Petra, which
is virtually a government mouthpiece.
	   The move is part of a privatization bid aimed at ridding the
government of costs of various public offices. Petra's
semi-independence will save the government more than 1.2 million
Jordanian dinars (dlrs 1.7 million), allocated annually to the news
agency.
	   Last year, the government followed a similar approach with the
Jordan Radio and Television Corp.
	   Under the new plan _ which is still under study _ Petra will
generate income through subscription of its news and photo
services, the agency's director-general Abdullah Etoum said Sunday.
	   But the editorial bulletin and photo distribution will remain
under the supervision of the Ministry of Information, Etoum said.
	   He said the plan also envisages expanding Petra's operations by
launching 28 new offices worldwide from the current 16 _ which are
mostly in Arab countries and the United States.
	   Information Minister Nasser Judeh was quoted in Jordanian
newspapers as saying Petra will soon be allowed to operate on
``commercial basis'' for the first time since it was founded in
1969.
 &UR; ___
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ The Cabinet approved Sunday the building of a new
city in Subiya, about 40 kilometers (25 miles) from the Iraqi
border, a mega project that would reportedly cost around 1.8
billion dinars (dlrs 5.9 billion).
	   A statement by the Cabinet said the government has decided to
expand the country's populated areas ``toward the north.'' The new
city will be connected with the capital, Kuwait City, by a bridge
across Kuwait bay. It said Subiya would house around 250,000 people
in the coming 30 years. Kuwait's population is estimated at 2.2
million, less than 800,000 of them are Kuwaiti nationals.
	   Subiya City will have an industrial area, a university,
technical colleges, ports and its own power station, the statement
said. It will be built by the private sector in association with
international companies, the government said.
	   The cabinet did not say what would be the cost of the city, but
a government report published by Al-Qabas daily in August, put it
at 1.8 billion dinars (dlrs 5.9 billion).
	   Iraq invaded this small oil-rich state eight years ago and
occupied it for seven months before a U.S.-led coalition drove
Iraqi troops out in February 1991.
 &UR; buros-sf
</TEXT>
