<SLUG> BC-Italy-Politics, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Italian Communists vote to yank support for Prodi
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: COMBINES previous; ADDs possible scenarios &QL; 
 &UR; With AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By FRANCES D'EMILIO
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Italy's Communists on Sunday voted to withdraw
support for Premier Romano Prodi's 2 1-2-year-old coalition, a move
that could trigger the collapse of one of the country's
longest-lived postwar governments.
	   There was no immediate reaction from the government, but Prodi
has said he would call a confidence vote if the Communists yanked
support. The coalition has a majority without the Communists in the
Senate, but counts on them for a majority in the Chamber.
	   A confidence vote could be scheduled in the next few days.
	   If Prodi fails to muster a majority in the chamber, he would be
forced to resign and new elections could be called.
	   Or President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro could ask Prodi to try to
muster a coalition majority, possibly from centrists now in the
opposition and from Communists unhappy with their party leader's
decision.
	   Defying other top Communist Refoundation officials, Fausto
Bertinotti, party secretary, defended his strategy to break away,
saying he was betting that a new government would be more leftist.
	   The Communists' No. 2, Armando Cossutta, had argued against
Bertinotti's plan, insisting it would be better to work with he
government for a 1999 budget that would devote more funds to job
creation and to continue backing the government.
	   A split left, Oliviero Diliberto, the Communist Chamber whip
feared, would only help the center-right opposition, led by
ex-premier Silvio Berlusconi, who has been pressing for early
elections. However, despite his dissent with Bertinotti, Diliberto
said he follow his party leader's decision.
	   Bertinotti's motion garnered 188 votes from the party's national
political committee to 112 for Cossutta's.
	   Prodi's coalition has outlived all but two of Italy's other 54
postwar governments.
	   In the past, political crises in a country known for ``revolving
door'' governments have sometimes taken weeks or months to resolve.
	   But any call for new elections, with their 60-day campaign
period, would have to come almost immediately soon.
	   Elections are avoided in what is known as the ``white semester''
-- the last six months of a presidential term, which would begin
for Scalfaro in January -- because the president is elected by
parliament and any vote for a new head of state would likely be
affected by campaigning for parliamentary seats.
	   (fd)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
