<SLUG> BC-Russia-Oil </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Oil to flow again from Far Eastern refinery
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Oil will soon begin flowing again from a Russian
refinery that had been idled for 10 days after the railways
insisted on pre-payment for shipping, the ITAR-Tass news agency
reported Sunday.
	   The East Siberian Railway had refused to ship oil without a cash
payment in advance. However, the refinery in Khabarovsk, about 6100
kilometers (3,800 miles) southeast of Moscow, did not have enough
cash on hand to pay 30-35 million rubles (dlrs 1.8-2.2 million) a
month for the shipments, ITAR-Tass said.
	   The Sidanko company, which owns the refinery, has agreed to pay
a 322 million ruble (dlrs 20.7 million) debt to the railway, said
refinery manager Nikolai Shalvin. He said this would be considered
a ``preliminary payment'' for oil shipments and guarantee shipment
of 150,000 metric tons of crude oil to the refinery every month,
ITAR-Tass said.
	   (ji) 	   
</TEXT>
