<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Brotherhood </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police detain 4 suspected Muslim Brotherhood activists
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Police detained four men suspected of
belonging to the outlawed Muslim Brotherhood on Sunday and accused
them of attempting to promote the movement.
	   The detentions occurred in the Imbaba neighborhood of Cairo,
police said. Those detained included an engineer, a teacher, a
banker and a university student, they said.
	   The police said the men were not immediately charged.
	   Although officially banned, the Brotherhood was long tolerated
by the government. But the government began a sweeping crackdown in
1995 after accusing the group of supporting Islamic militants.
	   Muslim extremists have waged a campaign of violence since the
spring of 1992 to try to overthrow Egypt's secular government and
install strict Islamic rule.
	   The Brotherhood advocates an Islamic state, but says violence is
not the way to realize it.
