<SLUG> BC-Britain-Interest Rate </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Treasury chief hints he wants Britain to lower interest rate
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With US-Financial Crisis

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Saying recession is now a bigger threat than
inflation, Britain's Treasury chief, Gordon Brown, hinted Sunday
that British interest rates should come down, but stressed he will
leave the decision to the Bank of England.
	   ``A few days ago the Federal Reserve lowered their interest
rates, Canada lowered their interest rates, the Bank of England
itself has said that the balance of risk has shifted,'' Chancellor
of the Exchequer Brown said.
	   Brown spoke in a British Broadcasting Corp. interview from
Washington where finance ministers and central bank governors from
the world's richest nations, the Group of Seven, discussed the
global financial crisis.
	   They are considering a U.S. proposal to allow the International
Monetary Fund to provide extra money quickly to countries
threatened with a flight of investors.
	   Prime Minister Tony Blair's Labor government yielded authority
to set interest rates to the Bank of England soon after its
election victory in May 1997. The bank has tightened monetary
policy, leading to protests from manufacturers about the high value
of the British pound making exports expensive and too high interest
rates.
	   The Bank of England is due to announce Thursday its latest
decision on interest rates. There is speculation it will cut the
rate from 7.50 percent rate to 7.25 percent.
	   Earlier, in an interview with Britain's GMTV channel, Brown
said, ``But of course the balance of risk has shifted. We've got
low inflation round the world and the Bank of England will make
their decisions in the light of these facts.''
	   (mj)
</TEXT>
