w1817 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 1stLd-Writethru   10-04 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru,0577 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian delegation meets Milosevic as NATO threatens strikes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Russians meeting Milosevic, report of Britain
preparing ground troops for Kosovo, new Tass report; TRIMS. CHANGES
byline  &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos BEL101-102
 &UR; By MISHA SAVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Reacting to the threat of a NATO
strike on Yugoslavia, Russia's defense and foreign ministers called
on President Slobodan Milosevic on Sunday, while Yugoslav generals
prepared to defend the country.
	   Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev
met with Milosevic and Milan Milutinovic, president of Serbia, the
dominant Yugoslav republic controlling Kosovo.
	   Despite Russia's opposition, NATO is preparing for possible
intervention in Serbia's southern province to end seven months of
bloodshed. Russia is the Serbs' main ally, sharing bonds of
religion, and joint Slavic roots.
	   There was no official confirmation of the surprise meeting and
no word of its substance, but news photographers captured the
meeting on film.
	   In Moscow, Itar-Tass carried a government statement again
expressing opposition to any NATO intervention in Kosovo without
the sanction of the U.N. Security Council, of which Russia is a
veto-carrying member.
	   ``Military interference ... would aggravate many times the
confrontation in Kosovo and undermine diplomatic efforts'' to
reestablish peace and dialogue, said the statement.
	   Preparing for any attack, Yugoslav generals put the nation's air
defense on high alert, even as Serbian authorities indicated they
were ready for compromise by installing an interim government in
the rebellious Serbian province. A Western diplomat also said that
up to 120 Yugoslav army armored vehicles, including tanks, have
been pulled out of Kosovo so far.
	   The West apparently remained unmoved.
	   Speaking in Copenhagen, Denmark, German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel said Friday that the NATO intervention clock ``is at one
minute to 12.'' He stressed that ``no ultimatum, no date has been
set,'' but added: ``Mr. Milosevic must know that we are serious.''
	   London's Sunday Times reported that Britain was preparing ground
troops and armored units for Kosovo. The defense ministry refused
to confirm or deny the report but repeated Britain was ready to
participate in a NATO attack.
	   The Yugoslav government said Friday the fighting had ended and
blamed continuing violence on ethnic Albanian rebels. Serbian
police and the Yugoslav army have routed separatist Kosovo Albanian
rebels in a seven-month crackdown. The conflict has killed hundreds
_ most of them Albanian civilians _ and left upward of 275,000
villagers refugees.
	   Ethnic Albanian political leaders rejected the interim council,
drawn up without their consultation with them, and made up of seven
Serbs, five ethnic Albanians, and other minorities.
	   Constituting the council, moribund since 1989, was part of a
last-ditch effort to show that Serbs intend to end the conflict.
U.N. chief Kofi Annan plans to report Monday to the Security
Council on whether Belgrade is complying with demands to halt its
assault on ethnic Albanians. If not, Washington has indicated that
NATO air strikes will follow within two weeks.
	   Momentum for outside involvement has increased in the past week
amid revelations of massacres of ethnic Albanian civilians in the
forests of Kosovo. 	   
</TEXT>
