<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sudan-Talks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Talks on southern Sudan war canceled
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CHEGE MBITIRU &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ The latest round of talks to seek ways of
ending southern Sudan civil war were canceled because the Sudanese
government declined to send representatives, a rebel official said
Sunday.
	   ``As far as we know, there are not talks tomorrow because
Khartoum is not sending anybody,'' said Justin Atop Yaac, a
spokesman for the Sudan People's Liberation Army.
	   The talks were scheduled to begin in the Kenyan capital,
Nairobi, Monday under the auspices of the regional
Intergovernmental Authority on Development.
	   Arop said the rebels had been informed of the cancellation by
authorities in Kenya, which was to host the talks. Officials in the
foreign ministry could not be reached for comment.
	   It was impossible to get a comment from Khartoum, but government
troops and the rebels have been fighting since Sept. 14 in the
southern province of East Eduatoria.
	   Khartoum accuses the rebels of launching an offensive to try and
capture the provincial town of Juba, about 1,200 kilometers (744
miles) south of Khartoum. Rebels say they attacked government
positions because the Sudanese air force was bombing civilian
targets in rebel-held areas.
	   Juba is the largest town in southern Sudan still in government
control.
	   The cancellation of the talks have dashed hopes among aid
agencies and donors that a three-month cease-fire to facilitate aid
program would be extended. The cease-fire expires Oct. 15.
	   Last month, the European Union said it hoped the cease-fire
would not only be extended but also expanded to cover other
provinces where aid, mostly food, is needed.
	   The government says the cease-fire applies to all of the south,
while the rebels insist it is restricted only to Bahr al-Ghazal, a
southwestern province where famine is concentrated.
	   Hunger is a persistent problem in southern Sudan, where the
15-year civil war often has led to famine because rebels or
government-backed militia burn or steal crops that their enemy or
civilians rely on. About 1.5 million people have died in the
fighting and famines.
	    &UR; (CM)
</TEXT>
