<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Politics, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Germany's Social Democrats and Greens plan for new government
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RAISES reference to gas tax, Washington trip; tightens &QL; 
 &UR; By PAUL GEITNER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ Germany's new Social Democratic-led
government will repeal cuts in pensions passed by Chancellor Helmut
Kohl before they take effect Jan. 1, a party leader said Sunday.
	   In an interview with German radio, parliamentary faction leader
Rudolf Scharping said his party will also ``immediately'' implement
another campaign promise: repealing a 1996 law allowing employers
to cut sick pay by 20 percent.
	   But Germans may still not end up with more money in their
pockets.
	   In a separate interview, Chancellor-elect Gerhard Schroeder said
he would support a rise in the gasoline tax _ although not as much
as his likely coalition partners, the Greens, would like.
	   Meanwhile, in a sign that Schroeder may have settled on a
foreign minister, Greens party leader Joschka Fischer is to
accompany Schroeder when he visits President Bill Clinton in
Washington on Thursday.
	   In his interview with Bild am Sonntag, Schroeder declined to
comment on personnel questions, other than to repeat that he wanted
union leader Walter Riester as Labor Minister.
	   But he said everything would be wrapped up in time so that he
can be sworn in as chancellor on Oct. 27.
	   Cuts in retirement benefits and sick pay were part of the modest
economic reforms pushed through parliament by Kohl, who lost his
bid for a fifth term last month to the Social Democrats.
	   Germany's double-digit unemployment was the main campaign issue,
and in coalition talks that opened Friday, Schroeder and the
ecology-minded Greens party set combating it as their top priority.
	   While no talks were held over the weekend, all sides continued
staking out positions.
	   Industry leaders warned they would leave Schroeder's proposed
roundtable on job creation if unions insist on a shorter work week
or too-high wages.
	   Hans Peter Stihl, chairman of the German Chamber of Industry and
Commerce, told Bild am Sonntag that some proposals being considered
by the future center-left government would actually lead to ``a
renewed climb in unemployment.''
	   Those include raising energy taxes, canceling a high-speed train
link between Berlin and Hamburg, and shutting down the country's
nuclear power reactors, he said.
	   Schroeder warned against setting conditions ahead of talks.
	   But asked about Green proposals for a higher gasoline tax,
Schroeder said he would accept an increase of no more than 6
pfennig (4 cents) per liter, not the 30 pfennig (18 cents) some
Greens have demanded.
	   Greens leader Juergen Trittin refused to comment on specifics at
a mini party convention Sunday.
	   But Fischer, considered more of a pragmatist than Trittin, said
it was time to move from old ideals to ``professional
negotiating.''
	   Noting that the Greens actually lost votes this year compared
with the 1994 election, Fischer blamed ``exaggerated'' proposals
like raising the price of gas long-term to 5 marks a liter (dlrs 12
a gallon).
	   ``We almost pushed ourselves over the precipice,'' he said,
calling for party unity as coalition talks progress.
	   Car-crazy Germans also got bad news from the Greens' transport
expert, Gila Altmann. The Koelner Zeitung quoted her as saying that
the new center-left government may support setting a speed limit of
120-130 kph (75-80 mph) on Germany's autobahns.
 &UR; (pfg)
</TEXT>
