<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dissidents say Clinton administration pledges anti-Saddam funds
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Newspaper name Kurdistan Niwe in 6th graf is CQ. &QL; 
 &UR; By SALAH NASRAWI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Iraqi dissidents said Sunday that Clinton
administration officials have promised to agree to financial aid to
groups trying to oust Iraqi President Saddam Hussein.
	   The dissidents, who had talks with senior U.S. officials in
Washington recently, said the officials informed them the
administration would not oppose a Republican proposal to fund
opposition groups. They spoke on condition of anonymity.
	   The White House in the past has opposed direct aid to the Iraqi
opposition on the grounds it could lead to further U.S.
obligations. The groups themselves also prefer covert assistance
that would not openly identify them as U.S.-backed.
	   Republican congressmen introduced legislation last month to
authorize President Clinton to give dlrs 97 million to Iraqi
opposition groups and dlrs 2 million to Radio Free Iraq.
	   The bill has some Democratic support. Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, Republican of Mississippi, who introduced the Iraq
Liberation Act, said he consulted with the administration in
drawing up the measure.
	   Kurdistan Niwe, published by the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan
guerrilla group, reported in its Monday edition that the
administration has promised to approve the legislation. A copy of
the paper was sent Sunday to The Associated Press in Cairo.
	   The paper said the administration informed Massoud Barazani,
leader of the Kurdistan Democratic Party, and Patriotic Union
leader Jalal Talabani about its plans on funding opposition groups.
They spoke on condition their names not be used.
	   The two Kurdish leaders, frequent rivals, signed a
reconciliation accord in Washington last month after holding talks
with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and National Security
Adviser Sandy Berger.
	   The CIA aided Iraqi resistance groups after the 1991 Gulf War,
and Congress earlier approved some humanitarian and political
support for Kurdish and other opposition groups operating outside
Iraq.
	   Iraq condemned the legislation last Wednesday, saying that
Washington will be wasting money and effort if it tried to oust
regime.
 &UR; var/eap
</TEXT>
