w1836 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Lebanon-ArabDream     10-04 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Arab Dream </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Half million people sing of Arab unity in politicized concert
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo available
 &UR; By JOSEPH PANOSSIAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ In the Arab world's biggest sing-along,
at least half a million people joined in chorus with 23 top singers
in a concert more about politics than Arab pop music's usual fare
of love and romance.
	   The show Saturday night in Beirut's main square was a live
version of a video cassette called ``The Arab Dream,'' fittingly so
since its theme _ unity of the Arabs _ is belied by the persistent
ruptures among their leaders.
	   In the video, the plea for Arab unity is accompanied by
emotional old newsreels from the Arabs' long battle with Israel _
Palestinians fleeing their homes at the founding of the Jewish
state in 1948 and Lebanese pulling bodies from wreckage left by
Israeli artillery.
	   Some Gulf satellite outlets say they're getting dozens of
requests to show ``The Arab Dream,'' since the video has been
distributed only to TV stations and many viewers want to tape it.
It's shown several times a day on Beirut stations.
	   Despite its political theme, Saturday's concert had its pop
aspects. Performers from 16 Arab countries included such
heartthrobs as Tunisia's Latifa, Egypt's Anoushka and Kadhem
al-Saher of Iraq.
	   But the show's climax was ``The Arab Dream,'' with each of the
singers doing one stanza, and audience and performers joining in
the refrain about Arab unity.
	   ``The darkness of the night may have separated us. A beam of
light can carry us to the farthest skies. This has always been our
dream, one nation to embrace us all,'' goes the song.
	   ``The Arab Dream'' was written to ``gently prod Arab leaders
through art to ... convene a summit meeting,'' said Rabeh Ayyoub,
spokesman for the organizers of Saturday's concert. The last Arab
summit was in 1990 when Iraq's invasion of Kuwait split the Arab
world into pro- and anti-Iraq camps.
	   Ayyoub said the ``darkness'' in the lyrics refers to ``the
current Arab state of affairs ... the failure to take collective
action after 50 years since the establishment of Israel.''
	   At the concert, there were no old film clips but plenty of
emotion. Beirut radio stations estimated 500,000 to one million
people crowded into or around Martyr's Square. The show started two
hours late after scuffles broke out as police held back the vast
crowds pushing toward the stage.
	   Some in the audience carried placards of late Egyptian president
Gamal Abdel Nasser, who was a symbol of Arab unity. Others shouted
slogans and waved the flags of various Arab nations and the
Palestinians.
	   ``The Arab Dream,'' written by poets Midhat el-Adl of Egypt and
Salem Seif al-Khaledi of the United Arab Emirates, was made into a
video last August. The video and Beirut concert were organized by
Ahmed el-Aryan, an Egyptian-Palestinian who lives in the Emirates.
	   Despite the song's theme of unity, divisions showed up at the
concert.
	   Iraqi singer al-Saher does not appear in the cassette, and some
sources say that's because of fears the popular Kuwait singer Nabil
Shuail would refuse to join in if al-Saher was included.
	   The Iraqi sang Saturday night. Just before the concert, it was
announced the Kuwaiti would not appear.
 &UR; jp-fsa-ggl
</TEXT>
