<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cycling-World Championships </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Drugs, Tour de France still Plague World Championships
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SALVATORE ZANCA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VALKENBURG, Netherlands (AP) - The World Cycling Championships
begin this week with repercussions from the Tour de France still
plaguing the sport both on and off the road.
	   The Tour de France may have ended more than two months ago, yet
the aftermath of the drug scandal still is present with revelations
still coming out. Even this past week, the Festina masseur that
started the scandal when he was picked up with drugs in a team car,
added more details of the team procedures that led to the Festina
team being kicked out of the Tour.
	   The International Cycling Union will hold a congress before the
road events begin on Tuesday. The UCI will have its hands full
dealing with the aftermath of the drug scandal and will look to
implement new procedures to curb doping in its sport.
	   There will be 10 races through Sunday. The top races are the
ones with the elite men and women with the men's road race
finishing the championships Sunday.
	   Yet the Tour de France has taken its toll on the participants in
various ways.
	   Laurent Jalabert of France, last year's time trial champion,
pulled out of the championship citing physical and psychological
fatigue.
	   Jalabert was a leader of a protest of the Tour de France in the
initial days of the drug scandal when the riders refused to start a
stage over the handling of the riders by the media and
organization.
	   The Frenchman was one of the first riders to drop out of the
Tour. He has since described the International Cycling Union as a
``dictatorship'' and its commissioners as ``half Dracula and half
neo-Nazi.'' The UCI threatened to ban Jalabert unless he
apologized.
	   Yet Jalabert said his decision to withdraw had nothing to do
with the ultimatum of UCI president Hein Verbruggen.
	   Last year's road champion, Laurent Brochard of France and the
1996 time trial champion, Alex Zuelle of Switzerland are not
competing after they admitted taking banned substances as members
of the Festina team.
	   The UCI must also deal with the relatively light sentences
handed down by the Swiss Federation.
	   Zuelle, Laurent Dufaux and Armin Meier were banned eight months
and fined 3,000 Swiss francs (dlrs 2,164). With the suspensions
effective immediately, the racers will miss only a few of the
important races and could be back racing in the Tour de France next
year.
	   Although the riders confessed to taking drugs, which can be
viewed as a positive drug test in other federations and a longer
ban, UCI rules only a suspension between six months and a year.
	   The UCI will meet to decide whether to accept the ban by the
Swiss Federation or change it.
	   On the road, the world championships will also be missing other
top riders not caught in any drug taking, including the last three
Tour de France winners.
	   Marco Pantani of Italy who had a double victory in the Tour of
Italy and the Tour de France this season, virtually shut down his
season except for a few money-making criteriums.
	   Jan Ullrich of Germany, second to Pantani and 1997 Tour winner,
dropped out with an Achilles tendon problem while Bjarne Riis of
Denmark, the 1996 Tour winner, also is not competing.
	   With the world men's road title a one-day ride instead of a
grueling multi-stage race, the most prestigious title could go to
people such as Michele Bartoli of Italy or a come-backing Lance
Armstrong of the United States.
	   Armstrong, who won the 1993 world title, is rebounding after a
year off to recuperate from testicular cancer. Just before the
world championships in 1996 he revealed he had it but came back to
cme in fourth in the recent Tour of Spain.
	   The junior women begin the competition with its road race on
Tuesday with the elite women's time trial on Wednesday the first
major race.
	   (sz)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
