<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Kurdish Rebels, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With BC-Syria-Turkey and BC-Israel-Turkey-Syria
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Demirel: Turkey in position of self-defense against Syria &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS with Turkish president quotes, ADDS background,
photoline, CHANGES byline &QL; 
 &UR; With AP Photo &QL; 
 &UR; By HARMONIE TOROS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ Turkey is in a position of self-defense
against Syria and is warning Damascus to stop supporting Kurdish
rebels, President Suleyman Demirel said Sunday.
	   ``I am not only warning Syria, I am warning the world. This
cannot continue,'' Demirel was quoted as saying by the
semi-official Anatolia news agency.
	   Ankara claims that Turkish Kurdish rebels, who wage cross-border
raids from camps in Iraq, Iran and Syria, are sheltered by Syrian
authorities. Damascus denies the charges.
	   ``We are in a position of self-defense .... The situation is
serious. Turkey has suffered for many years, and it no longer wants
to suffer,'' Demirel said.
	   The war in Turkey's southeast waged by rebels seeking autonomy
for the country's large Kurdish minority, has killed more than
37,000 people since 1984.
	   Turkey in the past few days sent about 10,000 soldiers into
northern Iraq to attack Kurdish rebel bases there.
	   Ankara has indicated it might send forces into Syria to
eradicate guerrilla bases there.
	   Hurriyet newspaper last week quoted the commander of Turkish
land forces, Gen. Atilla Ates, as saying: ``Our patience has run
out. We are determined to take all necessary measures if we don't
see any response to our goodwill.''
	   On Saturday, reports said Turkish jets buzzed the Syrian border
and Defense Minister Ismet Sezgin said would soon carry out
military exercises near the Syrian border, private television NTV
reported.
	   But Sezgin insisted Sunday that war was the last resort. ``I
don't believe it will come to that,'' he said.
	   Fueling tension between the two countries are Turkey and
Israel's expanding military and diplomatic ties. Syria claims the
ties are a threat to the Arab world, and on Saturday, Damascus
again accused Turkey of plotting with Israel to undermine Syria.
	   ``We have no part in this tension,'' Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu said Sunday.
	   In an effort to head off a military conflict, Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak held talks Sunday with Syrian President Hafez Assad
in Damascus.
	   Mubarak was initially expected in Ankara on Monday, but due to a
full schedule in Cairo he may be forced to postpone his visit to
midweek, sources said.
	   Turkish newspaper headlines reflected rising tensions in Turkey.
	   ``Critical Days,'' wrote daily Turkiye, while the daily Aksam
claimed that Turkish forces could reach the Syrian-controlled Bekaa
Valley in Lebanon, where Turkey claims there are rebel camps, in 30
minutes.
	   ``War is coming,'' said Kenan Kalelioglu, an engineer in Ankara.
``If the Syrians continue to support anarchy, Turkey will have to
act. We don't like war, but we are not afraid.''
	   (ht-fd)
</TEXT>
