<HEADLINE>
RETRANSMITSPeslier, on Sagamix, wins third successive Arc de
</HEADLINE>
Triomphe &QL; 
 &UR; EDS: ADDS details, updates and quotes throughout &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ French jockey Olivier Peslier, riding Sagamix, won
his third successive Arc de Triomphe on Sunday, after holding off a
persistent challenge by Leggera.
	   Sagamix, at 2/1, took the lead going in to the final straight
after Happy Valentine had held the lead in the early stages.
	   The colt won by a neck from 11/1-shot Leggera, ridden by Richard
Quinn, which briefly was in first place before Sagamix strode
powerfully to the front 200 meters (yards) from the finish.
	   In the 14-horse race, run over a 2,400-meter (1 1/2 mile) course
at Longchamps, Tiger Hill, at 8/1, came in third.
	   Sagamix, now unbeaten in four races, finished in an unofficial
time of 2 minutes, 34 seconds.
	   It started as favorite after winning the Prix Niel, the main Arc
de Triomphe trial, three weeks ago.
	   Peslier, who tasted glory at the Arc de Triomphe on Helissio
(1996) and Peintre Celebre (1997), has now recorded three straight
wins at Europe's most prestigious race - equalling Pat Eddery's
record hattrick between 1985 and 1987.
	   ``The race started slowly and then my horse accelerated well,''
Peslier said after the race.
	   The win also gives trainer Andre Fabre his fifth win at the Arc.
	   ``The horse was well-prepared for the race by the whole team,''
said Sagamix's owner Jean-Luc Lagardere. ``He showed an absolutely
extraordinary heart. A horse runs with his legs...but can only win
with his heart.''
	   Sagamix's victory rounds off a fine season for Peslier.
	   In June, Peslier won the English Derby, Europe's other showpiece
horse race, on High-Rise, which never challenged strongly in
Sunday's race.
	   (ae)
