r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Tennis-GrandSl     10-04 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Grand Slam Cup </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rios overcomes painful back to beat Agassi in five sets
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NESHA STARCEVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MUNICH, Germany (AP) _ Marcelo Rios overcame back problems and
beat Andre Agassi in five sets Sunday to win the Grand Slam Cup and
grab the richest prize in tennis, dlrs 1.3 million.
	   Rios, who looked like he would quit early in the match, finally
prevailed in two hours, 55 minutes, winning 6-4, 2-6, 7-6 (7-1),
5-7, 6-3.
	   Agassi at the end seemed to be worn out by nearly seven hours of
tennis in two days.
	   The American, who is No. 8 in the world, had not met the
qualifying standard but was given a wild card in an attempt to give
some luster to the men's field, which lacked No. 1 Pete Sampras and
No. 2 Pete Rafter.
	   Agassi had to settle for the runner-up prize of dlrs 650,000.
	   The dlrs 6.7 million tournament nominally brings together
players with the best records in the four Grand Slam events of the
year _ the Australian, French and U.S. Open and Wimbledon.
	   But three of the men's Grand Slam champions elected not to show
up.
	   Rios, the highest-ranked player in he event at No. 3, was in
pain early in the match. He was given a massage by a trainer after
the third game, then dropped his serve on a double-fault in the
fifth.
	   This time, he took an injury time-out and was stretched on the
floor for a couple of minutes while the trainer worked on his back.
Rios also took some painkillers.
	   Back in the match, Rios immediately broke Agassi to level the
score. In the next game, he hit two aces in holding serve at love.
	   Rios broke Agassi's serve to win the set, hitting a spectacular
running backhand passing shot on his second set point.
	   Double-faults by Rios on game points in the first and seventh
allowed Agassi to serve for the second set. He wasted one set point
with a double-fault of his own, but hit a forehand winner to the
corner on the next.
	   Although he lost the set, Rios produced one of its highlights:
winning a point while sitting on the floor after slipping and
falling on the hard-court surface.
	   Rios was devastating on his serve in the third set, winning five
of six games at love, although he used several changeovers to
stretch and get more massage.
	   Wincing with pain nearly every time he made a shot, the Chilean
still used the full range of his extraordinary talent to baffle
Agassi.
	   Agassi saved two set points to hold serve for 5-5 and the set
went into a tiebreaker. Rios raced to a 6-1 lead and won the set
when Agassi hit a backhand long.
	   But Rios was not so error-free in the next set and twice had two
stave off break points.
	   He fell into a 0-40 hole while serving to stay in the set,
hitting a weak volley straight at Agassi that the American turned
into a passing shot winner.
	   Rios saved one set point with an ace, but then hit a backhand
into the net off a powerful return by Agassi.
	   Agassi fell a break down in the fifth, only to break right back.
The Chilean then broke Agassi's serve again to go up 3-2.
	   Serving to save the match, Agassi produced a double-fault to
give Rios three match points. Agassi saved one, but then committed
another double-fault to surrender.
	   Agassi needed three hours, 40 minutes to beat Karol Kucera in
the semifinals. Rios beat Mark Philippoussis in three quick sets.
	   (ns)	   
</TEXT>
