<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cycling-Worlds-Armstrong </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
From being a sentimental favorite, in form Armstrong is now real
</HEADLINE>
contender &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Sports-Cycling-World Championships. &QL; 
 &UR; By MIKE CORDER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VALKENBURG, Netherlands (AP) _ Two weeks ago, American Lance
Armstrong was a sentimental favorite to win the World Cycling
Championships' top event, the elite men's road race. But after
landing fourth place in the recent Tour of Spain, he's suddenly a
genuine title contender.
	   ``The people who did well at the Tour of Spain are in race
condition for the World,'' Armstrong said. ``I will be in good race
condition,'' for Sunday's 258-kilometer (162-mile) road race.
	   ``I think my condition is better than ever before.''
	   Armstrong won the road racing world title in 1993 but then saw
his career _ and his life _ threatened by testicular cancer that
spread to his brain and lungs. Chemotherapy has now driven the
disease into remission, allowing the resilient 27-year-old Texan to
restart his career.
	   His challenge for the world title is helped by a long list of
absentees from the championships, which start Tuesday and climax
Sunday with the road race on the hilly roads in and around this
southern Dutch town.
	   Reigning road champion Laurent Brochard of France is not racing
after admitting taking banned substances as members of the
disgraced Festina team. Missing for the same reason is 1996 time
trial champion Alex Zuelle of Switzerland.
	   Also out of the running are reigning Tour de France titlist
Marco Pantani of Italy, 1997 Tour winner Jan Ullrich of Germany and
Bjarne Riis of Denmark, who won the tour in 1996.
	   Bobby Julich, third this year in the Tour also announced this
week he was dropping out because he was unfit after a grueling
season. And Frenchman Laurnet Jalabert, last year's time trial
champion, is out following a dispute with cycling's world governing
body.
	   Armstrong picked Italy's Michele Bartoli and Denmark's Rolf
Sorensen as possible winners, but admitted he also considers
himself a contender on a course which he believes favors him.
	   ``It is very much a classic course,'' Armstrong said. ``Very
difficult, long and (with) short, steep climbs. I have heard it
described as a puncher's course. The course suits me very well.''
	   (mc/sz)	   
</TEXT>
