<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Nepal-Asian Cricket </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Malaysia wins 1st match of 10-nation ACC cricket tournament
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) _ Malaysia defeated the tiny Indian Ocean
island of Maldives on better run rate on a soggy ground Sunday
after their one-day match in the Asian Cricket Council tournament
was abandoned midway due to rain.
	   A second match between Thailand and Nepal was washed out due to
the rain. Both teams gained a point each.
	   Malaysia scored 156 runs for 9 wickets in 43.4 overs, with Rohan
Selvaratnam scoring 37 runs in 56 balls in the rain-marred match
reduced from 50 to 45 overs in Katmandu, the capital of this
Himalayan kingdom. Selvaratnam was run out on a throw by Ali Nihad.
	   Maldives' Ibrahim Hussain, who clean bowled three Malaysian
batsmen _ Mathew Williams, Captain Menon and M Muniandy _ was
declared man of the match. Hussain's team-mate Mohammad Shahid also
took three wickets.
	   After losing its first wicket at three runs, Maldives lost
wickets at regular intervals and was at 69 for four after 26 overs,
when officials decided to stop play saying the outfield was too
wet.
	   Malaysian captain Ramesh Menon, who was out for four runs in his
innings, took three wickets.
	   Malaysia took two points from the game and leads the other nine
teams in the tournament _ Bangladesh, Thailand, Papua New Guinea,
the Maldives, Singapore, United Arab Emirates, Hong Kong, Japan and
hosts Nepal.
	   On Saturday, all four matches were canceled due to rain and all
the eight teams awarded one points each. The final of the 10-nation
ACC trophy is scheduled for Oct. 13.
	   (bgj, nnm)
</TEXT>
