<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Terrorism </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turin investigators probe any links to bin-Laden group
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TURIN, Italy (AP) _ Investigators Sunday were trying to
determine if one of three men arrested here has links to Osama bin
Laden, the suspected mastermind of the U.S. embassy bombings in
Africa, the Italian news agency ANSA reported.
	   Earlier Sunday, RAI state radio reported that police were
seeking to learn if the trio, arrested a few days ago in this
northern city, might have been planning a terrorist attack here or
abroad.
	   Seized by police in a warehouse rented by the three were pistols
equipped with silenzers, an Uzi machine gun, ammunition, wigs,
radio transmitters and gold ingots, ANSA said.
	   Police first said that all three were Egyptian, but ANSA later
reported that investigators suspected that one of three might be
Yemenite, possibly a member of the Islamic Jihad terrorist group or
have links with bin Laden, who is a Saudi exile who from
Afghanistan allegedly runs al-Qaeda, a radical Islamic network
accused of orchestrating the bombings in Kenya and Tanzania last
August.
	   ANSA quoted investigators as saying that one of the men, an
Egyptian, had received several calls from London that had been
intercepted by Scotland Yard. The calls apparently came from a
suspected hideout in London linked to the embassy bombings, the
news report said.
	   A hearing for the men, being temporarily held on weapons
possession charges, was scheduled for Monday.
	   The head of Turin's anti-terrorism police squad, Antonio De
Santis, indicated the probe could widen, refusing to rule out
further arrests.
	   (fd)
</TEXT>
