<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lesotho </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Opposition leader says South Africa invaded because of water
</HEADLINE>
project &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MASERU, Lesotho (AP) _ An opposition leader accused South Africa
on Sunday of having invaded Lesotho to control a hydroelectric
project, not to quell a military mutiny as the neighboring country
has claimed.
	   South African troops acting on behalf of the Southern African
Development Community arrived in this impoverished kingdom on Sept.
22 and immediately engaged in combat with Lesotho soldiers _ both
mutineers and loyalists who thought they were being invaded.
	   Basotho National Party leader Thesele Maseribane said South
Africa's intervention was aimed at controlling the Highlands Water
Project, which is intended to provide Lesotho with electrical power
and South Africa, which surrounds Lesotho, with water.
	   At least 16 Lesotho soldiers were killed in firefights with
South African troops at Katse dam, which forms part of the
hydroelectric project and is about 35 miles (55 kilometers) outside
the capital.
	   Maseribane appealed to all political leaders to ensure that
royalties from the water project are paid to Lesotho, and used for
reconstruction of Maseru and other areas which were devastated in
an arson and looting spree that erupted during the military
intervention, the South African Press Association reported.
	   Maseribane made the accusation during the funeral of a
15-year-old BNP youth, Molahli Mokenele, who was killed when South
African troops stormed King Letsie III's palace on Sept. 22 to
remove opposition protesters.
	   The South African army, meanwhile, announced that one of its
soldiers was found dead with three bullet wounds in the back near a
military base outside Maseru. Authorities were investigating how
the soldier was killed.
	   The discovery on Saturday brings to 10 the number of South
African soldiers killed in the intervention, said Lt. Col. Laverne
Machine.
	   SADC-brokered talks on new elections for Lesotho were scheduled
to continue on Monday.
	   Opposition and ruling party officials tentatively agreed Friday
during the first day of talks that Lesotho would hold new elections
in 15 to 18 months. Opposition parties claim the previous elections
in May, which the ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy won by a
landslide, were rigged.
	   Monday's meeting was to focus on who would govern Lesotho in the
period leading up to the new elections.
	   (aos)
</TEXT>
