<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iran-Italy-Spain </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iranian parliament speaker heads for Italy, Spain
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ Iran's powerful parliament speaker left
Sunday for talks in Italy and Spain, the official Islamic Republic
News Agency reported.
	   Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri told reporters at the airport that the
purpose of his week-long trip is to discuss political issues and to
expand trade relations between Tehran and the two countries.
	   Nateq-Nouri, a leading hard-liner in the Iranian government,
will meet with a number of senior officials including Italian Prime
Minister Romano Prodi. In Spain he will meet with Prime Minister
Jose Maria Aznar and King Juan Carlos.
	   Nateq-Nouri's trip follows an announcement by the Iranian
government distancing itself from the death edict on British author
Salman Rushdie and the dlrs 2.5 million bounty placed on his head
in 1989 by a semi-official Iranian foundation.
	   The announcement last month by Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi
angered hard-liners.
	   Nateq-Nouri has not publicly commented on the government's
position but 150 members of the hard-line parliament he heads said
Sunday the death edict was irrevocable, Iranian television
reported.
	   ``As Majlis deputies, we assure Muslims all over the world that,
in this case, nothing except the decrees issued by God and
(Khomeini) in Iran have any credibility and no one has the power to
follow any other path,'' said the letter, the television reported.
	   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, the late Iranian leader, said that
Rushdie must die for blaspheming Islam in his novel ``The Satanic
Verses.''
	   The Rushdie affair strained ties with the European Union.
Moderate President Mohammad Khatami, who defeated Nateq-Nouri in
elections in 1997, has been trying to improve ties with the West
since he took office.
	   Tehran also wants to increase trade with Italy, its fourth
biggest trading partner. Trade between the two countries totaled
dlrs 2.3 billion last year.
 &UR; fsa-lm 	   
</TEXT>
