<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Italian Roundup </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Edmundo keeps Fiorentina winning streak alive
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By HOWARD FENDRICH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Gabriel Batistuta had a quiet day, but another of
Fiorentina's many weapons hit the target Sunday to keep the club
alone atop the Italian League.
	   Brazilian striker Edmundo scored his first goal of the Serie A
season off a nice exchange with Portuguese playmaker Rui Costa in
the third minute of injury time to lift Fiorentina past Udinese 1-0
for its fourth win in as many games.
	   Batistuta, an Argentine, and Udinese's Marcio Amoroso, a
Brazilian, entered the day tied for the league lead with five goals
apiece, but both were held in check.
	   Fiorentina, enjoying its first stay in first place since 1982,
has 12 points, two more than Internazionale of Milan (3-1-0), which
continues to thrive despite the lengthy absences of superstar
strikers Ronaldo and Roberto Baggio.
	   Chile's Ivan Zamorano and France's Youri Djorkaeff did the
damage Sunday in a 2-0 win over pesky Perugia 2-0.
	   Zamorano scored with a 12-meter (yard) shot 11 minutes into the
game, and Djorkaeff, a member of the World Cup champions, capped a
superb individual outing with an insurance goal off a short-range
header in the 54th.
	   German striker Oliver Bierhoff headed home his fifth goal of the
season just three minutes into AC Milan's 2-0 road win against
Venezia.
	   Milan, coming off back-to-back poor seasons, has nine points and
shares third place with Juventus of Turin. The two-time defending
champions rebounded from last week's loss to AC Parma by edging
Piacenza 1-0 on Filippo Inzaghi's early goal.
	   Elsewhere Sunday, Italian Cup holder Lazio of Rome finally
recorded its first win of the season, 2-0 over 10-man Cagliari; AC
Parma was shut out for the third time and drew 0-0 at Bologna;
Vicenza beat Bari 1-0; and Salernitana and Empoli drew 1-1.
Sampdoria of Genoa hosted AS Roma in the night match.
	   The fifth round of games will be in two weeks, because Italy's
national team plays a Euro 2000 qualifier against Switzerland next
Saturday.
	    &UR; MORE
</TEXT>
