<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cycling-Paris-Tours </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Durand holds off challenge from Gualdi to win Paris-Tours race
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With AP Photos

<TEXT>
	   TOURS, France (AP) _ Jacky Durand of France clinched the
Paris-Tours World Cup cycling race on Sunday after a winning a
sprint finish against Italian Mirco Gualdi.
	   Durand, who races for the Casino team, collects 100 World Cup
points for winning the 254 kilometer (141 mile) race from Paris to
Tours.
	   Gualdi, who rides for the Polti team, picks up 75 points.
	   In wet conditions, the two riders broke away from the pack two
kilometers from the end, and Durand powered away to become the
first French winner of the Paris-Tours race since Albert Bouvet's
victory in 1956.
	   Estonia's Jaan Kirsipuu, Durand's team mate, came third, 30
second behind the winner, ahead of Italians Stefano Zanini in
fourth and Nicola Minali in fifth.
	   Michele Bartoli, of the Asics team, could have regained his
World Cup title with a good finish on Sunday but didn't figure
among the leaders.
	   (parf-ae)
</TEXT>
