<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-British Roundup </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bergkamp scores twice in Arsenal 3-0 victory over Newcastle
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: WILL update at 1700 GMT with Liverpool-Chelsea &QL; 
 &UR; By STEPHEN WADE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Dutch international Dennis Bergkamp, without a
goal and still recovering from this summer's World Cup, broke out
and scored twice Sunday as defending league and cup champion
Arsenal defeated Newcastle 3-0 at the Gunners ground in north
London.
	   Bergkamp scored in the 21st off a pass from French interantional
Nicola Anekla. Eight minutes later, Bergkamp slipped a pass across
the front of the net as Anekla scored, and then got his second on a
penalty in the 66th.
	   The victory gave Arsenal 13 points and moved the Gunners into
third place _ pending a late match Sunday with Chelsea at
Liverpool. Arsenal trails Aston Villa (20 points) and Manchester
United (14).
	   On Saturday, Ian Taylor scored twice as Villa defeated
struggling Coventry 2-1, and Manchester United moved into second
with a 3-0 win at last-place Southampton with goals from Dwight
Yorke, Andy Cole and substitute Jordi Cruyff
	   Two days after leaving Leeds to coach Spurs, George Graham
watched his team score a 1-0 victory over Derby with England
defender Sol Campbell heading the only goal. David Pleat handled
the coaching as Graham prepares to take over.
	   Leeds tumbled 1-0 at home to Leicester, whose manager, Martin
O'Neill, is rumored to be taking over at Elland Road. Veteran
striker Tony Cottee scored the winner 14 minutes to play.
	   Middlesbrough moved up to 12 points with a 4-0 crushing of
Sheffield Wednesday. Danish forward Mikkel Beck scored twice with
the others from Colombian Hamilton Ricard and Paul Gascoigne.
	   Struggling Blackburn gained a 3-0 victory over high-flying West
Ham with two goals from Gary Flitcroft.
	   Charlton's first away win came 1-0 at Nottingham Forest through
defender Eddie Youds, and Everton came from behind at Wimbledon to
win 2-1 on strikes by Danny Cadamarteri and Duncan Ferguson.
	   Also on Saturday, Huddersfield moved two points clear in
division one with a 2-0 victory over Oxford United while Sunderland
was held 0-0 at home by Bradford. On Sunday, West defeated Watford
4-1.
	   Kilmarnock opened up a one-point lead in the Scottish Premier
League Saturday but should have made it three after being held 0-0
at home by Dunfermline.
	   Rangers played Dundee at home Sunday and would move into first
with a victory.
	   (scw)	   
</TEXT>
