<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Equestrian-World Games </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New Zealand wins gold medals in team and individual three-day
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Blyth Tait won the individual gold medal and led the
New Zealand team to the victory in the three-day event at the 1998
World Equestrian Games Sunday.
	   Fellow New Zealander Mark Todd took the silver on Broadcast
News, while Sweden's Paula Tornquist on SAS Monaghan finished
third. Defending champion Vaughn Jeffreys, also from New Zealand,
was fourth.
	   After the event's final test, show jumping, Tait, on Ready
Teddy, had 43.4 penalties, compared to Todd's 44.2. Tornquist
finished with 45.6 penalties.
	   David O'Connor of The Plains, Va. scored the U.S. team best
result to finish sixth on Giltedge with 51.4 penalties. Kerry
Millikin of Westport, Mass., placed 15 on Out and About, and
two-time World champion Bruce Davidson of Unionsville, Pa. finished
21th on Heyday.
	   At the three-day event team competition, New Zealand claimed the
gold with a total of 137.6 penalties, while France finished second
with 182.8, and Britain took the bronze with 184.9.
	   The Americans, finished fourth with a total of 186.1 penalties.
	   At the Atlanta Olympics, Australia won, while the Americans
claimed the silver and New Zealand took the bronze.
	   The three-day event was held in Pratoni del Vivaro, 50
kilometers (30 miles) southeast of Rome, at a track inaugurated
during the Rome 1960 Olympic Games in the capital.
	   In the individual dressage, scheduled to finish later Sunday
with the event's final test, the Free Style, Isabel Werth of
Germany was atop the provisional standings.
	   (ar-fd)
</TEXT>
