<SLUG> BC-Britain-Kosovo, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Britain to deploy ground troops in Kosovo after NATO
</HEADLINE>
strikes &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: ADDS three grafs with marchers demand Milosevic be indicted as
a war criminal; no pickup &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Britain is planning to deploy several thousand
ground troops and tank unites in Kosovo following a NATO
bombardment of the Yugoslav province in reprisal for killings of
ethnic Albanians, The Sunday Telegraph reported.
	   Defense Secretary George Robertson refused to confirm or deny
the report. He reiterated Britain is ready to take part in a NATO
attack, saying ``cat and mouse tactics'' by Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic are unacceptable.
	   ``Our plans are not going to be disclosed to Slobodan Milosevic
on any program,'' Robertson said Sunday, asked about the news
report in a British Broadcasting Corp. television interview. ``But
I think you can take it that a whole series of options have been
worked through and that we are ready to move on them.''
	   The Sunday Telegraph said a Royal Marines rapid reaction force
is undergoing specialist training to operate in Kosovo, where Serb
forces are blamed for brutality against the ethnic Albanian
majority.
	   The marines' role after air strikes would be peacekeeping,
similar to that of the peacekeeping force in Bosnia, but the
British soldiers would be prepared to engage Serb troops directly
if necessary, The Sunday Telegraph said.
	   Britain has already announced it will on Monday send four more
groud-attack aircraft to a NATO base in southern Italy, doubling
the number of Royal Air Force planes there in readiness for an
attack on Kosovo.
	   Prime Minister Tony Blair's Cabinet meets Monday to approve
formally the use of force unless Milosevic halts the attacks on
ethnic Albanians and seeks a political settlement.
	   ``But it still remains to be seen by how much he is responding
and how long he is going to do it ... This time he can't get off
the hook with just cosmetics,'' said Robertson.
	   He added that sending a peacekeeping force to Kosovo after a
genuine cease-fire ``is part of the options that are available.''
	   ``What is clear is that Milosevic now recognizes that we mean
business and that's why he's moving with such speed at the
moment,'' he added.
	   Separately Sunday, some 500 people including human rights
activist Bianca Jagger and actor Corin Redgrave marched through
central London to demand that Milosevic be indicted as a war
criminal and tried in an international court.
	   ``The Serbian campaign in Kosovo has to be stopped and those
responsible for it brought to justice by the international
community,'' lawmaker John Austin said after marchers held a rally
in Trafalgar Square.
	   Ms. Jagger, 51, was held at gunpoint by Serb forces in Kosovo
this summer while filming a report for the British Broadcasting
Corp.
	   (mj-scl)
</TEXT>
