<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Drugs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Egyptian government-run magazine calls for legalizing marijuana
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ A columnist for a leading state-run magazine
urged the government on Sunday to lift its ban on the sale of
marijuana, saying that legal efforts had failed to stop sales of
the drug.
	   Mohammed Shalan, a prominent psychologist who writes for Rose
El-Youssef magazine, said that for the ``law to be more practical
and more human it (the government) should abrogate the ban so that
the use of marijuana will not be illegal.''
	   Shalan wrote that marijuana, called bango in Egypt, is less
harmful than tobacco and liquor which are legal.
	   The use of hashish and marijuana is widespread in Egypt. The
government has estimated that some dlrs 3 billion a year are spent
on illegal drugs in Egypt.
	   Drug trafficking is punishable by death. Possession of marijuana
or hashish is punishable by a prison sentence that can vary from
months to years, depending on the quantity of the drugs seized and
whether the drug was for personal use or for sale.
 &UR; sn-lm 	   
</TEXT>
