w2053 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Belgium-AsylumPolicy     10-04 0312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Belgium-Asylum Policy,0311 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Goverment approves new asylum policy measures, protests continue
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RAF CASERT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ The Belgian government announced
changes to its asylum policy Sunday, including a ban on the use of
pillows to subdue deportees, two weeks after the death of a
Nigerian woman during a deportation attempt prompted outraged
protests.
	   The government rejected calls for a blanket amnesty for illegal
immigrants, and said forced deportations would continue once the
appeals process was exhausted.
	   ``Because of the dramatic death of Semira Adamu, there was an
urgent need for initiatives to make the policy more humane,'' said
Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene Sunday.
	   Adamu, 20, died in a Brussels hospital from a brain hemorrhage
two weeks ago, hours after police had stuffed a pillow over her
mouth to keep her on a plane about to depart for Africa.
	   Interior Minister Louis Tobback resigned over the incident, as
did the head of the police unit responsible for deporting Adamu.
	   Other changes announced by the center-left government include
greater outside control on conditions within refugee detention
centers; the creation of a special post of commissioner for refugee
issues; and allowing a committee more say in which asylum seekers
could stay.
	   The government move came against a background of sustained
protest against the current treatment of asylum seekers. On Sunday,
over 5,000 people protested in Liege, 100 kilometers (65 miles)
east of Brussels, demanding better trearment. The march was marred
by skirmishes between police and demonstrators.
	   Adamu resisted returning to Nigeria because she claimed her
family was forcing her to marry a 65-year-old man who already has
three wives. Belgium argued that was not sufficient to grant her
refugee status. 	   
</TEXT>
