<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-British Roundup, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bergkamp scores twice in Arsenal 3-0 victory over Newcastle
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS Bergkamp misses hat trick; Dabizas sent off for
Newcastle &QL; 
 &UR; By STEPHEN WADE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Dutch international Dennis Bergkamp scored his
first two goals of the season Sunday as league and cup champion
Arsenal defeated Newcastle 3-0 at the Gunners' ground in London and
moved into third behind Aston Villa and Manchester United.
	   In Sunday's other key match, Jamie Redknapp scored on a free
kick in the 83rd as Liverpool rallied for a 1-1 draw at home at
Anfield, leaving Chelsea with one win there in 39 matches.
Pierluigi Casiraghi's first goal of the season gave Chelsea a 1-0
lead in the 10th.
	   The free kick went in to the left of Chelsea goalkeeper Ed De
Goey, who was caught flat-footed and fooled by the hooking shot
from 20 meters (yards).
	   Aston Villa is the surprise league leader with 20 points to 14
for Manchester United and 13 for Arsenal. Six clubs have 12 points:
Middlesbrough, Derby, Wimbledon, West Ham, Liverpool and Chelsea.
	   Bergkamp _ the man of the day _ scored in the 21st off a pass
from French interantional Nicolas Anekla. Eight minutes later,
Bergkamp slipped a pass across the front of the net as Anekla
scored, and then got his second on a penalty in the 66th. He also
missed another that would have given him a hat trick.
	   Newcastle's Nikolaos Dabizas was sent off in the 65th.
	   On Saturday in the Premier League, Ian Taylor scored twice as
Villa defeated struggling Coventry 2-1, and Manchester United moved
into second with a 3-0 win at last-place Southampton with goals
from Dwight Yorke, Andy Cole and substitute Jordi Cruyff
	   Two days after leaving Leeds to coach Spurs, George Graham
watched his team score a 1-0 victory over Derby with England
defender Sol Campbell heading the only goal. David Pleat handled
the coaching as Graham prepares to take over.
	   Leeds tumbled 1-0 at home to Leicester, whose manager, Martin
O'Neill, is rumored to be taking over at Elland Road. Veteran
striker Tony Cottee scored the winner 14 minutes to play.
	   Middlesbrough moved up to 12 points with a 4-0 crushing of
Sheffield Wednesday. Danish forward Mikkel Beck scored twice with
the others from Colombian Hamilton Ricard and Paul Gascoigne.
	   Struggling Blackburn gained a 3-0 victory over high-flying West
Ham with two goals from Gary Flitcroft.
	   Charlton's first away win came 1-0 at Nottingham Forest through
defender Eddie Youds, and Everton came from behind at Wimbledon to
win 2-1 on strikes by Danny Cadamarteri and Duncan Ferguson.
	   Also on Saturday, Huddersfield moved two points clear in
division one with a 2-0 victory over Oxford United while Sunderland
was held 0-0 at home by Bradford. On Sunday, West defeated Watford
4-1.
	   In Scotland on Sunday, Rangers moved into first place with a 1-0
as Jorg Albertz scored in the 79th. Rangers have 18 points to 16
for Kilmarnock. Celtic and Hearts have 13. Hearts Sunday drew 1-1
with St. Johnstone. Kilmarnock on Saturday was held to a 0-0 draw
at home by Dunfermline.
	   (scw)	   
</TEXT>
