<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bangladesh-Children Rescued,0202 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police rescue 21 child refugees from suspected traffickers
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) _ Police raided a hotel in the
Bangladeshi capital Sunday and rescued 21 Muslim child refugees
from Myanmar allegedly captured to be smuggled to Persian Gulf
nations for use as camel jockeys, an official said.
	   The boys and girls, aged 4 to 10, were brought by their captors
to Dhaka from the southern Cox's Bazar district, where more than
20,000 Muslim refugees from Myanmar have been living in camps since
1991, the police official said. He spoke on customary condition of
anonymity.
	   Police said they detained four women who claimed to be mothers
of the children.
	   A quarter of a million Muslim refugees fled to neighboring
Bangladesh from Myanmar's western province of Arakan to escape
alleged rape, arson and forced unpaid labor in 1991.
	   Though tens of thousands have since been repatriated, more than
20,000 refuse to return home for fear of persecution.
	   Trafficking of children from Bangladesh to Persian Gulf
countries is common. While the boys are used as jockeys in camel
racing, a popular sport, the girls are sold for prostitution,
police say. 	   
</TEXT>
