<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Italy-Drugs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Doping commission reopens inquiry
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ The Italian Olympic Committee's anti-drug
investigator said Sunday he will reopen his inquiry into the use of
performance-enhancing substances in the country's top soccer
league.
	   The official, Ugo Longo, said he will look into reports that a
positive doping test turned in by a player in a 1997 Serie A match
was covered up.
	   He will also investigate a report that 24 players of Serie A
club AC Parma showed abnormalities in blood tests in July. The
players allegedly had elevated levels of red blood cells _ which
could indicate the use of EPO, a banned synthetic hormone.
	   Longo will not undertake an examination of the Italian national
team, he said. Media reports had suggested he would.
	   Prosecutors in Torino and Bologna have been carrying out their
own, separate inquiries since the summer. The fallout has included
the resignation of Italian Olympic Committee (CONI) president Mario
Pescante and the firing of the chief of CONI's rug-testing
laboratory _ both last week.
	   In August, Longo wrapped up a two-week investigation, concluding
that legal muscle-builders such as creatine, not banned substances,
are a problem in Italian soccer and steps should be taken to curb
their use.
	   He has suggested creatine, an amino acid powder, be banned or
restricted.
	   (hjf-fd)
</TEXT>
