</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian government condemns possible NATO attack on Yugoslavia
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Patriarch Alexy's comments in new grafs 4-6,
edits to conform. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The Russian government on Sunday condemned any
unsanctioned NATO attack on Yugoslavia as a ``rude violation'' of
the United Nations charter, and urged that the conflict be solved
diplomatically.
	   ``The Russian government thinks it necessary to emphasize again
that using force against a sovereign state without the sanction of
the Security Council would be a rude violation of the U.N.
charter,'' according to a government statement.
	   ``We are convinced that complicated ethnic conflicts, which the
Kosovo conflict undoubtedly is, cannot be settled militarily.''
	   The head of Russia's Orthodox Church joined in warning NATO away
from any attacks on Yugoslav targets.
	   ``Any military interference can trigger irrevocable consequences
and cause people who have nothing to do with the conflict to
suffer,'' Patriarch Alexy II said, according to the Interfax news
agency.
	   Alexy spoke after meeting with the Orthodox Archbishop of Tirana
and All Albania, Anastasy. He noted that Kosovo is sacred to the
Serbs, ``a special place where the Orthodox Church keeps sacred
objects, which may also be destroyed.''
	   The government and church statements echoed earlier comments by
Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov and other Russian leaders,
who sharply opposed any NATO attacks.
	   Western governments have warned that NATO might take military
action after accusations that Serbian forces committed atrocities
against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
	   Russia's parliament last week declared that any NATO military
action over Kosovo taken without U.N. approval would be considered
an ``illegal act of aggression.''
	   In a unanimous resolution passed Friday, the State Duma said it
would review all agreements between NATO and Russia if the Western
alliance were to opt for force against Yugoslavia.
	   The NATO allies have not yet resolved their differences over
whether a further U.N. resolution is needed to launch air strikes,
and a final decision about whether to use force won't likely be
made until later this month.
	   (pvs/ji)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
