w2070 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 4thLd-Writethru   10-04 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian delegation meets Milosevic as NATO threatens strikes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES human rights report; expands on British ground force
preparations; CORRECTS atribution to Sunday Telegraph. Trims.
 &UR; AP Photos BEL101-102
 &UR; By MISHA SAVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Reacting to the threat of a NATO
strike on Yugoslavia, Russia's defense and foreign ministers called
on President Slobodan Milosevic on Sunday, as his generals prepared
to defend the country against attack.
	   Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev
met with Milosevic and Milan Milutinovic, president of Serbia, the
dominant Yugoslav republic.
	   Despite Russia's opposition, NATO is preparing for possible
intervention in Kosovo _Serbia's southern province _ to end seven
months of bloodshed.
	   Yugoslavia's state-run Tanjug news agency reported that
Yugoslavia's defense minister and top general had also attended,
and that Ivanov handed Milosevic a message from Russian President
Boris Yeltsin, but offered no details. A statement from Milosevic's
office afterward said any NATO strike would be an ``act of
aggression'' and asserted that in Kosovo the overall situation is
``improving daily.''
	   Russia is the Serbs' main ally, sharing bonds of religion, and
joint Slavic roots.
	   In Moscow, Itar-Tass carried a government statement again
expressing opposition to any NATO intervention in Kosovo without
the sanction of the U.N. Security Council, of which Russia is a
veto-carrying member.
	   Preparing for any attack, Yugoslav generals put the nation's air
defense on high alert, even as Serbian authorities indicated they
were ready for compromise by installing an interim government in
the rebellious Serbian province. A Western diplomat also said that
up to 120 Yugoslav army armored vehicles, including tanks, have
been pulled out of Kosovo so far.
	   The Serb side reported no fighting Sunday, beyond two attacks of
civilian cars by Albanian ``terrorists'' about 40 kilometers (25
miles) south of Pristina, Kosovo's provincial capital, in which one
person was wounded. Elsewhere, a policeman was killed after
stepping on a mine, said the Serb Media Center.
	   But the Kosovo Information Center, which reports for the
Albanian side, said there was heavy fighting between government
forces and the guerrillas, 40 kilometers (25 miles) southwest of
Pristina.
	   NATO countries continued preparations.
	   London's Sunday Telegraph reported Britain preparing ground
troops and armored units for Kosovo, to be deployed in a
post-airstrike peacekeeping role. The defense ministry refused to
confirm or deny the report but repeated Britain was ready to
participate in a NATO attack.
	   The Yugoslav government said Friday the fighting had ended and
blamed continuing violence on ethnic Albanian rebels. Serbian
police and the Yugoslav army have routed separatist Kosovo Albanian
rebels in a seven-month crackdown. The conflict has killed hundreds
_ most of them Albanian civilians _ and left upward of 275,000
villagers refugees.
	   Ethnic Albanian political leaders rejected the interim council,
drawn up without any consultation with them, in which Serbs
outnumber majority Albanians.
	   Constituting the council, moribund since 1989, was part of a
last-ditch effort to show that Serbs intend to end the conflict.
U.N. chief Kofi Annan plans report Monday to the Security Council
on whether Belgrade is complying with demands to halt its assault
on ethnic Albanians. If not, Washington has indicated that NATO air
strikes will follow within two weeks.
	   Momentum for outside involvement has increased in the past week
amid revelations of massacres of ethnic Albanian civilians in the
forests of Kosovo.
	   Human Rights watch, in a report issued Sunday, said both the
authorities and have committed atrocities in seven months of
conflict, but government abuses have been on a far greater scale.
	   The New York-based organization said Serbian police and military
``committed extrajudicial executions and other unlawful killings,
systematically destroyed civilian property and attacked
humanitarian aid workers, all of which are violations of the rules
of war.''
	   ``The Albanian insurgency ... has also violated the laws of war
by such actions as the taking of civilian hostages and by summary
executions,'' the report said. ``Although on a lesser scale than
the government abuses, these too are violations of international
standards and should be condemned.''
	   On Saturday, Serb police took reporters to the site of what they
thought was a mass grave on a mountain top near the village of
Volujak, about 60 kilometers (40 miles) west of the provincial
capital, Pristina. Dogs, they said, had unearthed human bones in an
area formerly held by the Albanian separatist Kosovo Liberation
Army.
	   By Sunday, parts of five skeletons had been found, along with
Chinese-made bullet casings and empty casings of hunting rifles at
the site _ both characteristic for ammunition used by the KLA.
	   (gj/ms)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
