<HEADER>
w2080 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Italy-Politics 4thLd   10-04 0250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Politics, 4th Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Italian Communists vote to yank support for Prodi
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: UPDATES with Prodi to go to Scalfaro Monday morning &QL; 
 &UR; With AP Photos
 &UR; By FRANCES D'EMILIO
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Italy's Communists on Sunday voted to withdraw
support for Premier Romano Prodi's 2 1-2-year-old coalition, a move
that could trigger the collapse of one of the country's
longest-lived postwar governments.
	   There was no immediate reaction from the government, but Prodi
has said he would call a confidence vote if the Communists yanked
support. The coalition has a majority without the Communists in the
Senate, but counts on them for a majority in the Chamber.
	   A confidence vote could be scheduled in the next few days.
	   If Prodi loses his majority in the chamber, he would be forced
to resign and new elections could be called.
	   The presidential palace announced Sunday evening that Prodi had
a Monday morning appointment with President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro to
discuss the developments. Prodi could offer his resignation.
	   Scalfaro could turn to another politician to put together a
coalition, or ask Prodi to try to muster a coalition majority,
possibly from centrists now in the opposition and from Communists
unhappy with their party leadership's decision.
	   But a key centrist leader, Francesco Cossiga, a former premier
and head of state, has indicated his followers wouldn't bail out
Prodi.
	   Defying other, 8th graf
	   (fd)
</TEXT>
