w2083 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Tennis-GrandSl 4thLd-Writethru   10-04 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Grand Slam Cup, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rios overcomes painful back to beat Agassi in five sets
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs; UPDATES with more quotes &QL; 
 &UR; By NESHA STARCEVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MUNICH, Germany (AP) _ Marcelo Rios and Venus Williams grabbed
the richest purse in tennis Sunday, collecting between them dlrs
2.1 million for winning the two titles at the Grand Slam Cup.
	   Rios took home dlrs 1.3 million for beating Andre Agassi in five
sets, while Williams earned dlrs 800,000 for winning the inaugural
women's event with a 6-2, 3-6, 6-2 victory over Patty Schnyder.
	   Rios, who looked like he would quit early in the match because
of back problems, recovered to prevail in two hours, 55 minutes,
winning 6-4, 2-6, 7-6 (7-1), 5-7, 6-3.
	   ``I was going to retire, but the trainer told me to give it one
more chance,'' Rios said.
	   ``Even if I was not feeling good, I played one of my best
matches,'' Rios said. ``I'm really proud I can win a match like
that.''
	   Williams, 18, won a battle of teen-agers, breaking serve for 4-2
in the final set and serving out the match in one hour, 34 minutes.
Schnyder, 19, got dlrs 400,000.
	   ``She picked it up in the second set, but I got an early break
in the third and then another one,'' said the fifth-ranked
American. Schnyder is ranked No. 9.
	   Williams just had too much power for Schnyder and ran down the
tenacious Swiss.
	   ``We both played hard. She really wanted this title and I really
wanted this title, too,'' Williams said.
	   Agassi, a former No. 1 who is back at No. 8 after dropping out
of the top 100 last year, at the end seemed to be worn out by
nearly seven hours of tennis in two days.
	   ``I wasn't feeling that good all day. It's hard to recover in 15
hours or so,'' said Agassi, who battled three hours and 40 minutes
to beat Karol Kucera in the semifinals, while Rios had a three-set
win over Mark Philippoussis.
	   ``I didn't really believe he was close to defaulting. I felt he
ran incredibly well,'' said Agassi, who got dlrs 650,000. ``He is
very talented.''
	   The American had not met the qualifying standard but was given a
wild card in an attempt to give some luster to the men's field,
which lacked No. 1 Pete Sampras and No. 2 Patrick Rafter.
	   The dlrs 6.7 million tournament nominally brings together
players with the best records in the four Grand Slam events of the
year _ the Australian, French and U.S. Open and Wimbledon.
	   But three of the men's Grand Slam champions elected not to show
up for the richest event in tennis, which awards no ranking points.
	   Asked what he would do with his share of the cash, Rios said,
``put it in the bank.''
	   ``I'm not the type of guy who buys houses or cars,'' he said.
	   Rios, Australian Open runner-up, said he thought of quitting.
``But once you are in the match, you're winning, you see all the
crowd, you are just going to do your best.''
	   The 22-year-old Chilean said his back started hurting the night
before the match. ``But you don't want to go home without a final
like this, playing Andre,'' Rios said.
	   Rios, the highest-ranked player in the event at No. 3, was in
pain early in the match.
	   He was given a massage by a trainer after the third game and
took an injury timeout two games later. He was stretched on the
floor for a couple of minutes while the trainer worked on his back.
	   But he still won the set, hitting a spectacular running backhand
passing shot.
	   With Rios wincing in pain nearly every time he hit the ball,
Agassi won the next set, although Rios produced one of its
highlights: winning a point while sitting on the floor after
slipping and falling on the hard-court surface.
	   Rios won five of his six service games in the third set at love,
but was less error-free in the fourth.
	   Serving to save the match in the fifth, Agassi produced a
double-fault to give Rios three match points. Agassi saved one, but
then committed another double-fault to surrender.
	   Williams said she didn't think about the money during the match.
	   ``It's a nice bonus for winning,'' she said. ``It's a nice prize
pool but generally when you're playing here you are trying to win
your matches.''
	   Schnyder said she had trouble reading Williams's shots.
	   ``It's hard to assess her balls coming high and low,'' she said.
``You make a lot of mistakes. Her serve was sometimes too fast for
me, even her second.''
	   (ns)	   
</TEXT>
