<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Latvia-Election, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With tense citizenship question resolved, Latvia turns to domestic
</HEADLINE>
matters &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: AMs. Leads throughout to RECAST, ADD Zyuganov quote. &QL; 
 &UR; By JIM HEINTZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   RIGA, Latvia (AP) _ With the divisive and distracting issue of
liberalized citizenship for ethnic Russians put behind them,
Latvian politicians on Sunday turned to the question of forming a
government.
	   Negotiations among the six parties that won seats in Saturday's
national elections are expected to take several days and could be
complicated because there are few traditional alliances to rely on.
	   The party that won the most votes didn't even exist six months
ago and is led by former prime minister Andris Skele, who made
enemies across the political spectrum before leaving the post last
year.
	   But it could be relatively easy in comparison with the tensions
over the citizenship referendum that was also voted on Saturday,
which pitted nationalist sentiment against pragmatism.
	   Voters approved easing naturalization laws by a 53-45 margin, a
slim margin statistically but substantial in light of the strong
resentment many Latvians feel for the country's huge ethnic Russian
community.
	   Some 450,000 of the Russians are non-citizens, having become
stateless with the collapse of the Soviet Union. Most of the
Russians came to Latvia during a halfcentury of Soviet rule, or are
their descendants, and many ethnic Latvians see them as unwelcome
remnants of a hated regime.
	   Latvia's naturalization laws placed high obstacles for the
stateless Russians who wanted to become citizens, requiring many of
them to wait until the next milennium even to apply.
	   Amid shrill denunciations from Russia and measured, but still
strong, criticism from the West, the Saeima parliament passed
liberalizing amendments in June. But nationalist politicians
mounted a referendum drive to overturn the changes.
	   Although the eased laws won't make naturalization necessarily
easy _ Russian speakers will still have to labor to learn Latvian _
the referendum paid off Sunday with something rare for Latvia: a
favorable word from Russia.
	   ``It is better to have Russia as a friendly neighbor than to
violate the rights of our compatriots,'' Russian Communist Party
leader Gennady Zyuganov said on Echo Moscow radio.
	   Approving the changes also means Latvia neutralized an issue
that could have blocked its dream of becoming a European Union
member. Now, the country can proceed with another challenge in
achieving the dream: building up its economy.
	   The parties that won Saeima seats are generally in agreement on
economic matters, desiring to continue the market-oriented moves
that have produced large pockets of prosperity and renovation after
a half-century of Soviet shabbiness.
	   Much of Latvia's new prosperity has come from being an important
transit point between Russia and the West. Skele in particular
wants to solidify the economy by building up domestic production.
	   Skele's People's Party was at the top of the results with 20.9
percent. The conservative Latvia's Way had 18 percent, followed by
the National Harmony Party, Fatherland and Freedom, the Union of
Social Democrats and the New Party.
	   (jh)
</TEXT>
