<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iran-UN, 1st ld-Writethru,0547 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. envoy in Iran to discuss problems with Afghanistan
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with comments from Afghan leader &QL; 
 &UR; By AFSHIN VALINEJAD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ The U.N. special envoy arrived here Sunday
to discuss the deepening conflict between Tehran and Afghanistan's
Taliban militia, which has seen both sides move troops to the
border.
	   During his five-day visit, Lakhdar Brahimi will hold talks with
Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi and his deputy, Mohsen Aminzadeh,
who is responsible for Afghan affairs.
	   Brahimi told reporters at the airport that he also hopes to meet
with Iranian President Mohammad Khatami.
	   He was to fly to Pakistan on Thursday.
	   ``I will not be going to Afghanistan because U.N personnel are
not allowed to travel there for security reasons,'' Brahimi said.
	   Pakistan is widely believed to be the Taliban's main backer, and
Iran has been accused of supporting the Afghan opposition in the
north.
	   Tensions between Iran and the Taliban have been high since the
militia admitted that its forces killed eight Iranian diplomats and
a journalist after taking the northern Afghan town of
Mazar-e-Sharif in August. Two diplomats escaped and made their way
home.
	   The Taliban, which rules about 90 percent of Afghanistan, said
renegade fighters killed the Iranians. But Taliban leaders have
refused Iranian demands that the killers be handed over.
	   In a statement released in Pakistan to the privately run News
Network International, the Taliban's reclusive leader said the
slain Iranians were not diplomats, but military personnel, and
accused Iran of ``repeatedly'' interfering in Afghanistan's
internal affairs.
	   ``If foreign interference continues..., it would force the
Taliban to take action,'' Mullah Mohammed Omar said.
	   Iran's response has been to deploy more than 200,000 Iranian
troops on the border with Afghanistan for military maneuvers.
Taliban leaders say they have moved 20,000 troops to the border in
response to the war games.
	   The Taliban on Friday accused Iran of violating its air space
during the maneuvers. Iran denied the allegation.
	   The Taliban continues to hold some 50 Iranian nationals. Tehran
says most were working as drivers delivering aid to Afghans
hard-hit by the war.
	   Apparently mindful of Brahimi's tour, Omar warned the United
Nations against using the killings of the Iranians as an excuse to
deny the Taliban recognition at U.N. headquarters in New York,
where the ousted government of President Burhanuddin Rabbani still
holds the Afghanistan seat.
	   ``It is highly regrettable that the United Nations still accord
recognition to the ousted and rejected Rabbani regime in sheer
violations of its own principles,'' said Omar in the statement
released in Pakistan. Rabbani's alliance controls barely 10 percent
of the country.
	   Omar's statement said every government has a right to introduce
the laws of its choice and the U.N. should not object to its stern
interpretation of Islam.
	   ``If the United Nations does not respect the aspirations of
Afghan majority and turns a blind eye to the ground realities...
then we will be left with no other option, but to make decisions on
our own,'' he said. 	   
</TEXT>
