<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Uganda-Missing Plane, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Reports: senior military officer killed in crash, flight plan
</HEADLINE>
tampered with &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS with report senior army officer killed in crash.
UPDATES throughout. Changes overline. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) _ A senior military officer was killed in
the crash of an airplane in western Uganda which was reportedly on
its way to eastern Congo, a radio report said Sunday.
	   The private Capital Radio, citing Transport Minister John
Nasasira, said the army had found the remains of Col. Jet Mwebaze,
the brother of acting Chief of Staff James Kazini, who was among
the nine passengers of the plane which crashed Sept. 25.
	   No confirmation of the report was immediately available Sunday
evening, but a reporter from the independent newspaper The Monitor
said he saw a helicopter arrive at Entebbe airport Sunday carrying
five survivors of the crash and two coffins.
	   Mwebaze was one of four additional passengers on the twin-engine
Islander who had gone missing since the plane crash-landed in the
foothills of the Rwenzori Mountains in western Uganda.
	   The army this week had already found the remains of the pilot
who was killed in the crash and on Thursday said it found five
survivors roaming the remote area. Another four passengers,
including Mwebaze, had last been reported missing.
	   It was unclear Sunday whether the remaining three passengers had
been found.
	   Meanwhile, the government-owned Sunday Vision newspaper said the
flight plan filed by the Ugandan pilot had been altered, apparently
to conceal its real destination in eastern Congo.
	   The destination of the plane, which took off nine days ago from
Entebbe airport, was erased and the town of Kasese, 390 kilometers
(245 miles) west of Kampala, was inserted, the Sunday Vision
reported.
	   The airplane crashed later that day near Kisomoro, about 60
kilometers (38 miles) north of Kasese.
	   The newspaper quoted a sister of one of the passengers as saying
the group was flying directly to Bunia in northeastern Congo,
en-route to Kisangani, Congo's third largest town now controlled by
Congolese rebels trying to oust President Laurent Kabila.
	   Kabila has accused Rwanda and Uganda of spearheading the
rebellion against him. Both countries maintain they are concerned
about Rwandan and Ugandan rebels operating against their
governments from bases in eastern Congo, but have not openly
admitted to militarily backing the Congolese rebellion.
	   Earlier this week Ugandan military officials said the plane had
been spotted over Kasese but never landed. They later gave a
contradicting statement that the plane had been destined for
Kasese.
	   The newspaper said three of the passengers had business links
with Kenya, Uganda and Congolese towns of Bunia and Kisangani.
	   The passengers also included an Israeli, an Asian, a Congolese
and several Ugandans.
 &UR; (VAR/hw-cm) 	   
</TEXT>
