<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Equestrian-World Games, 1st Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New Zealand wins gold medals in team and individual three-day
</HEADLINE>
event, Werth takes gold in individual dressage &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with results from individual dressage, CONFORMS to
style on state names &QL; 
 &UR; With AP Photos &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Blyth Tait won the individual gold medal and led the
New Zealand team to the victory in the three-day event at the 1998
World Equestrian Games Sunday.
	   Fellow New Zealander Mark Todd took the silver on Broadcast
News, while Sweden's Paula Tornquist on SAS Monaghan finished
third. Defending champion Vaughn Jeffreys, also from New Zealand,
was fourth.
	   After the event's final test, show jumping, Tait, on Ready
Teddy, had 43.4 penalties, compared to Todd's 44.2. Tornquist
finished with 45.6 penalties.
	   David O'Connor of The Plains, Virginia, scored the U.S. team
best result to finish sixth on Giltedge with 51.4 penalties. Kerry
Millikin of Westport, Massachussetts, placed 15 on Out and About,
and two-time World champion Bruce Davidson of Unionsville,
Pennsylvania, finished 21th on Heyday.
	   At the three-day event team competition, New Zealand claimed the
gold with a total of 137.6 penalties, while France finished second
with 182.8, and Britain took the bronze with 184.9.
	   The Americans, finished fourth with a total of 186.1 penalties.
	   At the Atlanta Olympics, Australia won, while the Americans
claimed the silver and New Zealand took the bronze.
	   The three-day event was held in Pratoni del Vivaro, 50
kilometers (30 miles) southeast of Rome, at a track inaugurated
during the Rome 1960 Olympic Games in the capital.
	   Also Sunday, Germany's Isabel Werth on chestnut Nissan Gigolo
won the gold medal in the individual dressage, after helping her
team secure the championships' first gold in the team dressage.
	   The silver medal went to Dutch Anky van Grunsven, who finished
second also at the Atlanta Olympics, on Gestion Bonfire, while
German Ulla Salzgeber on Rusty took the bronze.
	   The 1996 Olympic champion in individual and team dressage, Werth
won the discipline's final test, free style, on Sunday,
consolidating her lead over van Grunsven.
	   Werth had finished second in Friday's Grand Prix Special behind
van Grunsven, but had managed to stay atop the event standings.
	   In the overall standings, Werth totalled 241.7 points, while van
Grunsven had 241.3 and Salzgeber scored 225.0.
	   Gunter Seidel on Graf George was the top U.S. rider with 213.8
points and finished 9th. Fellow American Sue Blink on Flim Flam
placed 12th with 206.3.
	   Last Thursday, Germany won the team dressage title, with the
silver going to the Netherlands and the bronze to Sweden. The
United States was fourth.
	   The dressage event was held in the refurbished Flaminio stadium
in Rome.
	   (ar-fd)
</TEXT>
