w2131 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 2ndLd-Writethru   10-04 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0686 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian delegation meets Milosevic as NATO threatens strikes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Yugoslav statement of meeting, reports of
isolated fighting, Yugoslavia saying it is prepared for defense,
other details; human rights report; expands on British ground force
preparations; CORRECTS atribution to Sunday Telegraph. TRIMS. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos BEL101-102 &QL; 
 &UR; By MISHA SAVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Reacting to the threat of a NATO
strike on Yugoslavia, Russia's defense and foreign ministers called
on President Slobodan Milosevic on Sunday, while Yugoslav generals
prepared to defend the country.
	   Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev
met with Milosevic and Milan Milutinovic, president of Serbia, the
dominant Yugoslav republic, to discuss possible NATO intervention
in Kosovo _ Serbia's southern province _ to end seven months of
bloodshed.
	   Yugoslavia's state-run Tanjug news agency reported that
Yugoslavia's defense minister and top general had also attended,
and that Ivanov handed Milosevic a message from Russian President
Boris Yeltsin, but offered no details.
	   A statement from Milosevic's office afterward said any NATO
strike would be an ``act of aggression'' and asserted that in
Kosovo the overall situation is ``improving daily.''
	   Russia is the Serbs' main ally, sharing bonds of religion, and
joint Slavic roots.
	   In Moscow, Itar-Tass carried a government statement again
expressing opposition to any NATO intervention in Kosovo without
the sanction of the U.N. Security Council, of which Russia is a
veto-carrying member.
	   A Yugoslav statement afterward said the leadership wanted the
Kosovo dispute solved peacefully, ``but in case we are attacked, we
shall defend our country with all means.''
	   Yugoslav generals put the nation's air defense on high alert,
even as Serbian authorities indicated they were ready for
compromise by installing an interim government in the rebellious
Serbian province.
	   A Western diplomat also said that up to 120 Yugoslav army
armored vehicles, including tanks, have been pulled out of Kosovo
so far.
	   The Serb side reported no fighting Sunday, beyond two attacks on
civilian cars by Albanian ``terrorists'' about 40 kilometers (25
miles) south of Pristina, Kosovo's provincial capital, in which one
person was wounded. Elsewhere, a policeman was killed after
stepping on a mine, said the Serb Media Center.
	   The Kosovo Information Center, which reports for the Albanian
side, said there was heavy fighting between government forces and
the guerrillas, 40 kilometers (25 miles) southwest of Pristina.
	   Despite the apparent Serbian moves to withdraw, NATO countries
continued preparations.
	   London's Sunday Telegraph reported Britain preparing ground
troops and armored units, to be deployed in a post-airstrike
peacekeeping role. The defense ministry refused to confirm or deny
the report but repeated Britain was ready to participate in a NATO
attack.
	   Serbian police and the Yugoslav army have routed separatist
Kosovo Albanian rebels in a seven-month crackdown. The conflict has
killed hundreds _ most of them Albanian civilians _ and left upward
of 275,000 villagers refugees.
	   Ethnic Albanian political leaders have rejected the proposed
interim council, in which Serbs outnumber majority Albanians.
	   Constituting the council, moribund since 1989, was part of a
last-ditch effort to show that Serbs intend to end the conflict.
	   U.N. chief Kofi Annan plans to report Monday to the Security
Council on whether Belgrade is complying with demands to halt its
assault on ethnic Albanians. If not, Washington has indicated that
NATO air strikes will follow within two weeks.
	   Momentum for outside involvement has increased in the past week
amid revelations of massacres of ethnic Albanian civilians in the
forests of Kosovo.
	   Human Rights watch, in a report issued Sunday, said both the
authorities and have committed atrocities in seven months of
conflict, but government abuses have been on a far greater scale. 	   
</TEXT>
