w2138 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Brazil-Elections 2ndLdWritethru   10-04 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Brazil-Elections, 2nd Ld Writethru,0666 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
close at 2000 GMT, final results expected Monday
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with Cardoso voting, color, quotes; polls
 &UR; Cardoso support strong as Brazil goes to polls
 &UR; By PETER MUELLO
 &UR; Associated Press Writer

<TEXT>
	   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) _ President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso was the overwhelming favorite in Sunday's national
elections, getting a boost from fear of a deepening economic
crisis.
	   An imminent recession and soaring unemployment have overshadowed
the election, as the market panic that struck Asia and Russia now
targets Brazil, the world's ninth-largest economy.
	   ``The important thing is not to switch drivers in the middle of
the race,'' said Marcio Karte, a Rio newsstand dealer who voted for
the president.
	   Some 106 million voters went to the polls Sunday to choose a
president, 27 governors, all 513 federal deputies, a third of the
81-seat Senate and 1,405 state legislators. Voting is mandatory for
Brazilians between 18 and 70.
	   Pollsters unanimously predict Cardoso will be re-elected to a
second four-year term on the first ballot.
	   A survey taken Friday by the Datafolha polling institute gave
Cardoso 49 percent of the votes, compared to 26 percent for his
closest rival, former labor leader Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva of the
Workers Party. The poll questioned 21,057 people nationwide and had
a margin of error of 2 percentage points.
	   If he gets less than half the valid votes, which excludes blank
and voided ballots, Cardoso would face the No. 2 finisher in a
runoff on Oct. 25.
	   Cardoso, a 67-year-old sociologist, has held steady even as
Brazil lost the confidence of international investors _ and despite
promises to cut spending and even raise taxes if elected.
	   ``I voted for him even though he led the country into the
crisis, because he's the only one who can get us out,'' said
Rodrigo Jelmayer, a third-year law student in Sao Paulo.
	   Polls opened at 8 a.m. (1100 GMT) and close at 5 p.m. (2000
GMT). Voting was mostly peaceful, although army troops were
stationed in northern states with high Indian populations or a
history of land conlicts. A ban on liquor sales was in effect in
most of the country.
	   As usual, a ban on last-minute campaigning was widely flouted.
In Rio, 23 people were arrested for pamphleting.
	   Cardoso voted just before noon in Sao Paulo. He flashed a ``V''
sign to photographers but declined to talk to reporters. Lula voted
earlier in Sao Bernardo do Campo, an industrial suburb of Sao Paulo
where he worked for years as a factory lathe operator.
	   For the first time, more than half of Brazilian voters will use
electronic voting machines instead of paper ballots. The electronic
votes will be tallied in 24 hours, but the rest won't be counted
until Friday, electoral officials say.
	   Cardoso has pledged strong measures to control a ballooning
budget deficit of more than 70 billion reals, or dlrs 60 billion.
Fear that the government won't get financing has scared away
investors.
	   Many economists predict a recession in 1999 and even worse
unemployment, which unions now put at 18 percent of the work force.
	   Finance Minister Pedro Malan is heading negotiations for an
emergency loan package with the International Monetary Fund and
other public and private lenders, reportedly worth dlrs 30 billion.
	   Cardoso's success may hinge on the strength _ and cooperation _
of his inconstant five-party coalition in Congress. Legislators are
to vote on long-delayed reforms to cut spending and raise revenue.
	   Meanwhile, voters hope he can revive the magic of the Plano
Real, the economic program that eliminated 2,400 percent inflation
and propelled him to the presidency in 1994.
	   Markets have the same hope.
	   ``Cardoso has a clear vision and his policies don't stray off
track,'' said Carlos Kawall, chief economist at Citibank in Sao
Paulo. ``It's incredible to see how far we've come, after so many
years of mismanagement.'' 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
