<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Religion </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lutheran church reopens in Moscow after six decades
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A Moscow Lutheran church that Soviet authorities
closed down six decades ago, during the era of Soviet dictator
Josef Stalin, reopened on Sunday.
	   The altar of the Lutheran Church of Apostles Peter and Paul was
restored with funds from Germany, the Moscow city government and
the Russian federal government, the ITAR-Tass news agency said.
	   The church was founded in 1624 and closed in August 1938, as
Stalin's Communist campaign against religion intensified.
	   The majority of the church's congregation are Germans. Only
about 10 percent are ethnic Russians, ITAR-Tass said.
	   (ji) 	   
</TEXT>
