<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Obit-Delamuraz,0320 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former Swiss president Jean-Pascal Delamuraz dies at 62
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BERN, Switzerland (AP) _ Former Swiss President Jean-Pascal
Delamuraz, whose disparagement of Jewish groups seeking
compensation for Holocaust victims sparked an international outcry,
died Sunday, the Swiss government announced. He was 62.
	   The cause of Delamuraz's death, six months after he left office
on health grounds, was not given.
	   Born in Paudex, near Lausanne, in 1936, Delamuraz was president
in 1989 and 1996. He joined the seven-member Federal Council, or
cabinet, as defense minister in 1984 and was economics minister
from 1987 until his resignation earlier this year.
	   He courted international controversy last year with his role in
Swiss attempts to set up a fund to compensate for Switzerland's
failure to force its banks to track accounts belonging to Holocaust
victims and their families, and for profiting from goods looted by
the Nazis and deposited in Switzerland.
	   Delamuraz accused Jewish groups lobbying for the fund of
``blackmail.'' The remark prompted an international outcry and a
public relations debacle for the country. Delamuraz eventually
apologized.
	   The Swiss government subsequently proposed a 7 billion Swiss
franc (dlrs 5 billion) fund for a range of humanitarian causes,
including victims of the Holocaust.
	   He belonged to the centrist Radical Democrats, one of four
parties in the governing coalition that shares out the cabinet
seats.
	   Delamuraz left office in March this year after announcing in
January that, for health reasons, he was no longer certain he could
carry out his duties.
	   Last year, he underwent an operation for liver cancer. This
followed heart operations in 1992 and 1995.
	   Delamuraz is survived by his wife, Catherine, and their son and
daughter. Details of funeral arrangements were not immediately
available. 	   
</TEXT>
