<HEADLINE>
Pope seeks to heal wounds of war
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with pope's departure remarks; ADDS photo numbers &QL; 
 &UR; With AP Photos SOL101,102,106 &QL; 
 &UR; By VICTOR L. SIMPSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SPLIT, Croatia (AP) _ On a beach packed with pilgrims, Pope John
Paul II sought Sunday to heal the wounds left by war and
totalitarian rule and urged the international community to provide
``timely help'' to end the Kosovo conflict.
	   In departure remarks delivered at the airport alongside
President Franjo Tudjman, the pope said Croatia ``must show great
patience, wisdom, a willingness to make sacrifices and generous
solidarity in order to overcome definitively the present postwar
phase and attain the noble goals to which she aspires.
	   ``Democracy comes at a high price; the money to pay for it is
minted from the noble metal of honesty, reasonableness, respect for
others, the spirit of sacrifice, and patience. To claim that it can
be bought with a different currency is to run the risk of
bankruptcy.''
	   Tudjman is often criticized by western governments for
authoritarianism.
