w2178 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Uganda-MissingPlane 1stLd-Writethru   10-04 0418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Uganda-Missing Plane, 1st Ld-Writethru,0417 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Reports: senior military officer killed in crash, flight plan
</HEADLINE>
tampered with &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with report senior army officer killed in
crash &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) _ A senior Ugandan military officer was
killed when an airplane reportedly headed for rebel-held Congo
crashed in western Uganda, a radio report said Sunday.
	   The private Capital Radio, citing Transport Minister John
Nasasira, said the army had found the remains of Col. Jet Mwebaze,
among nine passengers on the plane which crashed Sept. 25. Mwebaze
was the brother of acting Chief of Staff James Kazini,
	   No confirmation of the report was immediately available Sunday
evening, but a reporter from the independent newspaper The Monitor
said he saw a helicopter arrive at Entebbe airport Sunday carrying
five survivors of the crash and two coffins.
	   The army found the five survivors wandering the remote area last
week, as well as the remains of the pilot.
	   Mwebaze was one of four passengers on the twin-engine Islander
who had gone missing after the plane crash-landed in the foothills
of the Rwenzori Mountains in western Uganda.
	   It was unclear Sunday whether the remaining three passengers had
been found.
	   Meanwhile, the government-owned Sunday Vision newspaper said the
flight plan filed by the Ugandan pilot had been altered, apparently
to conceal its real destination in eastern Congo.
	   The pilot had listed a Congolese destination in the flight plan,
but the destination of the plane was subsequently erased and the
Ugandan town of Kasese, 390 kilometers (245 miles) west of Kampala,
was inserted, Sunday Vision reported.
	   The newspaper quoted a sister of one of the passengers as saying
the group was flying directly to Bunia in northeastern Congo,
en-route to Kisangani, Congo's third largest town now controlled by
Congolese rebels trying to oust President Laurent Kabila.
	   The crash of a plane carrying a senior military officer headed
deep inside rebel-held territory would have drawn attention to
Ugandan ties with the rebels.
	   Kabila has accused Uganda of backing the rebel insurgency.
Uganda has denied any direct involvement.
	   The airplane crashed near Kisomoro, about 60 kilometers (38
miles) north of Kasese.
	   The newspaper said three of the passengers had business links
with Kenya, Uganda and in rebel-held Congo.
	   The passengers also included an Israeli, an Asian, a Congolese
and several Ugandans. 	   
</TEXT>
