<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Anti Abortion March </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1,000 march to protest abortion
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Nearly 1,000 people marched through Paris Sunday to
protest abortion and decry a newly tabled bill to give homosexual
and unmarried couples legal rights.
	   The demonstration, organized by Renouveau Catholique (Catholic
Renewal), took marchers from the Palais-Royal square on the Right
Bank to Sacre Coeur, the basilica perched on a hill in Montmartre,
in northern Paris.
	   ``A people who kills its children has no future,'' ``To abort is
to kill,'' read banners carried by the crowd.
	   Renouveau Catholique decried the proposal to adjust laws in
favor of unmarried couples, calling it a ``serious attack on the
basis of society, which is the family.''
	   In France, abortion is available on demand in the first 12 weeks
or later if the fetus is badly deformed or if the mother's life is
at risk.
	   The anti-abortion lobby is small but vocal.
	   (eg-parf)
</TEXT>
