<SLUG> BC-Sudan-Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede NAIROBI
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Government postpones talks on southern Sudan cease-fire &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with government saying it is postponing talks &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) _ Sudan on Sunday demanded a postponement
of talks on renewing a cease-fire agreement with rebels due to
fighting in the south.
	   Gen. Hassan Dahawi, the state minister for social planning,
accused the rebels of using the three-month cease-fire to shift its
forces to Eastern Equatoria, the scene of current fighting, the
Sudan News Agency reported Sunday. The cease-fire ends on Oct. 15.
	   Sudan called for a postponement of the talks ``because the time
was not suitable due to fighting currently taking place,'' the
agency quoted Dahawi as saying.
	   The talks were to be held Monday in the Kenyan capital, Nairobi,
under the auspices of the regional Intergovernmental Authority on
Development.
	   Sudan says the rebel offensive, which began on Sept. 14, aims to
capture the provincial town of Juba, about 1,200 kilometers (750
miles) south of Khartoum. Rebels say they attacked government
positions because the Sudanese air force was bombing civilian
targets in rebel-held areas.
	   Juba is the largest town in southern Sudan under government
control.
	   Dahawi also accused two of IGAD's members, Uganda and Eritrea,
of aiding the main rebel group, the Sudan People's Liberation Army,
in carrying out the offensive.
	   The postponement of the talks cut hopes among aid agencies and
donors that the three-month cease-fire to facilitate aid efforts
would be extended.
	   The government says the cease-fire applies to all of the south,
while the rebels insist it is restricted only to Bahr el-Ghazal,
where famine is widespread.
	   Last month, the European Union said it hoped the cease-fire
would not only be extended but also expanded to cover other
provinces where aid is needed.
	   The 15-year civil war often has led to famine because rebels or
government-backed militia burn or steal crops to deny food to their
enemies. Some 1.5 million people have died in the fighting and
famines.
 &UR; pvs-mo-tt-lm 	   
</TEXT>
