<SLUG> BC-Croatia-Pope, 6th Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pope seeks to heal wounds of war
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with pope's arrival back in Rome &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By VICTOR L. SIMPSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SPLIT, Croatia (AP) _ On a seaside beach packed with pilgrims,
Pope John Paul II sought Sunday to heal the wounds left by war and
totalitarian rule and urged the international community to provide
``timely help'' to end the Kosovo conflict.
	   In his departure remarks, with President Tudjman with him at the
airport, the pope said Croatia ``must show great patience, wisdom,
a willingness to make sacrifices and generous solidarity in order
to overcome definitively the present postwar phase and attain the
noble goals to which she aspires.''
	   ``Democracy comes at a high price; the money to pay for it is
minted from the noble metal of honesty, reasonableness, respect for
others, the spirit of sacrifice, and patience. To claim that it can
be bought with a different currency is to run the risk of
bankruptcy.''
	   Tudjman is often criticized by western governments for
authoritarianism.
	   John Paul arrived back in Rome late Sunday evening
	    &UR; Hundreds of, 5th graf prv
	   (vls-fd)
</TEXT>
