</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Britain-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With Britain-Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; French foreign minister meets British counterpart on Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with quote from ministry spokesman; ADDS more
background &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine met Sunday
night with his British counterpart to discuss the situation in
Kosovo where threats of a NATO strike loom, the Foreign Ministry
said.
	   A ministry spokesman, speaking on customary condition of
anonymity, provided no details on the meeting between Vedrine and
Robin Cook.
	   The encounter was preceded by a lengthy telephone conversation
between Vedrine and U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, the
spokesman said.
	   Vedrine and Cook were discussing ``the decisions that are to be
made on this dossier,'' the spokesman said, refusing to elaborate.
	   Tension surrounding an eventual NATO strike was mounting as
Western leaders sought a way to force Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic to halt attacks on ethnic Albanians seeking greater
autonomy for Kosovo province and find a political settlement to the
crisis.
	   Britain has said it will send four more ground-attack aircraft
to a NATO base in southern Italy on Monday, doubling the number of
Royal Air Force planes there in readiness for an attack on Kosovo.
	   Prime Minister Tony Blair's Cabinet meets Monday to formally
approve the use of force unless Milosevic backs down.
	   Also Monday, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan is to deliver his
own assessment to the Security Council on whether Belgrade is
complying with U.N. demands to halt its assault on ethnic
Albanians.
	   If not, Washington has indicated that NATO air attacks will come
within two weeks.
	   France, active in seeking a solution to the Kosovo crisis, is
not a member of NATO's military wing, but is nevertheless
consulted.
	   (eg-var-parf)
</TEXT>
