<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Finland-Championship,0270 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Briton Armstrong coaches team to title
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HELSINKI, Finland (AP) _ Champion Haka of Valkeakoski lost 1-0
away to VPS Vaasa Sunday in the last round of the season, but still
took the Finnish soccer championship.
	   Haka finished with 48 points in 27 games while VPS took the
silver medal with 45 points.
	   Haka, coached by Briton Keith Armstrong, secured the title last
week, becoming only the third promoted team in Finland to be
crowned champion.
	   The bronze went to another league newcomer, PK-35 of Helsinki,
coached by former German Bundesliga pro Pasi Rautiainen.
	   Second and third place, as well as the UEFA Cup qualifying spot
that goes with second place, were up for grabs to the very end.
PK-35 tied 1-1 against HJK, ending the season with 44 points, only
one behind VPS.
	   Armstrong is immensely popular in Finnish soccer after a stint
as a studio commentator on national TV during the World Cup in
France.
	   Armstrong, 40, who hails from Corbridge, in northeastern
England, has lived in Finland for 19 years, winning three
championship titles as a player. He gained back-to-back golds with
OPS of Oulu in 1979 and 1980, and also won with Kuusysi of Lahti in
1984.
	   ``I scored at Anfield Road against Liverpool (for OPS) in the
European Cup. It was great, but we lost 10-1,'' Armstrong said.
	   As a coach, Armstrong led Haka to the promotion last year, and
added the Cup title as well.
	   But in this year's Cup Winners' Cup, Haka was ousted last week
by Panionios of Greece in the first round on an aggregate score of
5-1.
</TEXT>
