<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Senior Club Pro,0140 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Wes Smith putts his way to victory
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WEST PALM BEACH, Florida (AP) _ Wes Smith's broom-handled putter
carried him to a one-stroke victory in the PGA Senior Club
Professional Championship on Sunday.
	   Closing out a 4-under-par 68 by sinking an 18-foot (5.5-meter)
putt on the 18th hole, the 53-year-old teaching pro in Hollywood,
Florida, birdied four of the final six holes.
	   Smith had a 4-under-par 284 for the four rounds, a shot better
than Tommy Price of Hickory, North Carolina. Price shot a 70 on
Sunday.
	   Dick McClean of Kapalua, Hawaii, and Michael Zinni of Mankato,
Minnesota, tied for third at 286 after closing with a 72 and 73,
respectively.
	   McLean led by two strokes through 13 holes before a double bogey
at the par-4 14th hole and a bogey at the par-3 16th.
</TEXT>
