w2299 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Soccer-GermanR     10-04 0322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-German Roundup </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dortmund stops Munich from setting record
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BERLIN (AP) _ Borussia Dortmund, showing signs of jelling in a
rebuilding year, on Sunday stopped Bayern Munich from equalling its
own Bundesliga record of seven straight victories to open the
season.
	   Christian Nerlinger, signed away from Munich this season, headed
in the 49th minute over error-prone 37-year-old libero Lothar
Matthaeus in the 49th minute to lift visiting Dortmund to a 2-2
draw.
	   Munich had opened with seven straight victories in the 1995-96
season before Dortmund dealt them a loss.
	   Dortmund, hoping to find the form that carried it to a Champions
Cup triumph two years ago, turned in its best performance under new
coach Michael Skibbe, hired this season to turn the club around.
	   Dortmund dominated the first 20 minutes, jumping ahead 1-0 on
Swiss striker Stephane Chapuisat's fifth minute roller off a feed
from Nerlinger.
	   But Munich rattled the club by striking for two goals within
seconds.
	   Giovane Elber directed in a deflected shot by Thorsten Fink in
the 39th minute, followed by the club's big striker, Carsten
Jancker, lofting the ball over Dortmund's diving keeper Stefan Klos
seconds later.
	   Nonetheless, in the wide-open contest with both teams firing
regularly at the goal, Dortmund showed it may be on the way up
again after a hard year following snaring the Champions Cup.
	   Nerlinger's header over a badly positioned Matthaeus led to boos
for the libero, who also showed his age by blundering on both goals
Manchester United scored Wednesday in the 2-2 Champions Cup draw
against Munich.
	   MSV Duisburg, apologizing to the fans in a letter for being
blasted 5-0 by RC Genk in the Cup Winners Cup, made some amends by
posting a 2-0 victory over Stuttgart.
	   Midfielder Thomas Hoersen scored for the team in the 43rd minute
and Markus Beierle in the 56th.
	    &UR; (rk)	   
</TEXT>
