<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Canadian Briefs,0789 </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Dollar amounts are in Canadian dollars &QL; 
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HALIFAX (AP) _ It was the toughest mission Sgt. Maurice Robert
ever had to fly.
	   The veteran search-and-rescue technician from Canadian Forces
Base Greenwood in Nova Scotia's Annapolis Valley parachuted into
gusting winds and landed at the crash site where six of his
colleagues lay dead on Friday.
	   Robert extracted himself from 26 feet up a hardwood tree and
followed a local prospector into the bush on a mountainside near
Marsoui, Quebec His heart sank as he recognized the red nose of his
squadron's Labrador helicopter.
	   ``It was 200 to 300 yards from the burnt area,'' Robert said in
an emotionally charged interview from his home on Sunday. ``It was
pretty well beaten up but it was still identifiable.''
	   All of the crew members were close by, he said. They were all
dead.
	   ---
	   HALIFAX (AP) _ A former Soviet spy has broken two decades of
silence about his role in an elaborate KGB deception that left the
careers of six RCMP counter-intelligence officers in tatters.
	   In a new book, Anatoly Maximov tells his side of Operation
Tournament, a KGB ploy to fool the RCMP Security Service into
thinking it had recruited Maximov as a double agent.
	   Maximov says the operation, from 1971 to 1978, gave the KGB a
wealth of information about the Security Service, sowed confusion
in enemy ranks _ and ironically helped lead to reform of Canada's
counter-intelligence arm to take it out of the hands of the RCMP
and make it a civilian operation.
	   ---
	   OTTAWA (AP) _ Canada is campaigning for a seat in one of the
world's most exclusive clubs, the United Nations Security Council,
and the prospects for winning look good.
	   On Thursday, the General Assembly votes to fill two of 10
non-permanent seats on the 15-member council. Canada is a favorite
to win one, along with the Netherlands.
	   While the United States, Britain, France, China and Russia hold
permanent seats on the council, the executive arm of the UN, the
other seats are filled for two-year terms.
	   Canada has won a seat every decade or so since 1948 and is
likely to keep that record intact, says Geoffrey Pearson, a retired
Canadian ambassador and son of Nobel Peace prizewinner Lester
Pearson.
	   ---
	   VANCOUVER (AP) _ Prime Minister Jean Chretien should be promptly
subpoenaed to testify at hearings into RCMP conduct at last year's
Asia-Pacific summit, says a lawyer for 27 protesters.
	   Cameron Ward will table a motion on the issue today as
long-awaited hearings by a three-member panel of the RCMP Public
Complaints Commission begin into clashes between police and
protesters at the 1997 summit.
	   The commission is a federal agency independent of the Mounties
that was created in 1986 to assess complaints against officers.
	   It cannot punish officers, but only report on its findings _ a
sore point for many protesters.
	   ---
	   WINDSOR (AP) _ A mother's nightmare ended in joy Sunday when she
was reunited with her three children almost two years after their
father took them to Lebanon.
	   A deeply moved Roula Chebaro knelt to embrace her daughter
Dalal, 5, and sons, Adnan, 9, and Ousama, 8, as they walked into
Windsor airport.
	   Their journey home began early Saturday in Lebanon, where their
father Chafic Chebaro fled with them on Dec. 14, 1996.
	   The couple were in the midst of a divorce, and he had picked the
children up for a weekend visit. They never came back.
	   Two Windsor police detectives worked on the case for months with
the RCMP, Canada Customs, and the federal immigration and foreign
affairs departments.
	   The father finally decided to return the children to their
mother after talking to her on the telephone and coming to the
conclusion they'd be better off with her.
	   ---
	   EDMONTON (AP) _ International speculators are helping create
turmoil in economies around the world and governments should try to
rein them in, says Conservative leadership candidate Joe Clark.
	   Canada should set the tone by using its international goodwill
and negotiating expertise to try to slow the rate at which money
traders bet on the fate of national currencies, he said in a
leadership debate on Sunday.
	   Clark said some European banks are already reconsidering their
lending policy towards speculative, high-risk ventures.
	   Federal Finance Minister Paul Martin and counterparts from the
world's seven richest countries were in Washington this weekend
hammering out an agreement in principle to ease panic in countries
shell-shocked by the roiling global economic crisis.
</TEXT>
