<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq-Turkey,0202 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With Turkey-Kurdish Rebels
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Iraq demands withdrawal of Turkish troops

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Baghdad has called on Turkey to withdraw
the 10,000 troops it sent into northern Iraq to battle Kurdish
rebels.
	   Turkey's claims that it is ``pursuing rebels who oppose Turkish
authorities does not give them the right to violate Iraqi ...
sovereignty,'' the Iraqi Foreign Ministry said in a statement on
Sunday.
	   Iraq demands that Turkey ``withdraw its invading forces ... and
stop their aggressive acts,'' the Foreign Ministry said in a
statement carried by the official Iraqi News Agency.
	   Turkey sent forces into northern Iraq on Friday.
	   Turkish Kurdish rebels fighting for autonomy in southeastern
Turkey carry out cross-border raids from camps in Iraq, Iran and
Syria.
	   Turkey has accused Syria of aiding the rebels and has indicated
that it is prepared to take military action to eradicate guerrilla
bases in Syria. Syria denies the charge.
	   Northern Iraq is controlled by Iraqi Kurds who oppose Baghdad.
	   The statement said that the ``the only guarantee for
establishing peace and stability in the region'' was to reestablish
Iraqi authority in the region.
</TEXT>
