<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0584 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ The chairman of the House Judiciary Committee
has said that the Senate does not now have the two-third majority
necessary to remove President Bill Clinton from office. Republican
Rep. Henry Hyde also said Sunday that he hopes to finish his
impeachment inquiry by year's end but won't accept Democratic
demands for limits on the investigation. Hyde's committee on Monday
was to take up a Republican resolution recommending an open-ended
inquiry into whether Clinton's behavior merits impeachment. The
Democrats will offer a separate version that would put a deadline
on the inquiry and limit it to the Monica Lewinsky affair, but it
is likely to be defeated. (US-CLINTON-CONGRESS)
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Reacting to the threat of a NATO
strike on Yugoslavia, Russia's defense and foreign ministers called
on President Slobodan Milosevic on Sunday, while Yugoslav generals
prepared to defend the country. Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and
Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev met with Milosevic and Milan
Milutinovic, president of Serbia, the dominant Yugoslav republic,
to discuss possible NATO intervention in Kosovo _ Serbia's southern
province _ to end seven months of bloodshed. (YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO)
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ Bickering broke out between the United States
and its rich allies even before the ink was dry on their action
plan for combating a widening economic crisis that has already
pushed a third of the world into recession. The disagreements
Sunday underscored that despite a major U.S. administration effort
to project unity and calm turbulent markets, the world's economic
powers still disagree strongly over just what they should be doing
to restore stability. The administration still played down the
disagreements and pushed ahead to demonstrate U.S. leadership by
assembling a multibillion-dollar bailout plan for Brazil, the
latest country threatened by panicked investors seeking to pull
their money out. (US-ECONOMIC CRISIS)
	   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) _ President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso was headed for re-election, according to exit polls,
indicating that Brazilians were giving him an unprecedented second
term to solve one of the country's worst economic crises in
decades. Exit polls conducted by the respected Ibope polling
institute showed Cardoso winning with 56 percent of the vote
compared to 29 percent for his closest rival, former labor leader
Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva of the Workers Party. The outcome was no
surprise. Cardoso, a 67-year-old sociologist, was the overwhelming
favorite in Sunday's national elections, getting a boost from
voters' fear of a deepening economic crisis. (BRAZIL-ELECTIONS)
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ As Turkey kept up warlike rhetoric against
Damascus, Egypt began shuttle diplomacy between the two neighbors
to avoid a military confrontation over Turkish Kurdish bases in
Syria. Turkish President Suleyman Demirel said Sunday that Turkey
had suffered for many years from Damascus' sheltering of the
autonomy-seeking rebels and needed to defend itself. Some 10,000
Turkish troops were deployed this week on the Turkish-Syrian
border, news reports said. Damascus denies that it is supporting
the rebels, who wage cross-border raids from camps in Iraq, Iran
and Syria. (TURKEY-KURDISH REBELS)
</TEXT>
