<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Latin American Briefs,,0495 </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items from Colombia and Mexico, Puerto Rico,
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) _ About 10,000 peasants forced from their
homes by fighting between leftist rebels and paramilitary groups
have agreed to return to their villages in rural northern Colombia
after receiving government assurances of protection, authorities
announced Sunday.
	   The refugees have spent the past three months camped in schools,
parks and sports halls in Barrancabermeja, a steamy oil refinery
city 180 miles north of the capital, Bogota.
	   The government said the first displaced peasants will begin
returning to their homes in Bolivar state on Tuesday.
	   President Andres Pastrana flew Sunday to Barrancabermeja, a
cauldron of political violence, to see off the refugees and to
reinforce his government's promise of military protection.
	   ___
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Hector Teran Teran, the second consecutive
opposition party leader to serve as governor of Baja California,
died of a heart attack Sunday. He was 67.
	   Family members said he died around 6:45 a.m. in the governor's
mansion in the state capital of Mexicali. He was the 10th governor
of Baja California, which borders California in the United States.
	   Unlike his predecessor, Ernesto Ruffo Appel, Teran was a quiet
but forceful politician who preferred backroom negotiations to
addressing crowds when it came to solving his state's many
problems.
	   Ruffo, a charismatic speaker, became Baja California's first
opposition governor in 1989 when his conservative National Action
Party won elections by a landslide despite fraud by the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, which has been in power
in Mexico for seven decades.
	   Teran, a lifelong member of National Action, was elected with 54
percent of the vote in 1995 for a six-year term. Before that, he
served in the state legislature and the federal congress, and as a
member of the party's national committee.
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ The Federal Emergency Management
Agency has received 62,000 damage claims in Puerto Rico since
Hurricane Georges hit Sept. 21, making it one of the costliest
disasters ever for the island.
	   About 53,500 claims had been filed by telephone by Sunday, and
another 8,500 were received in the first two days at application
centers around the island, said Ed Conly, a public affairs officer
for the agency.
	   At that rate, the total number of claims could eventually
eclipse those of Hurricane Hugo in 1989 or Hortense in 1996, Conly
said.
	   ``The impact of this event is huge,'' Conly said. ``This is
going to be a lot larger disaster than Hortense and it's going to
be a lot larger than Hugo.''
	   About 15,000 people remained in 219 hurricane shelters across
the island Sunday, most of them in schools. Civil Defense officials
were moving some of the shelters to vacant factories and warehouses
so that classes could resume Monday. 	   
</TEXT>
