<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japanese stocks fall, dollar higher in early trading
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japanese stocks fell in early trading Monday as
market sentiment remained bearish following last week's steep
declines. The U.S. dollar rose against the yen.
	   The benchmark Nikkei Stock Average shed 143.26 points, or 1.08
percent, to 13,080.43 points in the first 30 minutes of trading. On
Friday, the Nikkei posted a 26.57-point gain, or 0.20 percent.
	   The dollar bought 134.92 yen in early trading, up 0.14 yen from
late Friday in Tokyo but below its late New York level of 135.65
yen overnight.
	   Market players were waiting to see how soon the government would
take new steps to bolster Japan's economy and fragile financial
system.
	   They were also watching how other global markets would react to
the weekend meeting of financial officials from the world's major
economies.
	   ``Tokyo stocks are still looking downward, and the market hasn't
confirmed a downside support,'' said Masaaki Higashida, deputy
general manager at Nomura Securities Co.
	   Last week, the Nikkei index repeatedly set new 12-year closing
lows. Friday, the index briefly touched a low of 12,973.24, the
first time the average broke below 13,000 points since January
1986.
	   Traders said the market outlook would remain uncertain until
Japan's ruling and opposition parties agree on an injection of
public funds into the financial system.
	   At the Washington meeting, the Group of Seven industrialized
nations urged Japan to take ``swift and effective action'' to
strengthen its financial system, including the prompt enactment of
measures to support viable banks with public assistance.
	   The G-7 comprises the United States, Japan, Britain, Italy,
France, Canada and Germany.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was down 5.79 points, or 0.57 percent, to 1,008.23.
The TOPIX closed down 1.70 points, or 0.17 percent, on Friday.
	   The currency market was little affected by the G-7 finance
ministers' meeting, which issued no specific statements regarding
the yen-dollar rate, traders said.
	   The yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government
bond was unquoted in early morning. At Friday's close, the yield
stood at 0.715 percent and its price was 109.84 yen.
 &UR; (dj-km)
</TEXT>
