<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Croatia-Pope,0611 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pope pleads for postwar recovery, democracy
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS with new material.
 &UR; AP Photos SOL101,102,106 &QL; 
 &UR; By EUGENE BRCIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SPLIT, Croatia (AP) _ Pope John Paul II has called on Croats to
heal war wounds and build democracy, in a message at the end of a
three day visit that included the beatification of a controversial
World war cardinal.
	   ``After long years of dictatorship, and the terrible experiences
of violence, which the people of this region have undergone, it is
now necessary to make every effort to construct a democracy on the
moral values inscribed in the very nature of the human being,'' the
pope said before departure Sunday.
	   John Paul called on united Europe to support Croatia's bid to
join: ``On the path leading to the European joint home, no one
should be forgotten.''
	   But Croatia, he said, ``must show great patience, wisdom, a
willingness to make sacrifices and generous solidarity in order to
overcome definitively the present postwar phase and attain the
noble goals to which she aspires.''
	   Standing by the pope as he spoke was President Franjo Tudjman,
whose authoritarian rule is often cited by the western governments
in rejecting Croatia's admission to western institutions.
	   Tudjman said the pope ``reinforced us in faith, convinced us
that we can look with pride to our achievements and build up the
future with confidence.'' He also thanked John Paul for ``having
brought to Croatian people new messages of hope and forgiveness,
peace and community.''
	   Some 80 percent of Croatia's 4.7 million people are Roman
Catholics. They were overjoyed to see the pope again only four
years after his first visit. Hundreds of thousands attended pope's
public addresses; many others watched live TV coverage of the
events.
	   ``The pope's words heal and encourage,'' said Sanja Prpic, a
20-year-old student.
	   Earlier on Sunday, the pope held a Mass on Split's Adriatic
beach packed with up to 500,000 pilgrims.
	   He called on Croats to spur reconciliation among different
ethnic groups and to renew ``ethical and moral values undermined by
past totalitarianism and by the recent violence of war. It is an
urgent task, for without values there can be no true freedom or
democracy.''
	   The war erupted in 1991 when Croatian Serbs rebelled against the
country's independence from the former communist Yugoslavia. The
fighting only definitely ended in 1995, after the government
recaptured areas seized by rebels during the war.
	   The pope also addressed the most recent conflict, in the
Yugoslav southern province of Kosovo, urging the West to help
ending it.
	   ``Mutual respect, forgiveness and reconciliation'' were needed
to stop the violence, the pope said, expressing hopes that the
world powers would provide ``timely help'' to achieve those goals.
He made no mention of NATO planning for involvement in Kosovo.
	   The Vatican, one of the first countries to recognize Croatia's
independence, looks at the country as a Catholic bastion in the
Balkans, amid Orthodox Christians in Serbia and Muslims in Bosnia.
	   Orthodox clergymen and a Muslim delegation attended Sunday's
Mass, and the pope greeted them.
	   The frail 78-year-old pope appeared in generally good form
during a full-schedule visit, although he was visibly tired later
Sunday.
	   For most Croats, the highlight of the pope's visit was
Saturday's beatification, the last step before possible sainthood,
of the controversial World War II cardinal, Alojzije Stepinac.
	   Roman Catholics hail Stepinac as a martyr, but many Serbs and
Jews accuse him of sympathizing with the Nazis.
</TEXT>
