<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Malaysia's Anwar arrives in court wearing neck brace
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ALVIN UNG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Anwar Ibrahim, the reformer
politician who says police beat him in custody, arrived in court
Monday wearing a neck brace.
	   Police escorted Anwar to the High Court for arraignment on five
counts of corruption and five of illegal homosexual acts.
	   It was the first time the former deputy prime minister and
finance minister had been seen by his lawyers and wife since he was
charged in a lower court last Wednesday and pleaded innocent to all
charges.
	   After arraignment in the High Court, a trial date is to be set.
	   With the lower court's permission, Anwar had been admitted
Saturday night to University Hospital for medical check-ups after
he displayed a black eye, bruised arm and neck last week. He was
whisked away from the hospital Sunday after police barred his
family from seeing him.
	   Health Minister Chua Jui Meng said doctors would submit a report
of their findings to the court, but did not say when.
	   Anwar was once the heir apparent to Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad. But as Anwar's popularity increased along with his
challenges of the long-ruling Mahathir, he fell out of favor and
was arrested Sept. 20.
	   Anwar was arrested under the Internal Security Act, which allows
indefinite detention without charge and gives police the power to
prohibit prisoners from seeing their lawyers or families.
	   Anwar's wife, Azizah Ismail, called it a ``breach of human
rights'' that the lawyers had been denied access to their client.
	   Police have banned all gatherings connected with Anwar's reform
movement. And they forced two peaceful protests to disperse Sunday.
	   An eye surgeon who examined Anwar last week determined the
jailed politician had been ``assaulted'' but the injuries had not
caused permanent eye damage.
	   After he was fired Sept. 2, Anwar led thousands of people in
peaceful protests against Mahathir's 17-year rule.
	   The two top men in the government had clashed over economic
policy as Malaysia sank into recession. Mahathir has also accused
Anwar of plotting within the ruling party to supplant him before he
was ready to retire.
	   Mahathir initially suggested that his former protege had
inflicted the bruises on himself to win public sympathy. But as
global condemnation grew, Mahathir ordered an independent
investigation. 	   
</TEXT>
