w2520 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo     10-04 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo,0579 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian delegation meets Milosevic as NATO threatens strikes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS pvs, UPDATING with comments from foreign ministry
spokesman
 &UR; By MISHA SAVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ The pace of NATO preparations to
strike at Yugoslav targets may rise or fall depending on what the
U.N. secretary general tells the Security Council about the Kosovo
crisis on Monday.
	   U.N. chief Kofi Annan plans to report on whether Belgrade is
complying with demands to halt its assault on ethnic Albanians. If
not, Washington has said NATO will start air strikes within two
weeks.
	   Reacting to the threat of strikes, Russia's defense and foreign
ministers met President Slobodan Milosevic on Sunday, as his
generals prepared to defend the country.
	   Besides Milosevic, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and
Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev, the meeting was also attended by
Milan Milutinovic, president of Serbia, the dominant Yugoslav
republic, and Yugoslavia's top defense officials.
	   Russia is the Serbs' main ally, sharing bonds of religion, and
Slavic roots.
	   In Moscow, Itar-Tass carried a government statement repeating
opposition to NATO intervention in Kosovo without the sanction of
the U.N. Security Council, of which Russia is a veto-wielding
member.
	   A Yugoslav statement afterward said the leadership wanted the
Kosovo dispute solved peacefully. ``but in case we are attacked, we
shall defend our country with all means.''
	   The Yugoslav parliament scheduled a session for Monday to
discuss the crisis.
	   Preparing for any attack, Yugoslav generals put the nation's air
defense on high alert, even as Serbian authorities appeared ready
for compromise by installing an interim government in rebellious
Kosovo.
	   A Western diplomat also said that up to 120 Yugoslav army
armored vehicles, including tanks, have been pulled out of Kosovo
so far.
	   The Serb side reported no fighting Sunday, beyond two attacks of
civilian cars by Albanian ``terrorists'' about 40 kilometers (25
miles) south of Pristina, Kosovo's provincial capital, in which one
person was wounded.
	   But the Kosovo Information Center, which reports for the
Albanian side, said there was heavy fighting between government
forces and the guerrillas, 40 kilometers (25 miles) southwest of
Pristina.
	   Meanwhile, NATO countries continued preparations.
	   London's Sunday Telegraph reported Britain preparing troops and
armored units for Kosovo, to be deployed in a post-airstrike
peacekeeping role. The defense ministry refused to confirm or deny
the report but repeated Britain was ready to participate in a NATO
attack.
	   The Yugoslav government said Friday the fighting had ended and
blamed continuing violence on ethnic Albanian rebels.
	   Serbian police and the Yugoslav army have routed separatist
Kosovo Albanian rebels in a seven-month crackdown. The conflict has
killed hundreds _ most of them Albanian civilians _ and left upward
of 275,000 villagers refugees.
	   Ethnic Albanian political leaders rejected the interim council,
drawn up without any consultation with them, and one in which Serbs
outnumber majority Albanians.
	   Constituting the council, moribund since 1989, was part of a
last-ditch effort to show that Serbs intend to end the conflict.
	   Momentum for outside involvement has increased in the past week
amid revelations of massacres of ethnic Albanian civilians in the
forests of Kosovo. 	   
</TEXT>
