<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Malaysia's Anwar arrives in court wearing neck brace
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS; ADDS details &QL; 
 &UR; By ALVIN UNG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Anwar Ibrahim, the reformer
politician who says police beat him in custody, arrived in court
Monday wearing a neck brace after a weekend checkup in a hospital.
	   Anwar sat stiffly, staring straight ahead in the police vehicle
because of the neck brace, before officers escorted him into the
High Court for arraignment on five counts of corruption and five of
illegal homosexual acts.
	   It was the first time the former deputy prime minister and
finance minister had been seen by his lawyers and wife since he was
charged in a lower court last Tuesday and Wednesday and pleaded
innocent on all counts.
	   Anwar was once the heir apparent to Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad. But as Anwar's popularity increased along with his
challenges of Mahathir's 17-year-rule, he fell out of favor and was
fired Sept. 2.
	   After he conducted two weeks of rallies calling for Mahathir's
resignation and reform of the government, Anwar was arrested Sept.
20.
	   Anwar's wife, Azizah Ismail, called it a ``breach of human
rights'' that the lawyers had been denied access to their client.
	   After the High Court arraignment, a trial date is to be set.
	   Anwar had been admitted Saturday night to University Hospital
for medical checkups after he displayed a black eye, a bruised arm
and neck during his court appearances last week.
	   He said police had punched and slapped him in the face, knocking
him unconscious, and splitting his lip. He said he had been denied
medical attention for several days although he had trouble keeping
his balance and walking.
	   He was arrested under the Internal Security Act, which allows
indefinite detention without charge and gives police the power to
prohibit prisoners from seeing their lawyers or families.
	   Anwar was whisked away from the hospital Sunday after police
barricaded the stairwells and entryways, barring his family and
lawyers from seeing him. The hospital refused to give Anwar's wife,
a retired eye surgeon, a copy of his medical report.
	   Health Minister Chua Jui Meng said the doctors would submit a
report of their findings to the court, but did not say when.
	   Police have banned all gatherings connected with Anwar's reform
movement. And they forced two peaceful protests to disperse Sunday.
	   The two top men in the government had clashed over economic
policy as Malaysia sank into recession. Mahathir also accused Anwar
of plotting within the ruling party to supplant him before he was
ready to retire.
	   Mahathir initially suggested that his former protege had
inflicted the bruises on himself to win public sympathy. But as
global condemnation grew, Mahathir ordered an independent
investigation.
	   An eye surgeon who examined Anwar last week determined the
jailed politician had been ``assaulted'' but the injuries had not
caused permanent eye damage. 	   
</TEXT>
