<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Gas Shortage </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Victoria gets resupply of natural gas, industry to benefit first
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ANDREW TROUNSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) _ Victoria's hospital services,
nursing homes and bread and milk supplies were expected to return
to normal Monday, 10 days after a refinery explosion and fire cut
off the state's supply.
	   But businesses and households have been warned by the state's
gas distributor VENCorp not to turn on gas meters yet, or face
fines of Australian dollars 10,000 (U.S. dlrs 6,000).
	   Gas supplies for Victoria state's 1.4 million households were
expected to resume Thursday, VENCorp said.
	   Millions of state residents are taking cold showers and using
electric griddles and frying pans to cook their food. Many
industries have had to suspend operations; funeral homes have
turned to bottled gas in order to keep crematoriums operating.
	   Those people lucky enough to have electric hot water heaters are
finding out just how many friends they really have, as people
arrive with towels and soap to impose.
	   The state has opened sports stadiums and other public facilities
so people can shower there.
	   Gas producer Esso announced that gas started flowing from its
plant at Longford in southeastern Victoria, site of the Sept. 25
fire and explosion that killed two men and injured eight, on
Sunday.
	   The facility, which takes gas and oil from the offshore Bass
Strait fields, supplies 98 percent of Victoria's gas demand.
	   The incident led to 100,000 workers being sent home and millions
of dollars in lost production.
	   The Australian Industry Group estimates the crisis will cost 100
million Australian dollars (U.S. dlrs 58 million) each day it goes
on, which amounts to a third of the state's production.
	   ``A very small amount of gas is flowing from our plant into the
supply system,'' Esso's corporate and external affairs manager Ron
Webb said. ``It is essential that this message I am giving you is
understood _ that it is only a small amount of gas at this stage
and anybody thinking they can use this gas would be wrong.''
	   VENCorp spokesman David Guthrie-Jones said the company was
drawing up a list of large industries willing to begin taking gas
even if the early supply fluctuated.
	   He said some were unwilling because of the uncertainty of supply
but gas coming from New South Wales meant hospitals and nursing
homes should return to normal Monday.
	   ``Some critical industries such as bread and milk which use
small levels of gas are being able to progressively start using
gas,'' Guthrie-Jones said.
	   ``Otherwise, it is domestic on Thursday.''
	   Esso has so far been unable to determine the cause of the blaze
and explosions, which took two days to extinguish.
	   Victoria state is south of New South Wales, and Melbourne is
about 450 miles (720 km) southwest of Sydney. 	   
</TEXT>
