<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Chiapas Elections,0508 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Apathy in Chiapas state elections
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS, UPDATING with polls closing, First results expected by
early Monday. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos SCC101-104 &QL; 
 &UR; By TRINA KLEIST &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico (AP) _ Ignoring pleas from
government and church officials to vote, residents of the troubled
Mexican state of Chiapas stayed away from polling places.
	   Turnout Sunday among the state's 1.9 million registered voters
was estimated at 40 percent to 50 percent, said Francisco Gallardo
of Civic Alliance, an election monitoring group.
	   At stake in the elections were 40 state legislative seats and
the presidencies of 103 of the state's 111 counties.
	   First official results were expected early Monday.
	   Poverty and violence, widespread support for the anti-government
Zapatista rebels and the government's feeble response to
devastation caused by last month's floods have soured the
popularity of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party here.
Election results were expected to show the continued erosion of the
PRI's support.
	   The PRI, two other big opposition parties _ the conservative
National Action Party and the leftist Democratic Revolution Party _
and five other small political groups fielded a total of 477
candidates for the elections.
	   Despite exhortations from Bishop Arizmendi Esquivel of
Tapachula, who said Saturday it was the duty of all good Christians
to vote, few did so.
	   In La Hormiga, a community of about 10,000 near San Cristobal de
las Casas, only 20 people lined up to cast ballots when the polling
station opened.
	   Gabriel Samuel Gomez, 34, an unskilled worker, said he was going
to follow custom and vote for the PRI. But he added: ``What can you
do? They're all the same. They promise a lot but when they get into
power they forget about all of us poor people.''
	   The polls closed late Sunday without violence, though religious
disputes marred balloting in one county.
	   In San Juan Chamula, angry residents blocked 59 polling places
from opening to protest the jailing a year ago of five men.
	   The five were charged with murder in connection with a
long-standing dispute between ``traditionalist'' Catholics who
practice a syncretic form of their ancient Maya religion, and
neighbors who have converted to Protestantism.
	   More than 6,000 people milled in the central plaza under hastily
painted banners that read, ``There will be no vote until our
companions are freed,'' and ``Chamula united in one religion, we
are all traditional Catholics.''
	   Elections in the other eight counties near the Pacific Coast
were postponed until further notice because of flood damage.
	   The Zapatista National Liberation Front announced Saturday it
would not interfere with the voting. Hundreds have been killed in
sporadic clashes between rebel and government sympathizers since
the Zapatista rebellion began Jan. 1, 1994, to demand democracy and
better living conditions for the state's predominantly poor Indian
residents. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Mexico-Chiapas Elections; CT:i; 
