<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Sudan-A Tolerable Tragedy, 1st Add,0653 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANDELA CAMP: Barnaba asks.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ___
	   Jibril Hussein, at 15, is a newlywed at the camp.
	   His hands are still colored black by henna to mark his marriage
to his 14-year-old bride. To give them time together, his mother
and brother sleep outside on straw mats tossed in the dirt.
	   But their future together is bleak.
	   Jibril can neither read nor write. His father, a perfume seller,
died when he was 2. And he is a young man in another of the world's
militarized societies _ a candidate for war.
	   To Barnaba, the Mandela camp is sorrow, a life lost. To Jibril,
it is fear, a life to dread.
	   He is a Muslim from the drought-stricken west, and thus escapes
government efforts to convert the camp's Christians and animists
from the south. Residents say that some youths are forced to
memorize the Koran and that government aid agencies favor Muslims.
	   But Jibril fears the government's reach, just the same.
	   As part of a war that the government portrays as a religious
crusade, all young men must undergo two months of military
training. For the men in the camps, that is followed by 18 months
of service in the national militia, with likely duty in the south.
	   Such service is vastly unpopular. In the camps, where young men
are press-ganged in times of crisis, it is unpredictable, too.
	   ``They call you a holy warrior and send you to the south,''
Jibril says. ``But I don't want to go.''
	   Without proof of service, he cannot get a job other than day
labor. His passport will be invalid, a visa to work abroad
impossible. In a way, Jibril will live as a fugitive, dodging the
draft until he is 40 and perpetuating a cycle of idleness.
	   He doesn't care.
	   ``I could lose my leg or both legs. Or my arms. Is that a
future?'' he asks. ``I could die. Is that a future? That won't do,
that won't do at all. I don't want to die.''
	   ___
	   Michael Ashanding is the Mandela camp's everyman.
	   Like others here, he was a farmer in southern Sudan, raising the
corn, sorghum and cassava that grow so well in the reddish-brown
soil of the savanna.
	   But there are no farms near the camps around Khartoum. There's
no land to cultivate.
	   ``If there's work, I work,'' Michael says in his tukal of
cardboard bound by twine. ``If there's no work, I sit.''
	   He fled fighting in Bahr el-Ghazal province in the south in
1995. The journey, in driving rains, lasted five days.
	   He brought his wife and three children _ ``I didn't bring
anything else.'' He has had another child since.
	   Ensuring another generation of poverty, his children will not
learn to farm like their father, and they will not go to school to
pick up the skills that might secure them a job in the city.
	   Like their father, they will survive doing day labor _ digging
trenches for the phone company, making bricks along the Blue Nile,
picking cotton in fields to the south.
	   They will likely stay in the Mandela camp.
	   For them, the camp is misery that begets misery.
	   In every tragedy _ be it at Mandela or elsewhere _ those who
must endure it consider it their apocalypse, their end of the
world. To them, it is as cataclysmic as any disaster, anywhere.
	   Michael foresees a life without hope, without meaning _ for
either him or his children. He wants to leave. But to where?
	   His home in Wau is another apocalypse, where 80 people were
dying every day in August from famine.
	   The scenes were chilling: A woman grabbed a bowMichael, though, anythijg0ks preferable to the camp.
	   Even Wau.
	   ``In Wau, I can farm. I can eat what I grow, beans, anything.
Not like here,'' he says. ``Here, if I don't make money, I don't
eat.''
	   ``If God gave me the money, I'd go,'' he says.
</TEXT>
