<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NKorea-Missile </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
North Korea confirms plans to continue rocket test-firing
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ North Korea reiterated its position
Monday that it will continue to test-fire multi-stage rockets,
despite protests by the United States, Japan and other neighboring
countries.
	   North Korea took the stand, claiming that its Aug. 31 firing of
a rocket was an attempt to put an artificial satellite into orbit
and didn't pose any threat to other countries.
	   ``We make it clear once more that we will launch another
artificial satellite when we think it necessary, no matter what
anyone may say. This is our inviolable sovereign right,'' Minju
Joson newspaper, the North's government organ, said in an article.
	   The article was carried by Korean Central News Agency, the
North's official foreign news outlet.
	   The article charged that the United States and Japan are using
the North's Aug. 31 rocket-firing as an excuse to perfect their
``theater missile defense system.''
	   U.S. officials initially believed that what North Korea fired on
Aug. 31 was a two-stage missile which flew over Japan and landed in
the Pacific Ocean.
	   They later concluded that it was a three-stage ballistic rocket
with a range of over 2,000 kilometers (1,250 miles), which failed
to put an object into orbit.
	   Whether a missile or satellite, it showed a worrisome increase
in North Korea's missile capability, officials of the United
States, Japan and South Korea said.
	   The North's missile, believed to be Taepo Dong 1, is a variant
of Soviet-developed Scud missiles. It puts any targets in South
Korea and Japan within its range. 	   
</TEXT>
