w2541 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-Spain-EuropeanThr     10-04 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Spain-European Threshold,0925 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Desperate Africans brave treacherous strait seeking new life
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos NY307-310, Graphic GIBRALTAR &QL; 
 &UR; By KERNAN TURNER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CEUTA, Spain (AP) _ The Rock of Gibraltar looms over everything,
a sentinel guarding Europe. On dark, moonless nights, desperate
Africans jam into smugglers' boats and try to sneak across the
narrow waters that separate poverty from presumed paradise.
	   But the Strait of Gibraltar is a treacherous place. Its strong
currents and changeable weather mean the sea can be flat as a dish
one moment and a churning maelstrom the next.
	   The Spanish government knows of 13 of the small wooden boats
that have sunk so far this year, drowning 45 would-be immigrants.
	   But volunteers who work closely with illegal immigrants say many
accidents go undetected. Based on information from relatives and
other immigrants, they estimate close to 1,000 people have perished
this year.
	   In the worst incident ever, 38 people drowned one night in June,
apparently when their smugglers' ``patera'' was intentionally
rammed by another boat. The open boats, powered by outboard motor
and built for a dozen passengers, usually are loaded with 20 to 30
immigrants.
	   Still, the strait remains a busy threshold for impoverished
Africans who are looking for a better life in Europe.
	   Under pressure from the rest of Europe, Spain only recently
began cracking down on the flow. The Civil Guard says 8,854 illegal
immigrants were detained in the first eight months of this year,
compared to 12,132 for all of 1997.
	   Preventive measures include elaborate fences that seal off Ceuta
and Melilla, two Spanish enclaves on the North African coast. A new
Civil Guard Maritime Service patrols the strait at night, searching
with radar for smugglers' boats.
	   Europe's concern is that once illegal immigrants reach Spanish
soil, not much stands in their way to crossing passport-free
borders into France and beyond to other European Union countries.
	   Spain had welcomed outsiders for years to do tough jobs spurned
by Spaniards, especially on the farms that provide much of the
fruit and vegetables consumed in northern Europe.
	   But the attitude changed in 1992, after legislation was enacted
to meet Spain's obligations under an EU treaty that allows
passport-free travel within the economic bloc but requires members
to restrict immigration from outside the community.
	   Despite Spain's crackdown, an estimated 20,000 people have
slipped into the country this year and 15,000 more made it to other
European nations, according to the Association of Moroccan
Immigrant Workers of Spain, which claims 14,000 members.
	   In all, 60,000 to 150,000 foreigners are thought to be living
illegally in Spain, which has a population of 40 million.
	   Government policy may have changed, but Spaniards generally
sympathize with the immigrants. Humanitarian groups offer food,
shelter and clothing to new arrivals.
	   ``We say hunger travels by itself; it doesn't need a passport.
When one is hungry, one travels,'' said Julio Martinez Silvida, who
heads the largest private support group in the southern region of
Andalucia.
	   Speaking to reporters at his office in the port of Algeciras as
immigrant children arrived for lessons denied them at Spanish
schools, Martinez said such people are fleeing 50 percent
unemployment in Morocco and wars, famine and political upheaval
elsewhere in Africa.
	   ``The farms exist because of the immigrants,'' he said,
estimating 60 percent find jobs in agriculture.
	   The aid groups advocate making it easier for Africans to get
temporary work permits.
	   In addition to crowding into ``pateras'' for runs across the
strait, would-be immigrants also sneak across hidden aboard
container ships and ferry boats from Ceuta, opposite Gibraltar, and
Melilla, close to Morocco's border with Algeria. They each pay
around 150,000 pesetas (dlrs 1,000) for the trip.
	   Africans hitch rides or take buses across the Sahara to reach
Morocco and then climb over or cut through the fences or bribe
their way across the border into Ceuta and Melilla. They hope that
once they are on Spanish territory to get temporary political
asylum or work permits.
	   The 2.5-meter-high (8-foot-high) border walls consist of
parallel wire-mesh fences separated by a dirt lane and bordered by
razor-barbed concertina wire coiled along the ground. Electronic
sensors and floodlights are being installed.
	   Critics of the effort to keep out poor immigrants say there is
no barrier that can stop people who are fleeing hunger and war.
Even Civil Guard sentries belittle the fence, showing foreign
journalists on a recent visit how easy it is to cut or climb.
	   Moroccans who are caught in the Spanish enclaves face immediate
deportation. People from other African countries spend months in
squalid camps. A lucky few get temporary work permits, but most are
sent home.
	   About 500 Africans from 22 nations are penned up at the
Calamocarro camp on a hillside on the edge of Ceuta, where they
share a few tents and shanties amid the stench of smoke and
garbage. Volunteers provide food, language classes and basic
medical care.
	   Kendy Anshem, a 29-year-old detainee who spent months trekking
here from Liberia in West Africa, scoffs at Europe's worries about
illegal immigrants.
	   ``How many thousands of immigrants go into the United States
every year?'' he asked. ``And the Europeans are worried about a few
hundred of us?''
</TEXT>
