US: IMF - The policy-setting committee for the International
Monetary Fund said the global economic outlook has ``worsened
considerably'', but ended a day of discussions on the subject by
papering over disagreements on how to halt the widening financial
crisis. APTN has a wrap of Sunday's developments in Washington.
(FIRST RUN EXPECTED 0300 EUROPE EARLY)
----
KOSOVO: WRAP - While NATO awaits Secretary-General Kofi Annan's
report on Kosovo to determine whether to take military action in the
southern Serb province, a human rights organization has accused both
the Yugoslav government and the ethnic Albanian rebels of committing
atrocities in seven months of conflict. APTN has footage of a
village burnt down by Serb forces, comment from Human Rights Watch,
footage of ethnic Albanian refugees and of Serb military vehicles
withdrawing. (FIRST RUN 0300 EUROPE EARLY)
----
BRAZIL: RESULT - Preliminary results indicate that President
Fernando Henrique Cardoso has won just enough votes to avoid a
run-off. APTN's election result coverage includes footage of Cardoso
returning to Brasilia, plus party headquarters monitoring the
results. (F-L-A-S-H EXPECTED BEFORE 0200)
----
JAPAN: MARKETS - Tokyo stocks weakened in early morning trade after
the Group of Seven (G7) industrialized nations urged Japan over the
weekend to boost its economy and clean up its debt-ridden banking
sector. (FIRST RUN 0300 EUROPE EARLY)
----
MALAYSIA: ANWAR - Former deputy prime minister Anwar Ibrahim, who
says police beat him in custody, has appeared back in the Kuala
Lumpur High Court which is expected to set a date for his trial on
charges of corruption and illegal homosexual acts. APTN has coverage
of the arrival of Anwar - who was wearing a neck brace after
spending the weekend in hospital. (F-L-A-S-H DUE BEFORE 0500)
