<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Obit-Teran,0530 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Baja California Gov. Teran dead from apparent heart attack
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with more details and INCORPORATES US-Obit-Teran &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Hector Teran Teran, the second consecutive
opposition party leader to serve as governor of Baja California,
has died of a heart attack. He was 67.
	   Family members said he died of a sudden seizure at around 6:45
a.m. Sunday in the governor's mansion in the state capital of
Mexicali. He was the 10th governor of Baja California, which
borders with California in the United States.
	   Unlike his predecessor Ernesto Ruffo Appel, Teran was a quiet
but forceful politician who preferred backroom negotiation in
solving his state's many problems to addressing crowds.
	   Ruffo, a charismatic speaker, became Baja California's first
opposition governor in 1989 when his conservative National Action
Party won elections by a landslide despite fraud by the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, which has been in power
in Mexico for seven decades.
	   Teran, a lifelong member of National Action, was elected with 54
percent of the vote in 1995 for a six-year term. Before that, he
served in the state legislature and the federal congress and as a
member of the party's national committee.
	   During his election campaign, Teran stressed the need for
greater public participation in government decisions, promising to
reduce the governor's authority and provide greater autonomy for
the state's four big cities.
	   Both Ruffo and Teran were plagued by big problems, from having
to battle PRI campaigns to discredit their administrations to
shootings and killings by drug gangs.
	   Baja California, with more than 2 million people, has long been
the site of a turf war among Pacific coast drug cartels for the
lucrative illicit market across the border in the United States.
	   The latest outbreak of violence was a massacre on Sept. 17 near
the fishing and tourist port of Ensenada, when masked gunmen _
believed to be linked to a drug gang _ dragged three related
families out of their beds at night.
	   The gunmen lined the people against a wall, mowed them down with
assault rifles and fled. Nineteen people died. The victims were
suspected of being linked to the drug trade.
	   Even so, the state remains one of the richest in Mexico and has
one of its lowest unemployment rates, partly due to tourism from
neighboring California, as well as its many ``maquiladora'' or
in-bond border industries, and the money sent back to relatives by
migrant workers in the United States.
	   Baja California also has one of the highest concentration of
urban residents in the nation.
	   Teran was born in 1931 in Moctezuma, in neighboring Sonora
state, the son of a small-town grocer. He studied business
administration at Monterrey's Technological Institute in Nuevo Leon
state, and went into business for a while before turning to
politics.
	   He is survived by his wife Alma Corella Gilsamaniego and their
four children _ Celia, Hector, Alfredo and Armando.
	   Funeral services will be held Monday.
	   The family has requested that instead of flowers the money be
donated to charities.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Mexico-Obit-Teran; CT:i; 
