<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Brazil-Elections, 1st Ld-Writethru,0560 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With election sewn up, Brazil's Cardoso must tackle economy
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS and UPDATES throughout with latest results. No pick
up &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos SAO106,108-110,112; BSB101-102,108; RIO102 &QL; 
 &UR; By MICHAEL ASTOR &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) _ With exit polls and initial
returns pointing to a landslide victory, the election was a breeze
for incumbent President Fernando Henrique Cardoso. Now comes the
hard part, analysts say.
	   Cardoso managed to hold the rudder firm long enough to become
the first Brazilian president ever re-elected, even after fallout
from Russia's debt default which wiped out a good chunk of the
stock market's value and forced interest rates to near 50 percent a
month.
	   Now many economists predict a recession in 1999, deteriorating
unemployment and pressure on the government to raise taxes, all
which is likely to erode the president's popularity.
	   According to exit polls conducted by the respected Ibope polling
institute, Cardoso should win with 56 percent of the vote compared
to 29 percent for his closest rival, Worker's Party candidate Luis
Inacio ``Lula'' da Silva. Ibope questioned 54,000 voters
nationwide.
	   Official election results with 35.3 percent of the vote counted
had Cardoso with 50.9 percent and Lula with 34.3 percent.
	   ``It's very good for Brazil that the president has received this
mandate from the Brazilian people and that he can now do what is
needed to protect the real (the local currency) and the Brazilian
people,'' Foreign Minister Luis Felipe Lampreia told reporters in
Brasilia.
	   The outcome was not a surprise to the 106 million voters who
went to the polls Sunday to choose a president, 27 governors, all
513 federal deputies, a third of the 81-seat Senate and 1,405 state
legislators. Voting is mandatory for Brazilians between the ages of
18 and 70.
	   Cardoso's popularity stems largely from the success of the Real
Plan, which dropped inflation from around 2,400 percent a year to
near zero now. The country's deepening financial woes, brought on
by investors bailing out of Brazil and other emerging markets,
failed to dissuade the electorate.
	   ``In voting for Cardoso, the electorate demonstrated the
importance it attached to stability,'' said Joaquim Eloy de Toledo,
an economist with the University of Sao Paulo. ``The electorate
approved his clear message that he would do all in his power to
guarantee the survival of the Real Plan and the stability it
brought to prices.''
	   But ensuring that stability now looks like a bitter pill to
swallow.
	   Analysts say that while the massive popular support may give the
president a honeymoon period which will help him push through
desperately needed fiscal reforms, that support will erode as the
effects of harsh economic measures sink in.
	   Cardoso has pledged strong measures to control a ballooning
budget deficit of more than dlrs 60 billion. His success hinges
largely on the cooperation of a Congress that knows little party
discipline and have managed to delay essential reforms through out
most of the president's first term.
	   ``The voters have accepted his putting economic stability before
tackling the serious social problems facing the country,'' Carlos
Esteban Martins, a political scientist at the University of Sao
Paulo. 	   
</TEXT>
