<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japanese stocks fall, dollar lower in morning trading
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with late-morning stock, dollar and bond rates

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japanese stocks fell sharply in morning trading
Monday, dropping below the psychologically important 13,000 mark,
as investors remained skeptical about whether Japan will be able to
stabilize its ailing economy and financial system.
	   The benchmark Nikkei Stock Average shed 247.27 points, or 1.87
percent, to close the morning trading session at 12,976.42. On
Friday, the Nikkei posted a 26.57-point gain, or 0.20 percent.
	   The dollar bought 134.55 yen at midmorning, down 0.22 yen from
late Friday in Tokyo and below its level late Friday in New York of
135.65 yen.
	   At a meeting in Washington, the Group of Seven industrialized
nations urged Japan to take ``swift and effective action'' to
strengthen its financial system, including the prompt enactment of
measures to support viable banks with public assistance.
	   But traders and investors in Tokyo said they doubted the
government would implement effective measures soon.
	   ``Tokyo stocks are still looking downward, and the market hasn't
confirmed a downside support,'' said Masaaki Higashida, deputy
general manager at Nomura Securities Co.
	   Last week, the Nikkei index repeatedly set new 12-year closing
lows. Friday, the index briefly touched a low of 12,973.24, the
first time the average broke below 13,000 points since January
1986.
	   Traders said the market outlook would remain uncertain until
Japan's ruling and opposition parties agree on how to strengthen
the ailing financial system.
	   The G-7 comprises the United States, Japan, Britain, Italy,
France, Canada and Germany.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section fell 12.30 points, or 1.21 percent, to 1,001.72. The
TOPIX closed down 1.70 points, or 0.17 percent, on Friday.
	   The currency market was little affected by the G-7 finance
ministers' meeting, which issued no specific statements regarding
the yen-dollar rate, traders said.
	   The dollar weakened against the yen as overseas players dumped
the U.S. currency, dealers said. The decline came despite the sharp
fall in Japanese share prices, which often weakens the yen.
	   The dollar's failure to break above a technical barrier at
around 135.50 yen triggered a wave of selling, dealers said.
	   The benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government bond was
unquoted in morning trading. At Friday's close, the yield stood at
0.715 percent and its price was 109.84 yen.
 &UR; (dj-km-tz) 	   
</TEXT>
