<HEADER>
w2604 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Malaysia-Politics 2ndLd-Writethru   10-04 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Politics, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Malaysia's Anwar arrives in court with neck brace
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS; INSERTS 2nd graf with Anwar quote &QL; 
 &UR; By ALVIN UNG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Reform politician Anwar Ibrahim,
who says police beat him in custody, wore a neck brace during his
arraignment Monday as policemen surrounded him to block any
conversation with his lawyers or family.
	   ``I've been treated worse than any other criminal,'' Anwar told
the court.
	   High Court Judge Augustine Paul issued a gag order against all
public statements about Anwar's guilt or innocence and said the
trial would be conducted in English ``so that justice can be seen
to be done.''
	   ``The judge isn't only me but millions of others,'' said Paul,
noting international press attention that has brought expressions
of concern about the former deputy prime minister's treatment from
the United Nations, the World Bank, and government leaders from the
Philippines, the United States, Canada, Australia and Indonesia.
	   However, Paul rejected a request by Anwar's attorneys that they
be allowed to consult with him during the proceedings. Two were
allowed to meet him privately in a lockup during a court break
after the reading of the charges.
	   Anwar's wife, Azizah Ismail, said Sunday it was a ``breach of
human rights'' that lawyers have been prohibited from seeing their
client except when he is brought to court.
	   Anwar patted his mother's cheek as he stepped into the dock, but
his efforts to chat with her and his wife, sitting behind him, were
blocked by a barricade of five plain-clothed policemen.
	   The prosecution said that as a prisoner under the Internal
Security Act, Anwar is not entitled to visitors. He is being tried
on charges under the criminal code on five counts of corruption and
five of illegal homosexual acts.
	   He pleaded innocent to the charges in two lower court hearings
last week, when he appeared with a black eye, bruised neck and
arms, saying police had beat him until he was unconscious on the
night he was arrested, Sept. 20.
	   The prosecution also asked the judge to keep secret a report by
four government doctors who examined Anwar during a weekend
hospital stay until police complete their investigation of how he
was injured.
	   Anwar was once the heir apparent to Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad. But as his popularity increased along with his challenges
of Mahathir's 17-year-rule and disagreements over economic policy,
he fell out of favor and was fired Sept. 2 as finance minister and
deputy prime minister.
	   After he conducted two weeks of rallies calling for Mahathir's
resignation and reform of the government, Anwar was arrested under
the Internal Security Act, which allows indefinite detention
without charge and restricts other rights.
	   While Anwar has been held incommunicado and his wife has been
banned by police from addressing the public, the government and
ruling party has embarked on an information campaign, sending
Cabinet ministers and party leaders around the country to explain
why Mahathir fired him.
	   Judge Paul's gag order, issued at the request of the defense,
could stop that.
	   ``It isn't appropriate for anyone to comment on the guilt or
innocence of Anwar either directly or indirectly,'' Paul said. ``To
ensure a fair trial, from today onwards such statements should
cease to be made.''
	   In a clear reference to Mahathir, who described in detail the
sexual allegations against Anwar at a news conference and said he
is sure to be convicted, Anwar's chief lawyer, Raja Aziz Addruse
asked the judge to act.
	   ``A number of persons of high office have seen fit to express
publicly and in no uncertain terms their views that my client is
already guilty of the offenses,'' Raja Aziz said.
	   ``Because of the authoritative position these persons hold or
have held, their views are bound to influence the trial of the
accused and to adversely affect him.''
	   Police have banned all gatherings connected with Anwar's reform
movement. And they forced two peaceful protests to disperse Sunday.
</TEXT>
