<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-New Zealand-Bungy Jump </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Plunky plungee practices world record bungy jump in secret
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Jump due by 1200 GMT, lead to follow. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos expected &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) _ A world record bungy-jump attempt
goes ahead Monday evening, with the plunky plungee diving from the
Sky Tower casino, the city's highest building, 630 feet (192
meters) toward the street.
	   The jump is actually a formality for the media -- because A.J.
Hackett, who is credited with popularizing the ``extreme sport''
pastime of diving from heights with elastic bands tied to the
ankles, has already done it.
	   In fact, Hackett has done two Sky Tower leaps -- during an early
morning Saturday practice session.
	   Monday night's leap is being described as historic, but a
handful of spectators watched the practice jumps about 6 a.m.
Saturday.
	   In constant rain, and with cloud at times lower than the launch
platform, Hackett made two perfect jumps from 630 feet (192 meters)
above the street. He started bouncing when he was about 200 feet
(60 meters) from the ground.
	   Television New Zealand is dedicating 30 minutes of prime-time
television to the jump and a website has been set up to broadcast
it live on the Internet.
	   Promoter Neil Green said there was no intention to fool people
about Monday night's jump, which would still be a world record --
as Hackett would be going closer to the ground than in practice.
	   ``Obviously we didn't want to spoil it -- and the whole idea of
it was to create that sense of excitement.''
	   Green said there was no pretense tonight's jump was the first as
there was no way Hackett would attempt it without doing one or two
jumps first.
	   ``There's just too much danger in this one not to get it
right.''
	   Bungy jumping is a modernization of a traditional Vanuatu tribal
test of courage in which villagers plunge head-first from high
platforms with vines tied to their ankles to break their fall at
the last moment -- they hope.
	   pjs
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-New Zealand-Bungy Jump; CT:i; 
(REG:ASIA;)
